INSERT INTO verses (book_id, chapter, verse, text, version) VALUES
(27, 18, 3, 'When I raise my battle flag on the mountain, let all the world take notice. When I blow the trumpet, listen!', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 4, 'For the LORD has told me this: "I will watch quietly from my dwelling place--as quietly as the heat rises on a summer day, or as the dew forms on an autumn morning during the harvest."', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 5, 'Even before you begin your attack, while your plans are ripening like grapes, the LORD will cut you off as though with pruning shears. He will snip your spreading branches.', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 6, 'Your mighty army will be left dead in the fields for the mountain birds and wild animals to eat. The vultures will tear at corpses all summer. The wild animals will gnaw at bones all winter.', 'NLT'),
(27, 18, 7, 'But the time will come when the LORD Almighty will receive gifts from this land divided by rivers, from this tall, smooth-skinned people, who are feared far and wide for their conquests and destruction. They will bring the gifts to the LORD Almighty in Jerusalem, the place where his name dwells.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 1, 'This message came to me concerning Egypt: Look! The LORD is advancing against Egypt, riding on a swift cloud. The idols of Egypt tremble. The hearts of the Egyptians melt with fear.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 2, '"I will make the Egyptians fight against each other--brother against brother, neighbor against neighbor, city against city, province against province.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 3, 'The Egyptians will lose heart, and I will confuse their plans. They will plead with their idols for wisdom. They will call on spirits, mediums, and psychics to show them which way to turn.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 4, 'I will hand Egypt over to a hard, cruel master, to a fierce king," says the Lord, the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 5, 'The waters of the Nile will fail to rise and flood the fields. The riverbed will be parched and dry.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 6, 'The canals of the Nile will dry up, and the streams of Egypt will become foul with rotting reeds and rushes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 7, 'All the greenery along the riverbank will wither and blow away. All the crops will dry up, and everything will die.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 8, 'The fishermen will weep for lack of work. Those who fish with hooks and those who use nets will all be unemployed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 9, 'The weavers will have no flax or cotton, for the crops will fail.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 10, 'The weavers and all the workers will be sick at heart.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 11, 'What fools are the counselors of Zoan! Their best counsel to the king of Egypt is stupid and wrong. Will they still boast of their wisdom? Will they dare tell Pharaoh about their long line of wise ancestors?', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 12, 'What has happened to your wise counselors, Pharaoh? If they are so wise, let them tell you what the LORD Almighty is going to do to Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 13, 'The wise men from Zoan are fools, and those from Memphis are deluded. The leaders of Egypt have ruined the land with their foolish counsel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 14, 'The LORD has sent a spirit of foolishness on them, so all their suggestions are wrong. They cause the land of Egypt to stagger like a sick drunkard.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 15, 'Nobody in Egypt, whether rich or poor, important or unknown, can offer any help.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 16, 'In that day the Egyptians will be as weak as women. They will cower in fear beneath the upraised fist of the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 17, 'Just to speak the name of Israel will strike deep terror in their hearts, for the LORD Almighty has laid out his plans against them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 18, 'In that day five of Egypt''s cities will follow the LORD Almighty. They will even begin to speak the Hebrew language. One of these will be Heliopolis, the City of the Sun.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 19, 'In that day there will be an altar to the LORD in the heart of Egypt, and there will be a monument to the LORD at its border.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 20, 'It will be a sign and a witness to the LORD Almighty in the land of Egypt. When the people cry to the LORD for help against those who oppress them, he will send them a savior who will rescue them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 21, 'In that day the LORD will make himself known to the Egyptians. Yes, they will know the LORD and will give their sacrifices and offerings to him. They will make promises to the LORD and keep them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 22, 'The LORD will strike Egypt in a way that will bring healing. For the Egyptians will turn to the LORD, and he will listen to their pleas and heal them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 23, 'In that day Egypt and Assyria will be connected by a highway. The Egyptians and Assyrians will move freely between their lands, and they will worship the same God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 24, 'And Israel will be their ally. The three will be together, and Israel will be a blessing to them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 19, 25, 'For the LORD Almighty will say, "Blessed be Egypt, my people. Blessed be Assyria, the land I have made. Blessed be Israel, my special possession!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 1, 'In the year when King Sargon of Assyria captured the Philistine city of Ashdod,', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 2, 'the LORD told Isaiah son of Amoz, "Take off all your clothes, including your sandals." Isaiah did as he was told and walked around naked and barefoot.', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 3, 'Then the LORD said, "My servant Isaiah has been walking around naked and barefoot for the last three years. This is a sign--a symbol of the terrible troubles I will bring upon Egypt and Ethiopia.', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 4, 'For the king of Assyria will take away the Egyptians and Ethiopians as prisoners. He will make them walk naked and barefoot, both young and old, their buttocks uncovered, to the shame of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 5, 'How dismayed will be the Philistines, who counted on the power of Ethiopia and boasted of their allies in Egypt!', 'NLT'),
(27, 20, 6, 'They will say, `If this can happen to Egypt, what chance do we have? For we counted on Egypt to protect us from the king of Assyria.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 1, 'This message came to me concerning the land of Babylonia: Disaster is roaring down on you from the desert, like a whirlwind sweeping in from the Negev.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 2, 'I see an awesome vision: I see you plundered and destroyed. Go ahead, you Elamites and Medes, take part in the siege. Babylon will fall, and the groaning of all the nations she enslaved will end.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 3, 'My stomach aches and burns with pain. Sharp pangs of horror are upon me, like the pangs of a woman giving birth. I grow faint when I hear what God is planning; I am blinded with dismay.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 4, 'My mind reels; my heart races. The sleep I once enjoyed at night is now a faint memory. I lie awake, trembling.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 5, 'Look! They are preparing a great feast. They are spreading rugs for people to sit on. Everyone is eating and drinking. Quick! Grab your shields and prepare for battle! You are being attacked!', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 6, 'Meanwhile, the Lord said to me, "Put a watchman on the city wall to shout out what he sees.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 7, 'Tell him to sound the alert when he sees chariots drawn by horses and warriors mounted on donkeys and camels."', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 8, 'Then the watchman called out, "Day after day I have stood on the watchtower, my lord. Night after night I have remained at my post.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 9, 'Now at last--look! Here come the chariots and warriors!" Then the watchman said, "Babylon is fallen! All the idols of Babylon lie broken on the ground!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 10, 'O my people, threshed and winnowed, I have told you everything the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, has said.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 11, 'This message came to me concerning Edom: Someone from Edom keeps calling to me, "Watchman, how much longer until morning? When will the night be over?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 12, 'The watchman replies, "Morning is coming, but night will soon follow. If you wish to ask again, then come back and ask."', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 13, 'This message came to me concerning Arabia: O caravans from Dedan, hide in the deserts of Arabia.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 14, 'O people of Tema, bring food and water to these weary refugees.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 15, 'They have fled from drawn swords and sharp arrows and the terrors of war.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 16, '"But within a year," says the Lord, "all the glory of Kedar will come to an end.', 'NLT'),
(27, 21, 17, 'Only a few of its courageous archers will survive. I, the LORD, the God of Israel, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 1, 'This message came to me concerning Jerusalem: What is happening? Why is everyone running to the rooftops?', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 2, 'The whole city is in a terrible uproar. What do I see in this reveling city? Bodies are lying everywhere, killed by famine and disease.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 3, 'All your leaders flee. They surrender without resistance. The people try to slip away, but they are captured, too.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 4, 'Leave me alone to weep; do not try to comfort me. Let me cry for my people as I watch them being destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 5, 'Oh, what a day of crushing trouble! What a day of confusion and terror the Lord, the LORD Almighty, has brought upon the Valley of Vision! The walls of Jerusalem have been broken, and cries of death echo from the mountainsides.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 6, 'Elamites are the archers; Arameans drive the chariots. The men of Kir hold up the shields.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 7, 'They fill your beautiful valleys and crowd against your gates.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 8, 'Judah''s defenses have been stripped away. You run to the armory for your weapons.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 9, 'You inspect the walls of Jerusalem to see what needs to be repaired. You store up water in the lower pool.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 10, 'You check the houses and tear some down to get stone to fix the walls.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 11, 'Between the city walls, you build a reservoir for water from the old pool. But all your feverish plans are to no avail because you never ask God for help. He is the one who planned this long ago.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 12, 'The Lord, the LORD Almighty, called you to weep and mourn. He told you to shave your heads in sorrow for your sins and to wear clothes of sackcloth to show your remorse.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 13, 'But instead, you dance and play; you slaughter sacrificial animals, feast on meat, and drink wine. "Let''s eat, drink, and be merry," you say. "What''s the difference, for tomorrow we die."', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 14, 'The LORD Almighty has revealed to me that this sin will never be forgiven you until the day you die. That is the judgment of the Lord, the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 15, 'Furthermore, the Lord, the LORD Almighty, told me to confront Shebna, the palace administrator, and to give him this message:', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 16, '"Who do you think you are, building a beautiful tomb for yourself in the rock?', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 17, 'For the LORD is about to seize you and hurl you away. He is going to send you into captivity, you strong man!', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 18, 'He will crumple you up into a ball and toss you away into a distant, barren land. There you will die, and there your glorious chariots will remain, broken and useless. You are a disgrace to your master.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 19, '"Yes, I will drive you out of office," says the LORD. "I will pull you down from your high position.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 20, 'And then I will call my servant Eliakim son of Hilkiah to replace you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 21, 'He will have your royal robes, your title, and your authority. And he will be a father to the people of Jerusalem and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 22, 'I will give him the key to the house of David--the highest position in the royal court. He will open doors, and no one will be able to shut them; he will close doors, and no one will be able to open them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 23, 'He will bring honor to his family name, for I will drive him firmly in place like a tent stake.', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 24, 'He will be loaded down with responsibility, and he will bring honor to even the lowliest members of his family."', 'NLT'),
(27, 22, 25, 'The LORD Almighty says: "When that time comes, I will pull out the stake that seemed so firm. It will come out and fall to the ground. Everything it supports will fall with it. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 1, 'This message came to me concerning Tyre: Weep, O ships of Tarshish, returning home from distant lands! Weep for your harbor at Tyre because it is gone! The rumors you heard in Cyprus are all true.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 2, 'Mourn in silence, you people of the coast and you merchants of Sidon. Your traders crossed the sea,', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 3, 'sailing over deep waters. They brought you grain from Egypt and harvests from along the Nile. You were the merchandise mart of the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 4, 'But now you are put to shame, city of Sidon, fortress on the sea. For the sea says, "Now I am childless; I have no sons or daughters."', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 5, 'When Egypt hears the news about Tyre, there will be great sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 6, 'Flee now to Tarshish! Wail, you people who live by the sea!', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 7, 'How can this silent ruin be all that is left of your once joyous city? What a history was yours! Think of all the colonists you sent to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 8, 'Who has brought this disaster on Tyre, empire builder and chief trader of the world?', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 9, 'The LORD Almighty has done it to destroy your pride and show his contempt for all human greatness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 10, 'Come, Tarshish, sweep over your mother Tyre like the flooding Nile, for the city is defenseless.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 11, 'The LORD holds out his hand over the seas. He shakes the kingdoms of the earth. He has spoken out against Phoenicia and depleted its strength.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 12, 'He says, "Never again will you rejoice, O daughter of Sidon. Once you were a lovely city, but you will never again be strong. Even if you flee to Cyprus, you will find no rest."', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 13, 'Look at the land of Babylonia--the people of that land are gone! The Assyrians have handed Babylon over to the wild beasts. They have built siege ramps against its walls, torn down its palaces, and turned it into a heap of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 14, 'Wail, O ships of Tarshish, for your home port is destroyed!', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 15, 'For seventy years, the length of a king''s life, Tyre will be forgotten. But then the city will come back to life and sing sweet songs like a prostitute.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 16, 'Long absent from her lovers, she will take a harp, walk the streets, and sing her songs, so that she will again be remembered.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 17, 'Yes, after seventy years the LORD will revive Tyre. But she will be no different than she was before. She will return again to all her evil ways around the world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 23, 18, 'But in the end her businesses will give their profits to the LORD. Her wealth will not be hoarded but will be used to provide good food and fine clothing for the LORD''s priests.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 1, 'Look! The LORD is about to destroy the earth and make it a vast wasteland. See how he is scattering the people over the face of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 2, 'Priests and laypeople, servants and masters, maids and mistresses, buyers and sellers, lenders and borrowers, bankers and debtors--none will be spared.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 3, 'The earth will be completely emptied and looted. The LORD has spoken!', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 4, 'The earth dries up, the crops wither, the skies refuse to rain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 5, 'The earth suffers for the sins of its people, for they have twisted the instructions of God, violated his laws, and broken his everlasting covenant.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 6, 'Therefore, a curse consumes the earth and its people. They are left desolate, destroyed by fire. Few will be left alive.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 7, 'All the joys of life will be gone. The grape harvest will fail, and there will be no wine. The merrymakers will sigh and mourn.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 8, 'The clash of tambourines will be stilled; the happy cries of celebration will be heard no more. The melodious chords of the harp will be silent.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 9, 'Gone are the joys of wine and song; strong drink now turns bitter in the mouth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 10, 'The city writhes in chaos; every home is locked to keep out looters.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 11, 'Mobs gather in the streets, crying out for wine. Joy has reached its lowest ebb. Gladness has been banished from the land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 12, 'The city is left in ruins, with its gates battered down.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 13, 'Throughout the earth the story is the same--like the stray olives left on the tree or the few grapes left on the vine after harvest, only a remnant is left.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 14, 'But all who are left will shout and sing for joy. Those in the west will praise the LORD''s majesty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 15, 'In eastern lands, give glory to the LORD. In the coastlands of the sea, praise the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 16, 'Listen to them as they sing to the LORD from the ends of the earth. Hear them singing praises to the Righteous One! But my heart is heavy with grief. I am discouraged, for evil still prevails, and treachery is everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 17, 'Terror and traps and snares will be your lot, you people of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 18, 'Those who flee in terror will fall into a trap, and those who escape the trap will step into a snare. Destruction falls on you from the heavens. The world is shaken beneath you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 19, 'The earth has broken down and has utterly collapsed. Everything is lost, abandoned, and confused.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 20, 'The earth staggers like a drunkard. It trembles like a tent in a storm. It falls and will not rise again, for its sins are very great.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 21, 'In that day the LORD will punish the fallen angels in the heavens and the proud rulers of the nations on earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 22, 'They will be rounded up and put in prison until they are tried and condemned.', 'NLT'),
(27, 24, 23, 'Then the LORD Almighty will mount his throne on Mount Zion. He will rule gloriously in Jerusalem, in the sight of all the leaders of his people. There will be such glory that the brightness of the sun and moon will seem to fade away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 1, 'O LORD, I will honor and praise your name, for you are my God. You do such wonderful things! You planned them long ago, and now you have accomplished them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 2, 'You turn mighty cities into heaps of ruins. Cities with strong walls are turned to rubble. Beautiful palaces in distant lands disappear and will never be rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 3, 'Therefore, strong nations will declare your glory; ruthless nations will revere you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 4, 'But to the poor, O LORD, you are a refuge from the storm. To the needy in distress, you are a shelter from the rain and the heat. For the oppressive acts of ruthless people are like a storm beating against a wall,', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 5, 'or like the relentless heat of the desert. But you silence the roar of foreign nations. You cool the land with the shade of a cloud. So the boastful songs of ruthless people are stilled.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 6, 'In Jerusalem, the LORD Almighty will spread a wonderful feast for everyone around the world. It will be a delicious feast of good food, with clear, well-aged wine and choice beef.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 7, 'In that day he will remove the cloud of gloom, the shadow of death that hangs over the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 8, 'He will swallow up death forever! The Sovereign LORD will wipe away all tears. He will remove forever all insults and mockery against his land and people. The LORD has spoken!', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 9, 'In that day the people will proclaim, "This is our God. We trusted in him, and he saved us. This is the LORD, in whom we trusted. Let us rejoice in the salvation he brings!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 10, 'For the LORD''s good hand will rest on Jerusalem. Moab will be crushed like trampled straw and left to rot.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 11, 'God will push down Moab''s people as a swimmer pushes down water with his hands. He will end their pride and all their evil works.', 'NLT'),
(27, 25, 12, 'The high walls of Moab will be demolished and ground to dust.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 1, 'In that day, everyone in the land of Judah will sing this song: Our city is now strong! We are surrounded by the walls of God''s salvation.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 2, 'Open the gates to all who are righteous; allow the faithful to enter.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 3, 'You will keep in perfect peace all who trust in you, whose thoughts are fixed on you!', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 4, 'Trust in the LORD always, for the LORD GOD is the eternal Rock.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 5, 'He humbles the proud and brings the arrogant city to the dust. Its walls come crashing down!', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 6, 'The poor and oppressed trample it underfoot.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 7, 'But for those who are righteous, the path is not steep and rough. You are a God of justice, and you smooth out the road ahead of them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 8, 'LORD, we love to obey your laws; our heart''s desire is to glorify your name.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 9, 'All night long I search for you; earnestly I seek for God. For only when you come to judge the earth will people turn from wickedness and do what is right.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 10, 'Your kindness to the wicked does not make them do good. They keep doing wrong and take no notice of the LORD''s majesty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 11, 'O LORD, they do not listen when you threaten. They do not see your upraised fist. Show them your eagerness to defend your people. Perhaps then they will be ashamed. Let your fire consume your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 12, 'LORD, you will grant us peace, for all we have accomplished is really from you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 13, 'O LORD our God, others have ruled us, but we worship you alone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 14, 'Those we served before are dead and gone. Never again will they return! You attacked them and destroyed them, and they are long forgotten.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 15, 'We praise you, LORD! You have made our nation great; you have extended our borders!', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 16, 'LORD, in distress we searched for you. We were bowed beneath the burden of your discipline.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 17, 'We were like a woman about to give birth, writhing and crying out in pain. When we are in your presence, LORD,', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 18, 'we, too, writhe in agony, but nothing comes of our suffering. We have done nothing to rescue the world; no one has been born to populate the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 19, 'Yet we have this assurance: Those who belong to God will live; their bodies will rise again! Those who sleep in the earth will rise up and sing for joy! For God''s light of life will fall like dew on his people in the place of the dead!', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 20, 'Go home, my people, and lock your doors! Hide until the LORD''s anger against your enemies has passed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 26, 21, 'Look! The LORD is coming from heaven to punish the people of the earth for their sins. The earth will no longer hide those who have been murdered. They will be brought out for all to see.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 1, 'In that day the LORD will take his terrible, swift sword and punish Leviathan, the swiftly moving serpent, the coiling, writhing serpent, the dragon of the sea.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 2, '"In that day we will sing of the pleasant vineyard.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 3, 'I, the LORD, will watch over it and tend its fruitful vines. Each day I will water them; day and night I will watch to keep enemies away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 4, 'My anger against Israel will be gone. If I find briers and thorns bothering her, I will burn them up.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 5, 'These enemies will be spared only if they surrender and beg for peace and protection."', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 6, 'The time is coming when my people will take root. Israel will bud and blossom and fill the whole earth with her fruit!', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 7, 'Has the LORD punished Israel in the same way he has punished her enemies? No, for he devastated her enemies,', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 8, 'but he has punished Israel only a little. He has exiled her from her land as though blown away in a storm from the east.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 9, 'The LORD did this to purge away Israel''s sin. When he has finished, all the pagan altars will be crushed to dust. There won''t be an Asherah pole or incense altar left standing.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 10, 'Israel''s fortified cities will be silent and empty, the houses abandoned, the streets covered with grass. Cattle will graze there, chewing on twigs and branches.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 11, 'The people are like the dead branches of a tree, broken off and used for kindling beneath the cooking pots. Israel is a foolish and stupid nation, for its people have turned away from God. Therefore, the one who made them will show them no pity or mercy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 12, 'Yet the time will come when the LORD will gather them together one by one like handpicked grain. He will bring them to his great threshing floor--from the Euphrates River in the east to the brook of Egypt in the west.', 'NLT'),
(27, 27, 13, 'In that day the great trumpet will sound. Many who were dying in exile in Assyria and Egypt will return to Jerusalem to worship the LORD on his holy mountain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 1, 'Destruction is certain for the city of Samaria--the pride and joy of the drunkards of Israel! It sits in a rich valley, but its glorious beauty will suddenly disappear. Destruction is certain for that city--the pride of a people brought low by wine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 2, 'For the Lord will send the mighty Assyrian army against it. Like a mighty hailstorm and a torrential rain, they will burst upon it and dash it to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 3, 'The proud city of Samaria--the pride and joy of the drunkards of Israel--will be trampled beneath its enemies'' feet.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 4, 'It sits in a fertile valley, but its glorious beauty will suddenly disappear. It will be greedily snatched up, as an early fig is hungrily picked and eaten.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 5, 'Then at last the LORD Almighty will himself be Israel''s crowning glory. He will be the pride and joy of the remnant of his people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 6, 'He will give a longing for justice to their judges. He will give great courage to their warriors who stand at the gates.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 7, 'Now, however, Israel is being led by drunks! The priests and prophets reel and stagger from beer and wine. They make stupid mistakes as they carry out their responsibilities.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 8, 'Their tables are covered with vomit; filth is everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 9, 'They say, "Who does the LORD think we are? Why does he speak to us like this? Are we little children, barely old enough to talk?', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 10, 'He tells us everything over and over again, a line at a time, in very simple words! "', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 11, 'Since they refuse to listen, God will speak to them through foreign oppressors who speak an unknown language!', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 12, 'God''s people could have rest in their own land if they would only obey him, but they will not listen.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 13, 'So the LORD will spell out his message for them again, repeating it over and over, a line at a time, in very simple words. Yet they will stumble over this simple, straightforward message. They will be injured, trapped, and captured.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 14, 'Therefore, listen to this message from the LORD, you scoffing rulers in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 15, 'You boast that you have struck a bargain to avoid death and have made a deal to dodge the grave. You say, "The Assyrians can never touch us, for we have built a strong refuge made of lies and deception."', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 16, 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: "Look! I am placing a foundation stone in Jerusalem. It is firm, a tested and precious cornerstone that is safe to build on. Whoever believes need never run away again.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 17, '"I will take the measuring line of justice and the plumb line of righteousness to check the foundation wall you have built. Your refuge looks strong, but since it is made of lies, a hailstorm will knock it down. Since it is made of deception, the enemy will come like a flood to sweep it away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 18, 'I will cancel the bargain you made to avoid death, and I will overturn your deal to dodge the grave. When the terrible enemy floods in, you will be trampled into the ground.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 19, 'Again and again that flood will come, morning after morning, day and night, until you are carried away." This message will bring terror to your people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 20, 'For you have no place of refuge--the bed you have made is too short to lie on. The blankets are too narrow to cover you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 21, 'The LORD will come suddenly and in anger, as he did against the Philistines at Mount Perazim and against the Amorites at Gibeon. He will come to do a strange, unusual thing: He will destroy his own people!', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 22, 'So scoff no more, or your punishment will be even greater. For the Lord, the LORD Almighty, has plainly told me that he is determined to crush you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 23, 'Listen to me; listen as I plead!', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 24, 'Does a farmer always plow and never sow? Is he forever cultivating the soil and never planting it?', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 25, 'Does he not finally plant his seeds for dill, cumin, wheat, barley, and spelt, each in its own section of his land?', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 26, 'The farmer knows just what to do, for God has given him understanding.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 27, 'He doesn''t thresh all his crops the same way. A heavy sledge is never used on dill; rather, it is beaten with a light stick. A threshing wheel is never rolled on cumin; instead, it is beaten softly with a flail.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 28, 'Bread grain is easily crushed, so he doesn''t keep on pounding it. He threshes it under the wheels of a cart, but he doesn''t pulverize it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 28, 29, 'The LORD Almighty is a wonderful teacher, and he gives the farmer great wisdom.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 1, '"Destruction is certain for Ariel, the City of David. Year after year you offer your many sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 2, 'Yet I will bring disaster upon you, and there will be much weeping and sorrow. For Jerusalem will become as her name Ariel means--an altar covered with blood.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 3, 'I will be your enemy, surrounding Jerusalem and attacking its walls. I will build siege towers around it and will destroy it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 4, 'Your voice will whisper like a ghost from the earth where you will lie buried.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 5, '"But suddenly, your ruthless enemies will be driven away like chaff before the wind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 6, 'In an instant, I, the LORD Almighty, will come against them with thunder and earthquake and great noise, with whirlwind and storm and consuming fire.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 7, 'All the nations fighting against Jerusalem will vanish like a dream! Those who are attacking her walls will vanish like a vision in the night.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 8, 'A hungry person dreams of eating but is still hungry. A thirsty person dreams of drinking but is still faint from thirst when morning comes. In the same way, your enemies will dream of a victorious conquest over Jerusalem, but all to no avail."', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 9, 'Are you amazed and incredulous? Do you not believe it? Then go ahead and be blind if you must. You are stupid, but not from wine! You stagger, but not from beer!', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 10, 'For the LORD has poured out on you a spirit of deep sleep. He has closed the eyes of your prophets and visionaries.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 11, 'All these future events are a sealed book to them. When you give it to those who can read, they will say, "We can''t read it because it is sealed."', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 12, 'When you give it to those who cannot read, they will say, "Sorry, we don''t know how to read."', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 13, 'And so the Lord says, "These people say they are mine. They honor me with their lips, but their hearts are far away. And their worship of me amounts to nothing more than human laws learned by rote.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 14, 'Because of this, I will do wonders among these hypocrites. I will show that human wisdom is foolish and even the most brilliant people lack understanding."', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 15, 'Destruction is certain for those who try to hide their plans from the LORD, who try to keep him in the dark concerning what they do! "The LORD can''t see us," you say to yourselves. "He doesn''t know what is going on!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 16, 'How stupid can you be? He is the Potter, and he is certainly greater than you. You are only the jars he makes! Should the thing that was created say to the one who made it, "He didn''t make us"? Does a jar ever say, "The potter who made me is stupid"?', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 17, 'Soon--and it will not be very long--the wilderness of Lebanon will be a fertile field once again. And the fertile fields will become a lush and fertile forest.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 18, 'In that day deaf people will hear words read from a book, and blind people will see through the gloom and darkness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 19, 'The humble will be filled with fresh joy from the LORD. Those who are poor will rejoice in the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 20, 'Those who intimidate and harass will be gone, and all those who plot evil will be killed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 21, 'Those who make the innocent guilty by their false testimony will disappear. And those who use trickery to pervert justice and tell lies to tear down the innocent will be no more.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 22, 'That is why the LORD, who redeemed Abraham, says to the people of Israel, "My people will no longer pale with fear or be ashamed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 23, 'For when they see their many children and material blessings, they will recognize the holiness of the Holy One of Israel. They will stand in awe of the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 29, 24, 'Those in error will then believe the truth, and those who constantly complain will accept instruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 1, '"Destruction is certain for my rebellious children," says the LORD. "You make plans that are contrary to my will. You weave a web of plans that are not from my Spirit, thus piling up your sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 2, 'For without consulting me, you have gone down to Egypt to find help. You have put your trust in Pharaoh for his protection.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 3, 'But in trusting Pharaoh, you will be humiliated and disgraced.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 4, 'For though his power extends to Zoan and Hanes,', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 5, 'it will all turn out to your shame. He will not help you even one little bit."', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 6, 'Look at the animals moving slowly across the terrible desert to Egypt--donkeys and camels loaded with treasure to pay for Egypt''s aid. On through the wilderness they go, where lions and poisonous snakes live. All this, and Egypt will give you nothing in return.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 7, 'Egypt''s promises are worthless! I call her the Harmless Dragon.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 8, 'Now go and write down these words concerning Egypt. They will then stand until the end of time as a witness to Israel''s unbelief.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 9, 'For these people are stubborn rebels who refuse to pay any attention to the LORD''s instructions.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 10, 'They tell the prophets, "Shut up! We don''t want any more of your reports." They say, "Don''t tell us the truth. Tell us nice things. Tell us lies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 11, 'Forget all this gloom. We have heard more than enough about your `Holy One of Israel.'' We are tired of listening to what he has to say."', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 12, 'This is the reply of the Holy One of Israel: "Because you despise what I tell you and trust instead in oppression and lies,', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 13, 'calamity will come upon you suddenly. It will be like a bulging wall that bursts and falls. In an instant it will collapse and come crashing down.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 14, 'You will be smashed like a piece of pottery--shattered so completely that there won''t be a piece left that is big enough to carry coals from a fireplace or a little water from the well."', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 15, 'The Sovereign LORD, the Holy One of Israel, says, "Only in returning to me and waiting for me will you be saved. In quietness and confidence is your strength. But you would have none of it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 16, 'You said, `No, we will get our help from Egypt. They will give us swift horses for riding into battle.'' But the only swiftness you are going to see is the swiftness of your enemies chasing you!', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 17, 'One of them will chase a thousand of you. Five of them will make all of you flee. You will be left like a lonely flagpole on a distant mountaintop."', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 18, 'But the LORD still waits for you to come to him so he can show you his love and compassion. For the LORD is a faithful God. Blessed are those who wait for him to help them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 19, 'O people of Zion, who live in Jerusalem, you will weep no more. He will be gracious if you ask for help. He will respond instantly to the sound of your cries.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 20, 'Though the Lord gave you adversity for food and affliction for drink, he will still be with you to teach you. You will see your teacher with your own eyes,', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 21, 'and you will hear a voice say, "This is the way; turn around and walk here."', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 22, 'Then you will destroy all your silver idols and gold images. You will throw them out like filthy rags. "Ugh!" you will say to them. "Begone!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 23, 'Then the LORD will bless you with rain at planting time. There will be wonderful harvests and plenty of pastureland for your cattle.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 24, 'The oxen and donkeys that till the ground will eat good grain, its chaff having been blown away by the wind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 25, 'In that day, when your enemies are slaughtered, there will be streams of water flowing down every mountain and hill.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 26, 'The moon will be as bright as the sun, and the sun will be seven times brighter--like the light of seven days! So it will be when the LORD begins to heal his people and cure the wounds he gave them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 27, 'Look! The LORD is coming from far away, burning with anger, surrounded by a thick, rising smoke. His lips are filled with fury; his words consume like fire.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 28, 'His anger pours out like a flood on his enemies, sweeping them all away. He will sift out the proud nations. He will bridle them and lead them off to their destruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 29, 'But the people of God will sing a song of joy, like the songs at the holy festivals. You will be filled with joy, as when a flutist leads a group of pilgrims to Jerusalem--the mountain of the LORD--to the Rock of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 30, 'And the LORD will make his majestic voice heard. With angry indignation he will bring down his mighty arm on his enemies. It will descend with devouring flames, with cloudbursts, thunderstorms, and huge hailstones, bringing their destruction.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 31, 'At the LORD''s command, the Assyrians will be shattered. He will strike them down with his rod.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 32, 'And as the LORD strikes them, his people will keep time with the music of tambourines and harps.', 'NLT'),
(27, 30, 33, 'Topheth--the place of burning--has long been ready for the Assyrian king; it has been piled high with wood. The breath of the LORD, like fire from a volcano, will set it ablaze.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 1, 'Destruction is certain for those who look to Egypt for help, trusting their cavalry and chariots instead of looking to the LORD, the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 2, 'In his wisdom, the LORD will send great disaster; he will not change his mind. He will rise against those who are wicked, and he will crush their allies, too.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 3, 'For these Egyptians are mere humans, not God! Their horses are puny flesh, not mighty spirits! When the LORD clenches his fist against them, they will stumble and fall among those they are trying to help. They will all fall down and die together.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 4, 'But the LORD has told me this: "When a lion, even a young one, kills a sheep, it pays no attention to the shepherd''s shouts and noise. It just goes right on eating. In the same way, the LORD Almighty will come and fight on Mount Zion. He will not be frightened away!', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 5, 'The LORD Almighty will hover over Jerusalem as a bird hovers around its nest. He will defend and save the city; he will pass over it and rescue it."', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 6, 'Therefore, my people, though you are such wicked rebels, come and return to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 7, 'I know the glorious day will come when every one of you will throw away the gold idols and silver images that your sinful hands have made.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 8, '"The Assyrians will be destroyed, but not by the swords of men. The sword of God will strike them, and they will panic and flee. The strong young Assyrians will be taken away as captives.', 'NLT'),
(27, 31, 9, 'Even their generals will quake with terror and flee when they see the battle flags," says the LORD, whose flame burns brightly in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 1, 'Look, a righteous king is coming! And honest princes will rule under him.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 2, 'He will shelter Israel from the storm and the wind. He will refresh her as a river in the desert and as the cool shadow of a large rock in a hot and weary land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 3, 'Then everyone who can see will be looking for God, and those who can hear will listen to his voice.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 4, 'Even the hotheads among them will be full of sense and understanding. Those who stammer in uncertainty will speak out plainly.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 5, 'In that day ungodly fools will not be heroes. Wealthy cheaters will not be respected as outstanding citizens.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 6, 'Everyone will recognize ungodly fools for what they are. They spread lies about the LORD; they deprive the hungry of food and give no water to the thirsty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 7, 'The smooth tricks of evil people will be exposed, including all the lies they use to oppress the poor in the courts.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 8, 'But good people will be generous to others and will be blessed for all they do.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 9, 'Listen, you women who lie around in lazy ease. Listen to me, and I will tell you of your reward.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 10, 'In a short time--in just a little more than a year--you careless ones will suddenly begin to care. For your fruit crop will fail, and the harvest will never take place.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 11, 'Tremble, you women of ease; throw off your unconcern. Strip off your pretty clothes, and wear sackcloth in your grief.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 12, 'Beat your breasts in sorrow for your bountiful farms that will soon be gone, and for those fruitful vines of other years.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 13, 'For your land will be overgrown with thorns and briers. Your joyful homes and happy cities will be gone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 14, 'The palace and the city will be deserted, and busy towns will be empty. Herds of donkeys and goats will graze on the hills where the watchtowers are,', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 15, 'until at last the Spirit is poured down upon us from heaven. Then the wilderness will become a fertile field, and the fertile field will become a lush and fertile forest.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 16, 'Justice will rule in the wilderness and righteousness in the fertile field.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 17, 'And this righteousness will bring peace. Quietness and confidence will fill the land forever.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 18, 'My people will live in safety, quietly at home. They will be at rest.', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 19, 'Even though the forest will be destroyed and the city torn down,', 'NLT'),
(27, 32, 20, 'God will greatly bless his people. Wherever they plant seed, bountiful crops will spring up. Their flocks and herds will graze in green pastures.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 1, 'Destruction is certain for you Assyrians, who have destroyed everything around you but have never felt destruction yourselves. You expect others to respect their promises to you, while you betray your promises to them. Now you, too, will be betrayed and destroyed!', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 2, 'But LORD, be merciful to us, for we have waited for you. Be our strength each day and our salvation in times of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 3, 'The enemy runs at the sound of your voice. When you stand up, the nations flee!', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 4, 'Just as locusts strip the fields and vines, so Jerusalem will strip the fallen army of Assyria!', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 5, 'Though the LORD is very great and lives in heaven, he will make Jerusalem his home of justice and righteousness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 6, 'In that day he will be your sure foundation, providing a rich store of salvation, wisdom, and knowledge. The fear of the LORD is the key to this treasure.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 7, 'But now your ambassadors weep in bitter disappointment, for Assyria has refused their petition for peace.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 8, 'Your roads are deserted; no one travels them anymore. The Assyrians have broken their peace pact and care nothing for the promises they made before witnesses. They have no respect for anyone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 9, 'All the land of Israel is in trouble. Lebanon has been destroyed. The plain of Sharon is now a wilderness. Bashan and Carmel have been plundered.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 10, 'But the LORD says: "I will stand up and show my power and might.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 11, 'You Assyrians will gain nothing by all your efforts. Your own breath will turn to fire and kill you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 12, 'Your people will be burned up completely, like thorns cut down and tossed in a fire.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 13, 'Listen to what I have done, you nations far away! And you that are near, acknowledge my might!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 14, 'The sinners in Jerusalem shake with fear. "Which one of us," they cry, "can live here in the presence of this all-consuming fire?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 15, 'The ones who can live here are those who are honest and fair, who reject making a profit by fraud, who stay far away from bribes, who refuse to listen to those who plot murder, who shut their eyes to all enticement to do wrong.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 16, 'These are the ones who will dwell on high. The rocks of the mountains will be their fortress of safety. Food will be supplied to them, and they will have water in abundance.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 17, 'Your eyes will see the king in all his splendor, and you will see a land that stretches into the distance.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 18, 'You will think back to this time of terror when the Assyrian officers outside your walls counted your towers and estimated how much plunder they would get from your fallen city.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 19, 'But soon they will all be gone. These fierce, violent people with a strange, unknown language will disappear.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 20, 'Instead, you will see Zion as a place of worship and celebration. You will see Jerusalem, a city quiet and secure.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 21, 'The LORD will be our Mighty One. He will be like a wide river of protection that no enemy can cross.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 22, 'For the LORD is our judge, our lawgiver, and our king. He will care for us and save us.', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 23, 'The enemies'' sails hang loose on broken masts with useless tackle. Their treasure will be divided by the people of God. Even the lame will win their share!', 'NLT'),
(27, 33, 24, 'The people of Israel will no longer say, "We are sick and helpless," for the LORD will forgive their sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 1, 'Come here and listen, O nations of the earth. Let the world and everything in it hear my words.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 2, 'For the LORD is enraged against the nations. His fury is against all their armies. He will completely destroy them, bringing about their slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 3, 'Their dead will be left unburied, and the stench of rotting bodies will fill the land. The mountains will flow with their blood.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 4, 'The heavens above will melt away and disappear like a rolled-up scroll. The stars will fall from the sky, just as withered leaves and fruit fall from a tree.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 5, 'And when my sword has finished its work in the heavens, then watch. It will fall upon Edom, the nation I have completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 6, 'The sword of the LORD is drenched with blood. It is covered with fat as though it had been used for killing lambs and goats and rams for a sacrifice. Yes, the LORD will offer a great sacrifice in the rich city of Bozrah. He will make a mighty slaughter in Edom.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 7, 'The strongest will die--veterans and young men, too. The land will be soaked with blood and the soil enriched with fat.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 8, 'For it is the day of the LORD''s vengeance, the year when Edom will be paid back for all it did to Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 9, 'The streams of Edom will be filled with burning pitch, and the ground will be covered with fire.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 10, 'This judgment on Edom will never end; the smoke of its burning will rise forever. The land will lie deserted from generation to generation. No one will live there anymore.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 11, 'It will be haunted by the horned owl, the hawk, the screech owl, and the raven. For God will bring chaos and destruction to that land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 12, 'It will be called the Land of Nothing, and its princes soon will all be gone.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 13, 'Thorns will overrun its palaces; nettles will grow in its forts. The ruins will become a haunt for jackals and a home for ostriches.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 14, 'Wild animals of the desert will mingle there with hyenas, their howls filling the night. Wild goats will bleat at one another among the ruins, and night creatures will come there to rest.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 15, 'There the owl will make her nest and lay her eggs. She will hatch her young and cover them with her wings. And the vultures will come, each one with its mate.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 16, 'Search the book of the LORD, and see what he will do. He will not miss a single detail. Not one of these birds and animals will be missing, and none will lack a mate, for the LORD has promised this. His Spirit will make it all come true.', 'NLT'),
(27, 34, 17, 'He has surveyed and divided the land and deeded it over to those creatures. They will possess it forever, from generation to generation.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 1, 'Even the wilderness will rejoice in those days. The desert will blossom with flowers.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 2, 'Yes, there will be an abundance of flowers and singing and joy! The deserts will become as green as the mountains of Lebanon, as lovely as Mount Carmel''s pastures and the plain of Sharon. There the LORD will display his glory, the splendor of our God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 3, 'With this news, strengthen those who have tired hands, and encourage those who have weak knees.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 4, 'Say to those who are afraid, "Be strong, and do not fear, for your God is coming to destroy your enemies. He is coming to save you."', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 5, 'And when he comes, he will open the eyes of the blind and unstop the ears of the deaf.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 6, 'The lame will leap like a deer, and those who cannot speak will shout and sing! Springs will gush forth in the wilderness, and streams will water the desert.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 7, 'The parched ground will become a pool, and springs of water will satisfy the thirsty land. Marsh grass and reeds and rushes will flourish where desert jackals once lived.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 8, 'And a main road will go through that once deserted land. It will be named the Highway of Holiness. Evil-hearted people will never travel on it. It will be only for those who walk in God''s ways; fools will never walk there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 9, 'Lions will not lurk along its course, and there will be no other dangers. Only the redeemed will follow it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 35, 10, 'Those who have been ransomed by the LORD will return to Jerusalem, singing songs of everlasting joy. Sorrow and mourning will disappear, and they will be overcome with joy and gladness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 1, 'In the fourteenth year of King Hezekiah''s reign, King Sennacherib of Assyria came to attack the fortified cities of Judah and conquered them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 2, 'Then the king of Assyria sent his personal representative with a huge army from Lachish to confront King Hezekiah in Jerusalem. The Assyrians stopped beside the aqueduct that feeds water into the upper pool, near the road leading to the field where cloth is bleached.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 3, 'These are the officials who went out to meet with them: Eliakim son of Hilkiah, the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and Joah son of Asaph, the royal historian.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 4, 'Then the Assyrian king''s personal representative sent this message to King Hezekiah: "This is what the great king of Assyria says: What are you trusting in that makes you so confident?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 5, 'Do you think that mere words can substitute for military skill and strength? Which of your allies will give you any military backing against Assyria?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 6, 'Will Egypt? If you lean on Egypt, you will find it to be a stick that breaks beneath your weight and pierces your hand. The Pharaoh of Egypt is completely unreliable!', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 7, '"But perhaps you will say, `We are trusting in the LORD our God!'' But isn''t he the one who was insulted by King Hezekiah? Didn''t Hezekiah tear down his shrines and altars and make everyone in Judah worship only at the altar here in Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 8, '"I''ll tell you what! My master, the king of Assyria, will strike a bargain with you. If you can find two thousand horsemen in your entire army, he will give you two thousand horses for them to ride on!', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 9, 'With your tiny army, how can you think of challenging even the weakest contingent of my master''s troops, even with the help of Egypt''s chariots and horsemen?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 10, 'What''s more, do you think we have invaded your land without the LORD''s direction? The LORD himself told us, `Go and destroy it!''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 11, 'Then Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah said to the king''s representative, "Please speak to us in Aramaic, for we understand it well. Don''t speak in Hebrew, for the people on the wall will hear."', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 12, 'But Sennacherib''s representative replied, "My master wants everyone in Jerusalem to hear this, not just you. He wants them to know that if you do not surrender, this city will be put under siege. The people will become so hungry and thirsty that they will eat their own dung and drink their own urine."', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 13, 'Then he stood and shouted in Hebrew to the people on the wall, "Listen to this message from the great king of Assyria!', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 14, 'This is what the king says: Don''t let King Hezekiah deceive you. He will never be able to rescue you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 15, 'Don''t let him fool you into trusting in the LORD by saying, `The LORD will rescue us! This city will never be handed over to the Assyrian king.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 16, '"Don''t listen to Hezekiah! These are the terms the king of Assyria is offering: Make peace with me--open the gates and come out. Then I will allow each of you to continue eating from your own garden and drinking from your own well.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 17, 'Then I will arrange to take you to another land like this one--a country with bountiful harvests of grain and wine, bread and vineyards--a land of plenty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 18, '"Don''t let Hezekiah mislead you by saying, `The LORD will rescue us!'' Have the gods of any other nations ever saved their people from the king of Assyria?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 19, 'What happened to the gods of Hamath and Arpad? And what about the gods of Sepharvaim? Did they rescue Samaria from my power?', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 20, 'What god of any nation has ever been able to save its people from my power? Name just one! So what makes you think that the LORD can rescue Jerusalem?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 21, 'But the people were silent and did not answer because Hezekiah had told them not to speak.', 'NLT'),
(27, 36, 22, 'Then Eliakim son of Hilkiah, the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and Joah son of Asaph, the royal historian, went back to Hezekiah. They tore their clothes in despair, and they went in to see the king and told him what the Assyrian representative had said.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 1, 'When King Hezekiah heard their report, he tore his clothes and put on sackcloth and went into the Temple of the LORD to pray.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 2, 'And he sent Eliakim the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary, and the leading priests, all dressed in sackcloth, to the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 3, 'They told him, "This is what King Hezekiah says: This is a day of trouble, insult, and disgrace. It is like when a child is ready to be born, but the mother has no strength to deliver it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 4, 'But perhaps the LORD your God has heard the Assyrian representative defying the living God and will punish him for his words. Oh, pray for those of us who are left!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 5, 'After King Hezekiah''s officials delivered the king''s message to Isaiah,', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 6, 'the prophet replied, "Say to your master, `This is what the LORD says: Do not be disturbed by this blasphemous speech against me from the Assyrian king''s messengers.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 7, 'Listen! I myself will make sure that the king will receive a report from Assyria telling him that he is needed at home. Then I will make him want to return to his land, where I will have him killed with a sword.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 8, 'Meanwhile, the Assyrian representative left Jerusalem and went to consult his king, who had left Lachish and was attacking Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 9, 'Soon afterward King Sennacherib received word that King Tirhakah of Ethiopia was leading an army to fight against him. Before leaving to meet the attack, he sent this message back to Hezekiah in Jerusalem:', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 10, '"This message is for King Hezekiah of Judah. Don''t let this God you trust deceive you with promises that Jerusalem will not be captured by the king of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 11, 'You know perfectly well what the kings of Assyria have done wherever they have gone. They have crushed everyone who stood in their way! Why should you be any different?', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 12, 'Have the gods of other nations rescued them--such nations as Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the people of Eden who were in Tel-assar? The former kings of Assyria destroyed them all!', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 13, 'What happened to the king of Hamath and the king of Arpad? What happened to the kings of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 14, 'After Hezekiah received the letter and read it, he went up to the LORD''s Temple and spread it out before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 15, 'And Hezekiah prayed this prayer before the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 16, '"O LORD Almighty, God of Israel, you are enthroned between the mighty cherubim! You alone are God of all the kingdoms of the earth. You alone created the heavens and the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 17, 'Listen to me, O LORD, and hear! Open your eyes, O LORD, and see! Listen to Sennacherib''s words of defiance against the living God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 18, '"It is true, LORD, that the kings of Assyria have destroyed all these nations, just as the message says.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 19, 'And they have thrown the gods of these nations into the fire and burned them. But of course the Assyrians could destroy them! They were not gods at all--only idols of wood and stone shaped by human hands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 20, 'Now, O LORD our God, rescue us from his power; then all the kingdoms of the earth will know that you alone, O LORD, are God."', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 21, 'Then Isaiah son of Amoz sent this message to Hezekiah: "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: This is my answer to your prayer concerning King Sennacherib of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 22, 'This is the message that the LORD has spoken against him: `The virgin daughter of Zion despises you and laughs at you. The daughter of Jerusalem scoffs and shakes her head as you flee.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 23, '`Whom do you think you have been insulting and ridiculing? Against whom did you raise your voice? At whom did you look in such proud condescension? It was the Holy One of Israel!', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 24, 'By your messengers you have mocked the Lord. You have said, "With my many chariots I have conquered the highest mountains--yes, the remotest peaks of Lebanon. I have cut down its tallest cedars and its choicest cypress trees. I have reached its farthest corners and explored its deepest forests.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 25, 'I have dug wells in many a foreign land and refreshed myself with their water. I even stopped up the rivers of Egypt so that my armies could go across!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 26, '`But have you not heard? It was I, the LORD, who decided this long ago. Long ago I planned what I am now causing to happen, that you should crush fortified cities into heaps of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 27, 'That is why their people have so little power and are such easy prey for you. They are as helpless as the grass, as easily trampled as tender green shoots. They are like grass sprouting on a housetop, easily scorched by the sun.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 28, '`But I know you well--your comings and goings and all you do. I know the way you have raged against me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 29, 'And because of your arrogance against me, which I have heard for myself, I will put my hook in your nose and my bridle in your mouth. I will make you return by the road on which you came.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 30, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, "Here is the proof that the LORD will protect this city from Assyria''s king. This year you will eat only what grows up by itself, and next year you will eat what springs up from that. But in the third year you will plant crops and harvest them; you will tend vineyards and eat their fruit.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 31, 'And you who are left in Judah, who have escaped the ravages of the siege, will take root again in your own soil, and you will flourish and multiply.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 32, 'For a remnant of my people will spread out from Jerusalem, a group of survivors from Mount Zion. The passion of the LORD Almighty will make this happen!', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 33, '"And this is what the LORD says about the king of Assyria: His armies will not enter Jerusalem to shoot their arrows. They will not march outside its gates with their shields and build banks of earth against its walls.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 34, 'The king will return to his own country by the road on which he came. He will not enter this city, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 35, 'For my own honor and for the sake of my servant David, I will defend it."', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 36, 'That night the angel of the LORD went out to the Assyrian camp and killed 185,000 Assyrian troops. When the surviving Assyrians woke up the next morning, they found corpses everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 37, 'Then King Sennacherib of Assyria broke camp and returned to his own land. He went home to his capital of Nineveh and stayed there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 37, 38, 'One day while he was worshiping in the temple of his god Nisroch, his sons Adrammelech and Sharezer killed him with their swords. They then escaped to the land of Ararat, and another son, Esarhaddon, became the next king of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 1, 'About that time Hezekiah became deathly ill, and the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz went to visit him. He gave the king this message: "This is what the LORD says: Set your affairs in order, for you are going to die. You will not recover from this illness."', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 2, 'When Hezekiah heard this, he turned his face to the wall and prayed to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 3, '"Remember, O LORD, how I have always tried to be faithful to you and do what is pleasing in your sight." Then he broke down and wept bitterly.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 4, 'Then this message came to Isaiah from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 5, '"Go back to Hezekiah and tell him, `This is what the LORD, the God of your ancestor David, says: I have heard your prayer and seen your tears. I will add fifteen years to your life,', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 6, 'and I will rescue you and this city from the king of Assyria. Yes, I will defend this city.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 7, '" `And this is the sign that the LORD will give you to prove he will do as he promised:', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 8, 'I will cause the sun''s shadow to move ten steps backward on the sundial of Ahaz!''" So the shadow on the sundial moved backward ten steps.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 9, 'When King Hezekiah was well again, he wrote this poem about his experience:', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 10, 'I said, "In the prime of my life, must I now enter the place of the dead? Am I to be robbed of my normal years?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 11, 'I said, "Never again will I see the LORD GOD while still in the land of the living. Never again will I see my friends or laugh with those who live in this world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 12, 'My life has been blown away like a shepherd''s tent in a storm. It has been cut short, as when a weaver cuts cloth from a loom. Suddenly, my life was over.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 13, 'I waited patiently all night, but I was torn apart as though by lions. Suddenly, my life was over.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 14, 'Delirious, I chattered like a swallow or a crane, and then I moaned like a mourning dove. My eyes grew tired of looking to heaven for help. I am in trouble, Lord. Help me!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 15, 'But what could I say? For he himself had sent this sickness. Now I will walk humbly throughout my years because of this anguish I have felt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 16, 'Lord, your discipline is good, for it leads to life and health. You have restored my health and have allowed me to live!', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 17, 'Yes, it was good for me to suffer this anguish, for you have rescued me from death and have forgiven all my sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 18, 'For the dead cannot praise you; they cannot raise their voices in praise. Those who go down to destruction can no longer hope in your faithfulness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 19, 'Only the living can praise you as I do today. Each generation can make known your faithfulness to the next.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 20, 'Think of it--the LORD has healed me! I will sing his praises with instruments every day of my life in the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 21, 'Isaiah had said to Hezekiah''s servants, "Make an ointment from figs and spread it over the boil, and Hezekiah will recover."', 'NLT'),
(27, 38, 22, 'And Hezekiah had asked, "What sign will prove that I will go to the Temple of the LORD three days from now?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 1, 'Soon after this, Merodach-baladan son of Baladan, king of Babylon, sent Hezekiah his best wishes and a gift. He had heard that Hezekiah had been very sick and that he had recovered.', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 2, 'Hezekiah welcomed the Babylonian envoys and showed them everything in his treasure-houses--the silver, the gold, the spices, and the aromatic oils. He also took them to see his armory and showed them all his other treasures--everything! There was nothing in his palace or kingdom that Hezekiah did not show them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 3, 'Then Isaiah the prophet went to King Hezekiah and asked him, "What did those men want? Where were they from?" Hezekiah replied, "They came from the distant land of Babylon."', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 4, '"What did they see in your palace?" asked Isaiah. "They saw everything," Hezekiah replied. "I showed them everything I own--all my treasures."', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 5, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, "Listen to this message from the LORD Almighty:', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 6, 'The time is coming when everything you have--all the treasures stored up by your ancestors--will be carried off to Babylon. Nothing will be left, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 7, 'Some of your own descendants will be taken away into exile. They will become eunuchs who will serve in the palace of Babylon''s king."', 'NLT'),
(27, 39, 8, 'Then Hezekiah said to Isaiah, "This message you have given me from the LORD is good." But the king was thinking, "At least there will be peace and security during my lifetime."', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 1, '"Comfort, comfort my people," says your God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 2, '"Speak tenderly to Jerusalem. Tell her that her sad days are gone and that her sins are pardoned. Yes, the LORD has punished her in full for all her sins."', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 3, 'Listen! I hear the voice of someone shouting, "Make a highway for the LORD through the wilderness. Make a straight, smooth road through the desert for our God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 4, 'Fill the valleys and level the hills. Straighten out the curves and smooth off the rough spots.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 5, 'Then the glory of the LORD will be revealed, and all people will see it together. The LORD has spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 6, 'A voice said, "Shout!" I asked, "What should I shout?Shout that people are like the grass that dies away. Their beauty fades as quickly as the beauty of flowers in a field.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 7, 'The grass withers, and the flowers fade beneath the breath of the LORD. And so it is with people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 8, 'The grass withers, and the flowers fade, but the word of our God stands forever."', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 9, 'Messenger of good news, shout to Zion from the mountaintops! Shout louder to Jerusalem--do not be afraid. Tell the towns of Judah, "Your God is coming!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 10, 'Yes, the Sovereign LORD is coming in all his glorious power. He will rule with awesome strength. See, he brings his reward with him as he comes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 11, 'He will feed his flock like a shepherd. He will carry the lambs in his arms, holding them close to his heart. He will gently lead the mother sheep with their young.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 12, 'Who else has held the oceans in his hand? Who has measured off the heavens with his fingers? Who else knows the weight of the earth or has weighed out the mountains and the hills?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 13, 'Who is able to advise the Spirit of the LORD? Who knows enough to be his teacher or counselor?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 14, 'Has the LORD ever needed anyone''s advice? Does he need instruction about what is good or what is best?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 15, 'No, for all the nations of the world are nothing in comparison with him. They are but a drop in the bucket, dust on the scales. He picks up the islands as though they had no weight at all.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 16, 'All Lebanon''s forests do not contain sufficient fuel to consume a sacrifice large enough to honor him. All Lebanon''s sacrificial animals would not make an offering worthy of our God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 17, 'The nations of the world are as nothing to him. In his eyes they are less than nothing--mere emptiness and froth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 18, 'To whom, then, can we compare God? What image might we find to resemble him?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 19, 'Can he be compared to an idol formed in a mold, overlaid with gold, and decorated with silver chains?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 20, 'Or is a poor person''s wooden idol better? Can God be compared to an idol that must be placed on a stand so it won''t fall down?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 21, 'Have you never heard or understood? Are you deaf to the words of God--the words he gave before the world began? Are you so ignorant?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 22, 'It is God who sits above the circle of the earth. The people below must seem to him like grasshoppers! He is the one who spreads out the heavens like a curtain and makes his tent from them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 23, 'He judges the great people of the world and brings them all to nothing.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 24, 'They hardly get started, barely taking root, when he blows on them and their work withers. The wind carries them off like straw.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 25, '"To whom will you compare me? Who is my equal?" asks the Holy One.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 26, 'Look up into the heavens. Who created all the stars? He brings them out one after another, calling each by its name. And he counts them to see that none are lost or have strayed away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 27, 'O Israel, how can you say the LORD does not see your troubles? How can you say God refuses to hear your case?', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 28, 'Have you never heard or understood? Don''t you know that the LORD is the everlasting God, the Creator of all the earth? He never grows faint or weary. No one can measure the depths of his understanding.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 29, 'He gives power to those who are tired and worn out; he offers strength to the weak.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 30, 'Even youths will become exhausted, and young men will give up.', 'NLT'),
(27, 40, 31, 'But those who wait on the LORD will find new strength. They will fly high on wings like eagles. They will run and not grow weary. They will walk and not faint.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 1, '"Listen in silence before me, you lands beyond the sea. Bring your strongest arguments. Come now and speak. The court is ready for your case.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 2, '"Who has stirred up this king from the east, who meets victory at every step? Who, indeed, but the LORD? He gives him victory over many nations and permits him to trample their kings underfoot. He puts entire armies to the sword. He scatters them in the wind with his bow.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 3, 'He chases them away and goes on safely, though he is walking over unfamiliar ground.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 4, 'Who has done such mighty deeds, directing the affairs of the human race as each new generation marches by? It is I, the LORD, the First and the Last. I alone am he."', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 5, 'The lands beyond the sea watch in fear. Remote lands tremble and mobilize for war.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 6, 'They encourage one another with the words, "Be strong!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 7, 'The craftsmen rush to make new idols. The carver hurries the goldsmith, and the molder helps at the anvil. "Good," they say. "It''s coming along fine." Carefully they join the parts together, then fasten the thing in place so it won''t fall over.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 8, '"But as for you, Israel my servant, Jacob my chosen one, descended from my friend Abraham,', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 9, 'I have called you back from the ends of the earth so you can serve me. For I have chosen you and will not throw you away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 10, 'Don''t be afraid, for I am with you. Do not be dismayed, for I am your God. I will strengthen you. I will help you. I will uphold you with my victorious right hand.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 11, '"See, all your angry enemies lie there, confused and ashamed. Anyone who opposes you will die.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 12, 'You will look for them in vain. They will all be gone!', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 13, 'I am holding you by your right hand--I, the LORD your God. And I say to you, `Do not be afraid. I am here to help you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 14, 'Despised though you are, O Israel, don''t be afraid, for I will help you. I am the LORD, your Redeemer. I am the Holy One of Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 15, 'You will be a new threshing instrument with many sharp teeth. You will tear all your enemies apart, making chaff of mountains.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 16, 'You will toss them in the air, and the wind will blow them all away; a whirlwind will scatter them. And the joy of the LORD will fill you to overflowing. You will glory in the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 17, '"When the poor and needy search for water and there is none, and their tongues are parched from thirst, then I, the LORD, will answer them. I, the God of Israel, will never forsake them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 18, 'I will open up rivers for them on high plateaus. I will give them fountains of water in the valleys. In the deserts they will find pools of water. Rivers fed by springs will flow across the dry, parched ground.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 19, 'I will plant trees--cedar, acacia, myrtle, olive, cypress, fir, and pine--on barren land.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 20, 'Everyone will see this miracle and understand that it is the LORD, the Holy One of Israel, who did it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 21, '"Can your idols make such claims as these? Let them come and show what they can do!" says the LORD, the King of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 22, '"Let them try to tell us what happened long ago or what the future holds.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 23, 'Yes, that''s it! If you are gods, tell what will occur in the days ahead. Or perform a mighty miracle that will fill us with amazement and fear. Do something, whether good or bad!', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 24, 'But no! You are less than nothing and can do nothing at all. Anyone who chooses you becomes filthy, just like you!', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 25, '"But I have stirred up a leader from the north and east. He will come against the nations and call on my name, and I will give him victory over kings and princes. He will trample them as a potter treads on clay.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 26, '"Who but I have told you this would happen? Who else predicted this, making you admit that he was right? No one else said a word!', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 27, 'I was the first to tell Jerusalem, `Look! Help is on the way!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 28, 'Not one of your idols told you this. Not one gave any answer when I asked.', 'NLT'),
(27, 41, 29, 'See, they are all foolish, worthless things. Your idols are all as empty as the wind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 1, '"Look at my servant, whom I strengthen. He is my chosen one, and I am pleased with him. I have put my Spirit upon him. He will reveal justice to the nations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 2, 'He will be gentle--he will not shout or raise his voice in public.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 3, 'He will not crush those who are weak or quench the smallest hope. He will bring full justice to all who have been wronged.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 4, 'He will not stop until truth and righteousness prevail throughout the earth. Even distant lands beyond the sea will wait for his instruction."', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 5, 'God, the LORD, created the heavens and stretched them out. He created the earth and everything in it. He gives breath and life to everyone in all the world. And it is he who says,', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 6, '"I, the LORD, have called you to demonstrate my righteousness. I will guard and support you, for I have given you to my people as the personal confirmation of my covenant with them. And you will be a light to guide all nations to me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 7, 'You will open the eyes of the blind and free the captives from prison. You will release those who sit in dark dungeons.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 8, '"I am the LORD; that is my name! I will not give my glory to anyone else. I will not share my praise with carved idols.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 9, 'Everything I prophesied has come true, and now I will prophesy again. I will tell you the future before it happens."', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 10, 'Sing a new song to the LORD! Sing his praises from the ends of the earth! Sing, all you who sail the seas, all you who live in distant coastlands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 11, 'Join in the chorus, you desert towns; let the villages of Kedar rejoice! Let the people of Sela sing for joy; shout praises from the mountaintops!', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 12, 'Let the coastlands glorify the LORD; let them sing his praise.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 13, 'The LORD will march forth like a mighty man; he will come out like a warrior, full of fury. He will shout his thundering battle cry, and he will crush all his enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 14, 'He will say, "I have long been silent; yes, I have restrained myself. But now I will give full vent to my fury; I will gasp and pant like a woman giving birth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 15, 'I will level the mountains and hills and bring a blight on all their greenery. I will turn the rivers into dry land and will dry up all the pools.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 16, 'I will lead blind Israel down a new path, guiding them along an unfamiliar way. I will make the darkness bright before them and smooth out the road ahead of them. Yes, I will indeed do these things; I will not forsake them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 17, 'But those who trust in idols, calling them their gods--they will be turned away in shame.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 18, '"Oh, how deaf and blind you are toward me! Why won''t you listen? Why do you refuse to see?', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 19, 'Who in all the world is as blind as my own people, my servant? Who is as deaf as my messengers? Who is as blind as my chosen people, the servant of the LORD?', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 20, 'You see and understand what is right but refuse to act on it. You hear, but you don''t really listen."', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 21, 'The LORD has magnified his law and made it truly glorious. Through it he had planned to show the world that he is righteous.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 22, 'But what a sight his people are, for they have been robbed, enslaved, imprisoned, and trapped. They are fair game for all and have no one to protect them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 23, 'Will not even one of you apply these lessons from the past and see the ruin that awaits you?', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 24, 'Who allowed Israel to be robbed and hurt? Was it not the LORD? It was the LORD whom we sinned against, for the people would not go where he sent them, nor would they obey his law.', 'NLT'),
(27, 42, 25, 'That is why he poured out such fury on them and destroyed them in battle. They were set on fire and burned, but they still refused to understand.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 1, 'But now, O Israel, the LORD who created you says: "Do not be afraid, for I have ransomed you. I have called you by name; you are mine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 2, 'When you go through deep waters and great trouble, I will be with you. When you go through rivers of difficulty, you will not drown! When you walk through the fire of oppression, you will not be burned up; the flames will not consume you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 3, 'For I am the LORD, your God, the Holy One of Israel, your Savior. I gave Egypt, Ethiopia, and Seba as a ransom for your freedom.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 4, 'Others died that you might live. I traded their lives for yours because you are precious to me. You are honored, and I love you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 5, '"Do not be afraid, for I am with you. I will gather you and your children from east and west', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 6, 'and from north and south. I will bring my sons and daughters back to Israel from the distant corners of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 7, 'All who claim me as their God will come, for I have made them for my glory. It was I who created them."', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 8, 'Bring out the people who have eyes but are blind, who have ears but are deaf.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 9, 'Gather the nations together! Which of their idols has ever foretold such things? Can any of them predict something even a single day in advance? Where are the witnesses of such predictions? Who can verify that they spoke the truth?', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 10, '"But you are my witnesses, O Israel!" says the LORD. "And you are my servant. You have been chosen to know me, believe in me, and understand that I alone am God. There is no other God; there never has been and never will be.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 11, 'I am the LORD, and there is no other Savior.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 12, 'First I predicted your deliverance; I declared what I would do, and then I did it--I saved you. No foreign god has ever done this before. You are witnesses that I am the only God," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 13, '"From eternity to eternity I am God. No one can oppose what I do. No one can reverse my actions."', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 14, 'The LORD your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel, says: "For your sakes I will send an invading army against Babylon. And the Babylonians will be forced to flee in those ships they are so proud of.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 15, 'I am the LORD, your Holy One, Israel''s Creator and King.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 16, 'I am the LORD, who opened a way through the waters, making a dry path through the sea.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 17, 'I called forth the mighty army of Egypt with all its chariots and horses. I drew them beneath the waves, and they drowned, their lives snuffed out like a smoldering candlewick.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 18, '"But forget all that--it is nothing compared to what I am going to do.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 19, 'For I am about to do a brand-new thing. See, I have already begun! Do you not see it? I will make a pathway through the wilderness for my people to come home. I will create rivers for them in the desert!', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 20, 'The wild animals in the fields will thank me, the jackals and ostriches, too, for giving them water in the wilderness. Yes, I will make springs in the desert, so that my chosen people can be refreshed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 21, 'I have made Israel for myself, and they will someday honor me before the whole world.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 22, '"But, my dear people, you refuse to ask for my help. You have grown tired of me!', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 23, 'You have not brought me lambs for burnt offerings. You have not honored me with sacrifices, though I have not burdened and wearied you with my requests for grain offerings and incense.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 24, 'You have not brought me fragrant incense or pleased me with the fat from sacrifices. Instead, you have burdened me with your sins and wearied me with your faults.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 25, '"I--yes, I alone--am the one who blots out your sins for my own sake and will never think of them again.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 26, 'Let us review the situation together, and you can present your case if you have one.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 27, 'From the very beginning, your ancestors sinned against me--all your leaders broke my laws.', 'NLT'),
(27, 43, 28, 'That is why I have disgraced your priests and assigned Israel a future of complete destruction and shame.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 1, '"But now, listen to me, Jacob my servant, Israel my chosen one.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 2, 'The LORD who made you and helps you says: O Jacob, my servant, do not be afraid. O Israel, my chosen one, do not fear.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 3, 'For I will give you abundant water to quench your thirst and to moisten your parched fields. And I will pour out my Spirit and my blessings on your children.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 4, 'They will thrive like watered grass, like willows on a riverbank.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 5, 'Some will proudly claim, `I belong to the LORD.'' Others will say, `I am a descendant of Jacob.'' Some will write the LORD''s name on their hands and will take the honored name of Israel as their own.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 6, '"This is what the LORD, Israel''s King and Redeemer, the LORD Almighty, says: I am the First and the Last; there is no other God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 7, 'Who else can tell you what is going to happen in the days ahead? Let them tell you if they can and thus prove their power. Let them do as I have done since ancient times.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 8, 'Do not tremble; do not be afraid. Have I not proclaimed from ages past what my purposes are for you? You are my witnesses--is there any other God? No! There is no other Rock--not one!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 9, 'How foolish are those who manufacture idols to be their gods. These highly valued objects are really worthless. They themselves are witnesses that this is so, for their idols neither see nor know. No wonder those who worship them are put to shame.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 10, 'Who but a fool would make his own god--an idol that cannot help him one bit!', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 11, 'All who worship idols will stand before the LORD in shame, along with all these craftsmen--mere humans--who claim they can make a god. Together they will stand in terror and shame.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 12, 'The blacksmith stands at his forge to make a sharp tool, pounding and shaping it with all his might. His work makes him hungry and thirsty, weak and faint.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 13, 'Then the wood-carver measures and marks out a block of wood, takes the tool, and carves the figure of a man. Now he has a wonderful idol that cannot even move from where it is placed!', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 14, 'He cuts down cedars; he selects the cypress and the oak; he plants the cedar in the forest to be nourished by the rain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 15, 'And after his care, he uses part of the wood to make a fire to warm himself and bake his bread. Then--yes, it''s true--he takes the rest of it and makes himself a god for people to worship! He makes an idol and bows down and praises it!', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 16, 'He burns part of the tree to roast his meat and to keep himself warm.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 17, 'Then he takes what''s left and makes his god: a carved idol! He falls down in front of it, worshiping and praying to it. "Rescue me!" he says. "You are my god!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 18, 'Such stupidity and ignorance! Their eyes are closed, and they cannot see. Their minds are shut, and they cannot think.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 19, 'The person who made the idol never stops to reflect, "Why, it''s just a block of wood! I burned half of it for heat and used it to bake my bread and roast my meat. How can the rest of it be a god? Should I bow down to worship a chunk of wood?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 20, 'The poor, deluded fool feeds on ashes. He is trusting something that can give him no help at all. Yet he cannot bring himself to ask, "Is this thing, this idol that I''m holding in my hand, a lie?"', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 21, '"Pay attention, O Israel, for you are my servant. I, the LORD, made you, and I will not forget to help you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 22, 'I have swept away your sins like the morning mists. I have scattered your offenses like the clouds. Oh, return to me, for I have paid the price to set you free."', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 23, 'Sing, O heavens, for the LORD has done this wondrous thing. Shout, O earth! Break forth into song, O mountains and forests and every tree! For the LORD has redeemed Jacob and is glorified in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 24, 'The LORD, your Redeemer and Creator, says: "I am the LORD, who made all things. I alone stretched out the heavens. By myself I made the earth and everything in it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 25, 'I am the one who exposes the false prophets as liars by causing events to happen that are contrary to their predictions. I cause wise people to give bad advice, thus proving them to be fools.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 26, 'But I carry out the predictions of my prophets! When they say Jerusalem will be saved and the towns of Judah will be lived in once again, it will be done!', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 27, 'When I speak to the rivers and say, `Be dry!'' they will be dry.', 'NLT'),
(27, 44, 28, 'When I say of Cyrus, `He is my shepherd,'' he will certainly do as I say. He will command that Jerusalem be rebuilt and that the Temple be restored."', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 1, 'This is what the LORD says to Cyrus, his anointed one, whose right hand he will empower. Before him, mighty kings will be paralyzed with fear. Their fortress gates will be opened, never again to shut against him.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 2, 'This is what the LORD says: "I will go before you, Cyrus, and level the mountains. I will smash down gates of bronze and cut through bars of iron.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 3, 'And I will give you treasures hidden in the darkness--secret riches. I will do this so you may know that I am the LORD, the God of Israel, the one who calls you by name.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 4, '"And why have I called you for this work? It is for the sake of Jacob my servant, Israel my chosen one. I called you by name when you did not know me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 5, 'I am the LORD; there is no other God. I have prepared you, even though you do not know me,', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 6, 'so all the world from east to west will know there is no other God. I am the LORD, and there is no other.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 7, 'I am the one who creates the light and makes the darkness. I am the one who sends good times and bad times. I, the LORD, am the one who does these things.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 8, 'Open up, O heavens, and pour out your righteousness. Let the earth open wide so salvation and righteousness can sprout up together. I, the LORD, created them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 9, '"Destruction is certain for those who argue with their Creator. Does a clay pot ever argue with its maker? Does the clay dispute with the one who shapes it, saying, `Stop, you are doing it wrong!'' Does the pot exclaim, `How clumsy can you be!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 10, 'How terrible it would be if a newborn baby said to its father and mother, `Why was I born? Why did you make me this way?''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 11, 'This is what the LORD, the Creator and Holy One of Israel, says: "Do you question what I do? Do you give me orders about the work of my hands?', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 12, 'I am the one who made the earth and created people to live on it. With my hands I stretched out the heavens. All the millions of stars are at my command.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 13, 'I will raise up Cyrus to fulfill my righteous purpose, and I will guide all his actions. He will restore my city and free my captive people--and not for a reward! I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 14, 'This is what the LORD says: "The Egyptians, Ethiopians, and Sabeans will be subject to you. They will come to you with all their merchandise, and it will all be yours. They will follow you as prisoners in chains. They will fall to their knees in front of you and say, `God is with you, and he is the only God.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 15, 'Truly, O God of Israel, our Savior, you work in strange and mysterious ways.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 16, 'All who make idols will be humiliated and disgraced.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 17, 'But the LORD will save the people of Israel with eternal salvation. They will never again be humiliated and disgraced throughout everlasting ages.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 18, 'For the LORD is God, and he created the heavens and earth and put everything in place. He made the world to be lived in, not to be a place of empty chaos. "I am the LORD," he says, "and there is no other.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 19, 'I publicly proclaim bold promises. I do not whisper obscurities in some dark corner so no one can understand what I mean. And I did not tell the people of Israel to ask me for something I did not plan to give. I, the LORD, speak only what is true and right.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 20, '"Gather together and come, you fugitives from surrounding nations. What fools they are who carry around their wooden idols and pray to gods that cannot save!', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 21, 'Consult together, argue your case, and state your proofs that idol worship pays. Who made these things known long ago? What idol ever told you they would happen? Was it not I, the LORD? For there is no other God but me--a just God and a Savior--no, not one!', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 22, 'Let all the world look to me for salvation! For I am God; there is no other.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 23, 'I have sworn by my own name, and I will never go back on my word: Every knee will bow to me, and every tongue will confess allegiance to my name."', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 24, 'The people will declare, "The LORD is the source of all my righteousness and strength." And all who were angry with him will come to him and be ashamed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 45, 25, 'In the LORD all the generations of Israel will be justified, and in him they will boast.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 1, 'The idols of Babylon, Bel and Nebo, are being hauled away on ox carts. But look! The beasts are staggering under the weight!', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 2, 'Both the idols and the ones carrying them are bowed down. The gods cannot protect the people, and the people cannot protect the gods. They go off into captivity together.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 3, '"Listen to me, all you who are left in Israel. I created you and have cared for you since before you were born.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 4, 'I will be your God throughout your lifetime--until your hair is white with age. I made you, and I will care for you. I will carry you along and save you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 5, '"To whom will you compare me? Who is my equal?', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 6, 'Some people pour out their silver and gold and hire a craftsman to make a god from it. Then they bow down and worship it!', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 7, 'They carry it around on their shoulders, and when they set it down, it stays there. It cannot even move! And when someone prays to it, there is no answer. It has no power to get anyone out of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 8, '"Do not forget this, you guilty ones.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 9, 'And do not forget the things I have done throughout history. For I am God--I alone! I am God, and there is no one else like me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 10, 'Only I can tell you what is going to happen even before it happens. Everything I plan will come to pass, for I do whatever I wish.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 11, 'I will call a swift bird of prey from the east--a leader from a distant land who will come and do my bidding. I have said I would do it, and I will.', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 12, 'Listen to me, you stubborn, evil people!', 'NLT'),
(27, 46, 13, 'For I am ready to set things right, not in the distant future, but right now! I am ready to save Jerusalem and give my glory to Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 1, '"Come, Babylon, unconquered one, sit in the dust. For your days of glory, pomp, and honor have ended. O daughter of Babylonia, never again will you be the lovely princess, tender and delicate.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 2, 'Take heavy millstones and grind the corn. Remove your veil and strip off your robe. Expose yourself to public view.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 3, 'You will be naked and burdened with shame. I will take vengeance against you and will not negotiate."', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 4, 'Our Redeemer, whose name is the LORD Almighty, is the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 5, '"O daughter of Babylonia, sit now in darkness and silence. Never again will you be known as the queen of kingdoms.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 6, 'For I was angry with my chosen people and began their punishment by letting them fall into your hands. But you, Babylon, showed them no mercy. You have forced even the elderly to carry heavy burdens.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 7, 'You thought, `I will reign forever as queen of the world!'' You did not care at all about my people or think about the consequences of your actions.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 8, '"You are a pleasure-crazy kingdom, living at ease and feeling secure, bragging as if you were the greatest in the world! You say, `I''m self-sufficient and not accountable to anyone! I will never be a widow or lose my children.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 9, 'Well, those two things will come upon you in a moment: widowhood and the loss of your children. Yes, these calamities will come upon you, despite all your witchcraft and magic.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 10, '"You felt secure in all your wickedness. `No one sees me,'' you said. Your `wisdom'' and `knowledge'' have caused you to turn away from me and claim, `I am self-sufficient and not accountable to anyone!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 11, 'So disaster will overtake you suddenly, and you won''t be able to charm it away. Calamity will fall upon you, and you won''t be able to buy your way out. A catastrophe will arise so fast that you won''t know what hit you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 12, '"Call out the demon hordes you have worshiped all these years. Ask them to help you strike terror into the hearts of people once again.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 13, 'You have more than enough advisers, astrologers, and stargazers. Let them stand up and save you from what the future holds.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 14, 'But they are as useless as dried grass burning in a fire. They cannot even save themselves! You will get no help from them at all. Their hearth is not a place to sit for warmth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 47, 15, 'And all your friends, those with whom you have done business since childhood, will slip away and disappear, unable to help.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 1, '"Listen to me, O family of Jacob, who are called by the name of Israel and born into the family of Judah. Listen, you who take oaths in the name of the LORD and call on the God of Israel. You don''t follow through on any of your promises,', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 2, 'even though you call yourself the holy city and talk about depending on the God of Israel, whose name is the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 3, 'Time and again I warned you about what was going to happen in the future. Then suddenly I took action, and all my predictions came true.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 4, '"I know how stubborn and obstinate you are. Your necks are as unbending as iron. You are as hardheaded as bronze.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 5, 'That is why I told you ahead of time what I was going to do. That way, you could never say, `My idols did it. My wooden image and metal god commanded it to happen!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 6, 'You have heard my predictions and seen them fulfilled, but you refuse to admit it. Now I will tell you new things I have not mentioned before, secrets you have not yet heard.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 7, 'They are brand new, not things from the past. So you cannot say, `We knew that all the time!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 8, '"Yes, I will tell you of things that are entirely new, for I know so well what traitors you are. You have been rebels from your earliest childhood, rotten through and through.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 9, 'Yet for my own sake and for the honor of my name, I will hold back my anger and not wipe you out.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 10, 'I have refined you but not in the way silver is refined. Rather, I have refined you in the furnace of suffering.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 11, 'I will rescue you for my sake--yes, for my own sake! That way, the pagan nations will not be able to claim that their gods have conquered me. I will not let them have my glory!', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 12, '"Listen to me, O family of Jacob, Israel my chosen one! I alone am God, the First and the Last.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 13, 'It was my hand that laid the foundations of the earth. The palm of my right hand spread out the heavens above. I spoke, and they came into being.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 14, '"Have any of your idols ever told you this? Come, all of you, and listen: `The LORD has chosen Cyrus as his ally. He will use him to put an end to the empire of Babylon, destroying the Babylonian armies.''', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 15, 'I have said it: I am calling Cyrus! I will send him on this errand and will help him succeed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 16, 'Come closer and listen. I have always told you plainly what would happen so you would have no trouble understanding." And now the Sovereign LORD and his Spirit have sent me with this message:', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 17, '"The LORD, your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel, says: I am the LORD your God, who teaches you what is good and leads you along the paths you should follow.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 18, 'Oh, that you had listened to my commands! Then you would have had peace flowing like a gentle river and righteousness rolling like waves.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 19, 'Then you would have become as numerous as the sands along the seashore--too many to count! There would have been no need for your destruction."', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 20, 'Yet even now, be free from your captivity! Leave Babylon and the Babylonians, singing as you go! Shout to the ends of the earth that the LORD has redeemed his servants, the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 21, 'They were not thirsty when he led them through the desert. He divided the rock, and water gushed out for them to drink.', 'NLT'),
(27, 48, 22, '"But there is no peace for the wicked," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 1, 'Listen to me, all of you in far-off lands! The LORD called me before my birth; from within the womb he called me by name.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 2, 'He made my words of judgment as sharp as a sword. He has hidden me in the shadow of his hand. I am like a sharp arrow in his quiver.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 3, 'He said to me, "You are my servant, Israel, and you will bring me glory."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 4, 'I replied, "But my work all seems so useless! I have spent my strength for nothing and to no purpose at all. Yet I leave it all in the LORD''s hand; I will trust God for my reward."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 5, 'And now the LORD speaks--he who formed me in my mother''s womb to be his servant, who commissioned me to bring his people of Israel back to him. The LORD has honored me, and my God has given me strength.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 6, 'He says, "You will do more than restore the people of Israel to me. I will make you a light to the Gentiles, and you will bring my salvation to the ends of the earth."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 7, 'The LORD, the Redeemer and Holy One of Israel, says to the one who is despised and rejected by a nation, to the one who is the servant of rulers: "Kings will stand at attention when you pass by. Princes will bow low because the LORD has chosen you. He, the faithful LORD, the Holy One of Israel, chooses you."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 8, 'This is what the LORD says: "At just the right time, I will respond to you. On the day of salvation, I will help you. I will give you as a token and pledge to Israel. This will prove that I will reestablish the land of Israel and reassign it to its own people again.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 9, 'Through you I am saying to the prisoners of darkness, `Come out! I am giving you your freedom!'' They will be my sheep, grazing in green pastures and on hills that were previously bare.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 10, 'They will neither hunger nor thirst. The searing sun and scorching desert winds will not reach them anymore. For the LORD in his mercy will lead them beside cool waters.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 11, 'And I will make my mountains into level paths for them. The highways will be raised above the valleys.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 12, 'See, my people will return from far away, from lands to the north and west, and from as far south as Egypt. "', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 13, 'Sing for joy, O heavens! Rejoice, O earth! Burst into song, O mountains! For the LORD has comforted his people and will have compassion on them in their sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 14, 'Yet Jerusalem says, "The LORD has deserted us; the Lord has forgotten us."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 15, '"Never! Can a mother forget her nursing child? Can she feel no love for a child she has borne? But even if that were possible, I would not forget you!', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 16, 'See, I have written your name on my hand. Ever before me is a picture of Jerusalem''s walls in ruins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 17, 'Soon your descendants will come back, and all who are trying to destroy you will go away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 18, 'Look and see, for all your children will come back to you. As surely as I live," says the LORD, "they will be like jewels or bridal ornaments for you to display.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 19, '"Even the most desolate parts of your abandoned land will soon be crowded with your people. Your enemies who enslaved you will be far away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 20, 'The generations born in exile will return and say, `We need more room! It''s crowded here!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 21, 'Then you will think to yourself, `Who has given me all these descendants? For most of my children were killed, and the rest were carried away into exile. I was left here all alone. Who bore these children? Who raised them for me?''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 22, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: "See, I will give a signal to the godless nations. They will carry your little sons back to you in their arms; they will bring your daughters on their shoulders.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 23, 'Kings and queens will serve you. They will care for all your needs. They will bow to the earth before you and lick the dust from your feet. Then you will know that I am the LORD. Those who wait for me will never be put to shame."', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 24, 'Who can snatch the plunder of war from the hands of a warrior? Who can demand that a tyrant let his captives go?', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 25, 'But the LORD says, "The captives of warriors will be released, and the plunder of tyrants will be retrieved. For I will fight those who fight you, and I will save your children.', 'NLT'),
(27, 49, 26, 'I will feed your enemies with their own flesh. They will be drunk with rivers of their own blood. All the world will know that I, the LORD, am your Savior and Redeemer, the Mighty One of Israel. "', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 1, 'The LORD asks, "Did I sell you as slaves to my creditors? Is that why you are not here? Is your mother gone because I divorced her and sent her away? No, you went away as captives because of your sins. And your mother, too, was taken because of your sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 2, 'Was I too weak to save you? Is that why the house is silent and empty when I come home? Is it because I have no power to rescue? No, that is not the reason! For I can speak to the sea and make it dry! I can turn rivers into deserts covered with dying fish.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 3, 'I am the one who sends darkness out across the skies, bringing it to a state of mourning."', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 4, 'The Sovereign LORD has given me his words of wisdom, so that I know what to say to all these weary ones. Morning by morning he wakens me and opens my understanding to his will.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 5, 'The Sovereign LORD has spoken to me, and I have listened. I do not rebel or turn away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 6, 'I give my back to those who beat me and my cheeks to those who pull out my beard. I do not hide from shame, for they mock me and spit in my face.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 7, 'Because the Sovereign LORD helps me, I will not be dismayed. Therefore, I have set my face like a stone, determined to do his will. And I know that I will triumph.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 8, 'He who gives me justice is near. Who will dare to oppose me now? Where are my enemies? Let them appear!', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 9, 'See, the Sovereign LORD is on my side! Who will declare me guilty? All my enemies will be destroyed like old clothes that have been eaten by moths!', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 10, 'Who among you fears the LORD and obeys his servant? If you are walking in darkness, without a ray of light, trust in the LORD and rely on your God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 50, 11, 'But watch out, you who live in your own light and warm yourselves by your own fires. This is the reward you will receive from me: You will soon lie down in great torment.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 1, '"Listen to me, all who hope for deliverance--all who seek the LORD! Consider the quarry from which you were mined, the rock from which you were cut!', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 2, 'Yes, think about your ancestors Abraham and Sarah, from whom you came. Abraham was alone when I called him. But when I blessed him, he became a great nation."', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 3, 'The LORD will comfort Israel again and make her deserts blossom. Her barren wilderness will become as beautiful as Eden--the garden of the LORD. Joy and gladness will be found there. Lovely songs of thanksgiving will fill the air.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 4, '"Listen to me, my people. Hear me, Israel, for my law will be proclaimed, and my justice will become a light to the nations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 5, 'My mercy and justice are coming soon. Your salvation is on the way. I will rule the nations. They will wait for me and long for my power.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 6, 'Look up to the skies above, and gaze down on the earth beneath. For the skies will disappear like smoke, and the earth will wear out like a piece of clothing. The people of the earth will die like flies, but my salvation lasts forever. My righteous rule will never end!', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 7, '"Listen to me, you who know right from wrong and cherish my law in your hearts. Do not be afraid of people''s scorn or their slanderous talk.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 8, 'For the moth will destroy them as it destroys clothing. The worm will eat away at them as it eats wool. But my righteousness will last forever. My salvation will continue from generation to generation."', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 9, 'Wake up, LORD! Robe yourself with strength! Rouse yourself as in the days of old when you slew Egypt, the dragon of the Nile.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 10, 'Are you not the same today, the one who dried up the sea, making a path of escape when you saved your people?', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 11, 'Those who have been ransomed by the LORD will return to Jerusalem, singing songs of everlasting joy. Sorrow and mourning will disappear, and they will be overcome with joy and gladness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 12, '"I, even I, am the one who comforts you. So why are you afraid of mere humans, who wither like the grass and disappear?', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 13, 'Yet you have forgotten the LORD, your Creator, the one who put the stars in the sky and established the earth. Will you remain in constant dread of human oppression? Will you continue to fear the anger of your enemies from morning till night?', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 14, 'Soon all you captives will be released! Imprisonment, starvation, and death will not be your fate!', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 15, 'For I am the LORD your God, who stirs up the sea, causing its waves to roar. My name is the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 16, 'And I have put my words in your mouth and hidden you safely within my hand. I set all the stars in space and established the earth. I am the one who says to Israel, `You are mine!''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 17, 'Wake up, wake up, O Jerusalem! You have drunk enough from the cup of the LORD''s fury. You have drunk the cup of terror, tipping out its last drops.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 18, 'Not one of your children is left alive to help you or tell you what to do.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 19, 'These two things have been your lot: desolation and destruction, famine and war. And who is left to sympathize? Who is left to comfort you?', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 20, 'For your children have fainted and lie in the streets, helpless as antelopes caught in a net. The LORD has poured out his fury; God has rebuked them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 21, 'But now listen to this, you afflicted ones, who sit in a drunken stupor, though not from drinking wine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 22, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD, your God and Defender, says: "See, I am taking the terrible cup from your hands. You will drink no more of my fury. It is gone at last!', 'NLT'),
(27, 51, 23, 'But I will put that cup into the hands of those who tormented you. I will give it to those who trampled you into the dust and walked on your backs."', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 1, 'Wake up, wake up, O Zion! Clothe yourselves with strength. Put on your beautiful clothes, O holy city of Jerusalem, for unclean and godless people will no longer enter your gates.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 2, 'Rise from the dust, O Jerusalem. Remove the slave bands from your neck, O captive daughter of Zion.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 3, 'For this is what the LORD says: "When I sold you into exile, I received no payment. Now I can redeem you without paying for you."', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 4, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: "Long ago my people went to live as resident foreigners in Egypt. Now they have been oppressed without cause by Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 5, 'And now, what is this?" asks the LORD. "Why are my people enslaved again? Those who rule them shout in exultation. My name is being blasphemed all day long.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 6, 'But I will reveal my name to my people, and they will come to know its power. Then at last they will recognize that it is I who speaks to them."', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 7, 'How beautiful on the mountains are the feet of those who bring good news of peace and salvation, the news that the God of Israel reigns!', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 8, 'The watchmen shout and sing with joy, for before their very eyes they see the LORD bringing his people home to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 9, 'Let the ruins of Jerusalem break into joyful song, for the LORD has comforted his people. He has redeemed Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 10, 'The LORD will demonstrate his holy power before the eyes of all the nations. The ends of the earth will see the salvation of our God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 11, 'Go now, leave your bonds and slavery. Put Babylon behind you, with everything it represents, for it is unclean to you. You are the LORD''s holy people. Purify yourselves, you who carry home the vessels of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 12, 'You will not leave in a hurry, running for your lives. For the LORD will go ahead of you, and the God of Israel will protect you from behind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 13, 'See, my servant will prosper; he will be highly exalted.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 14, 'Many were amazed when they saw him--beaten and bloodied, so disfigured one would scarcely know he was a person.', 'NLT'),
(27, 52, 15, 'And he will again startle many nations. Kings will stand speechless in his presence. For they will see what they had not previously been told about; they will understand what they had not heard about.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 1, 'Who has believed our message? To whom will the LORD reveal his saving power?', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 2, 'My servant grew up in the LORD''s presence like a tender green shoot, sprouting from a root in dry and sterile ground. There was nothing beautiful or majestic about his appearance, nothing to attract us to him.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 3, 'He was despised and rejected--a man of sorrows, acquainted with bitterest grief. We turned our backs on him and looked the other way when he went by. He was despised, and we did not care.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 4, 'Yet it was our weaknesses he carried; it was our sorrows that weighed him down. And we thought his troubles were a punishment from God for his own sins!', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 5, 'But he was wounded and crushed for our sins. He was beaten that we might have peace. He was whipped, and we were healed!', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 6, 'All of us have strayed away like sheep. We have left God''s paths to follow our own. Yet the LORD laid on him the guilt and sins of us all.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 7, 'He was oppressed and treated harshly, yet he never said a word. He was led as a lamb to the slaughter. And as a sheep is silent before the shearers, he did not open his mouth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 8, 'From prison and trial they led him away to his death. But who among the people realized that he was dying for their sins--that he was suffering their punishment?', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 9, 'He had done no wrong, and he never deceived anyone. But he was buried like a criminal; he was put in a rich man''s grave.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 10, 'But it was the LORD''s good plan to crush him and fill him with grief. Yet when his life is made an offering for sin, he will have a multitude of children, many heirs. He will enjoy a long life, and the LORD''s plan will prosper in his hands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 11, 'When he sees all that is accomplished by his anguish, he will be satisfied. And because of what he has experienced, my righteous servant will make it possible for many to be counted righteous, for he will bear all their sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 53, 12, 'I will give him the honors of one who is mighty and great, because he exposed himself to death. He was counted among those who were sinners. He bore the sins of many and interceded for sinners.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 1, '"Sing, O childless woman! Break forth into loud and joyful song, O Jerusalem, even though you never gave birth to a child. For the woman who could bear no children now has more than all the other women," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 2, '"Enlarge your house; build an addition; spread out your home!', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 3, 'For you will soon be bursting at the seams. Your descendants will take over other nations and live in their cities.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 4, '"Fear not; you will no longer live in shame. The shame of your youth and the sorrows of widowhood will be remembered no more,', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 5, 'for your Creator will be your husband. The LORD Almighty is his name! He is your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel, the God of all the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 6, 'For the LORD has called you back from your grief--as though you were a young wife abandoned by her husband," says your God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 7, '"For a brief moment I abandoned you, but with great compassion I will take you back.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 8, 'In a moment of anger I turned my face away for a little while. But with everlasting love I will have compassion on you," says the LORD, your Redeemer.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 9, '"Just as I swore in the time of Noah that I would never again let a flood cover the earth and destroy its life, so now I swear that I will never again pour out my anger on you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 10, 'For the mountains may depart and the hills disappear, but even then I will remain loyal to you. My covenant of blessing will never be broken," says the LORD, who has mercy on you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 11, '"O storm-battered city, troubled and desolate! I will rebuild you on a foundation of sapphires and make the walls of your houses from precious jewels.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 12, 'I will make your towers of sparkling rubies and your gates and walls of shining gems.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 13, 'I will teach all your citizens, and their prosperity will be great.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 14, 'You will live under a government that is just and fair. Your enemies will stay far away; you will live in peace. Terror will not come near.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 15, 'If any nation comes to fight you, it will not be because I sent them to punish you. Your enemies will always be defeated because I am on your side.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 16, 'I have created the blacksmith who fans the coals beneath the forge and makes the weapons of destruction. And I have created the armies that destroy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 54, 17, 'But in that coming day, no weapon turned against you will succeed. And everyone who tells lies in court will be brought to justice. These benefits are enjoyed by the servants of the LORD; their vindication will come from me. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 1, '"Is anyone thirsty? Come and drink--even if you have no money! Come, take your choice of wine or milk--it''s all free!', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 2, 'Why spend your money on food that does not give you strength? Why pay for food that does you no good? Listen, and I will tell you where to get food that is good for the soul!', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 3, '"Come to me with your ears wide open. Listen, for the life of your soul is at stake. I am ready to make an everlasting covenant with you. I will give you all the mercies and unfailing love that I promised to David.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 4, 'He displayed my power by being my witness and a leader among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 5, 'You also will command the nations, and they will come running to obey, because I, the LORD your God, the Holy One of Israel, have made you glorious."', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 6, 'Seek the LORD while you can find him. Call on him now while he is near.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 7, 'Let the people turn from their wicked deeds. Let them banish from their minds the very thought of doing wrong! Let them turn to the LORD that he may have mercy on them. Yes, turn to our God, for he will abundantly pardon.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 8, '"My thoughts are completely different from yours," says the LORD. "And my ways are far beyond anything you could imagine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 9, 'For just as the heavens are higher than the earth, so are my ways higher than your ways and my thoughts higher than your thoughts.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 10, '"The rain and snow come down from the heavens and stay on the ground to water the earth. They cause the grain to grow, producing seed for the farmer and bread for the hungry.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 11, 'It is the same with my word. I send it out, and it always produces fruit. It will accomplish all I want it to, and it will prosper everywhere I send it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 12, 'You will live in joy and peace. The mountains and hills will burst into song, and the trees of the field will clap their hands!', 'NLT'),
(27, 55, 13, 'Where once there were thorns, cypress trees will grow. Where briers grew, myrtles will sprout up. This miracle will bring great honor to the LORD''s name; it will be an everlasting sign of his power and love.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 1, '"Be just and fair to all," says the LORD. "Do what is right and good, for I am coming soon to rescue you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 2, 'Blessed are those who are careful to do this. Blessed are those who honor my Sabbath days of rest by refusing to work. And blessed are those who keep themselves from doing wrong.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 3, '"And my blessings are for Gentiles, too, when they commit themselves to the LORD. Do not let them think that I consider them second-class citizens. And my blessings are also for the eunuchs. They are as much mine as anyone else.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 4, 'For I say this to the eunuchs who keep my Sabbath days holy, who choose to do what pleases me and commit their lives to me:', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 5, 'I will give them--in my house, within my walls--a memorial and a name far greater than the honor they would have received by having sons and daughters. For the name I give them is an everlasting one. It will never disappear!', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 6, '"I will also bless the Gentiles who commit themselves to the LORD and serve him and love his name, who worship him and do not desecrate the Sabbath day of rest, and who have accepted his covenant.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 7, 'I will bring them also to my holy mountain of Jerusalem and will fill them with joy in my house of prayer. I will accept their burnt offerings and sacrifices, because my Temple will be called a house of prayer for all nations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 8, 'For the Sovereign LORD, who brings back the outcasts of Israel, says: I will bring others, too, besides my people Israel."', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 9, 'Come, wild animals of the field! Come, wild animals of the forest! Come and devour my people!', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 10, 'For the leaders of my people--the LORD''s watchmen, his shepherds--are blind to every danger. They are like silent watchdogs that give no warning when danger comes. They love to lie around, sleeping and dreaming.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 11, 'And they are as greedy as dogs, never satisfied. They are stupid shepherds, all following their own path, all of them intent on personal gain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 56, 12, '"Come," they say. "We will get some wine and have a party. Let''s all get drunk. Let this go on and on, and tomorrow will be even better."', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 1, 'The righteous pass away; the godly often die before their time. And no one seems to care or wonder why. No one seems to understand that God is protecting them from the evil to come.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 2, 'For the godly who die will rest in peace.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 3, '"But you--come here, you witches'' children, you offspring of adulterers and prostitutes!', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 4, 'Whom do you mock, making faces and sticking out your tongues? You children of sinners and liars!', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 5, 'You worship your idols with great passion beneath every green tree. You slaughter your children as human sacrifices down in the valleys, under overhanging rocks.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 6, 'Your gods are the smooth stones in the valleys. You worship them with drink offerings and grain offerings. They, not I, are your inheritance. Does all this make me happy?', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 7, 'You have committed adultery on the mountaintops by worshiping idols there, and so you have been unfaithful to me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 8, 'Behind closed doors, you have set up your idols and worship them instead of me. This is adultery, for you are loving these idols instead of loving me. You have climbed right into bed with these detestable gods.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 9, 'You have given olive oil and perfume to Molech as your gift. You have traveled far, even into the world of the dead, to find new gods to love.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 10, 'You grew weary in your search, but you never gave up. You strengthened yourself and went on.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 11, 'Why were you more afraid of them than of me? How is it that you don''t even remember me or think about me? Is it because I have not corrected you that you have no fear of me?', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 12, '"Now I will expose your so-called good deeds that you consider so righteous. None of them will benefit or save you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 13, 'Let''s see if your idols can do anything for you when you cry to them for help. They are so helpless that a breath of wind can knock them down! But whoever trusts in me will possess the land and inherit my holy mountain.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 14, 'I will say, `Rebuild the road! Clear away the rocks and stones so my people can return from captivity.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 15, 'The high and lofty one who inhabits eternity, the Holy One, says this: "I live in that high and holy place with those whose spirits are contrite and humble. I refresh the humble and give new courage to those with repentant hearts.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 16, 'For I will not fight against you forever; I will not always show my anger. If I did, all people would pass away--all the souls I have made.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 17, 'I was angry and punished these greedy people. I withdrew myself from them, but they went right on sinning.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 18, 'I have seen what they do, but I will heal them anyway! I will lead them and comfort those who mourn.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 19, 'Then words of praise will be on their lips. May they have peace, both near and far, for I will heal them all," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 20, '"But those who still reject me are like the restless sea. It is never still but continually churns up mire and dirt.', 'NLT'),
(27, 57, 21, 'There is no peace for the wicked," says my God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 1, '"Shout with the voice of a trumpet blast. Tell my people Israel of their sins!', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 2, 'Yet they act so pious! They come to the Temple every day and seem delighted to hear my laws. You would almost think this was a righteous nation that would never abandon its God. They love to make a show of coming to me and asking me to take action on their behalf.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 3, '`We have fasted before you!'' they say. `Why aren''t you impressed? We have done much penance, and you don''t even notice it!''"I will tell you why! It''s because you are living for yourselves even while you are fasting. You keep right on oppressing your workers.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 4, 'What good is fasting when you keep on fighting and quarreling? This kind of fasting will never get you anywhere with me.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 5, 'You humble yourselves by going through the motions of penance, bowing your heads like a blade of grass in the wind. You dress in sackcloth and cover yourselves with ashes. Is this what you call fasting? Do you really think this will please the LORD?', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 6, '"No, the kind of fasting I want calls you to free those who are wrongly imprisoned and to stop oppressing those who work for you. Treat them fairly and give them what they earn.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 7, 'I want you to share your food with the hungry and to welcome poor wanderers into your homes. Give clothes to those who need them, and do not hide from relatives who need your help.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 8, '"If you do these things, your salvation will come like the dawn. Yes, your healing will come quickly. Your godliness will lead you forward, and the glory of the LORD will protect you from behind.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 9, 'Then when you call, the LORD will answer. `Yes, I am here,'' he will quickly reply. "Stop oppressing the helpless and stop making false accusations and spreading vicious rumors!', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 10, 'Feed the hungry and help those in trouble. Then your light will shine out from the darkness, and the darkness around you will be as bright as day.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 11, 'The LORD will guide you continually, watering your life when you are dry and keeping you healthy, too. You will be like a well-watered garden, like an ever-flowing spring.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 12, 'Your children will rebuild the deserted ruins of your cities. Then you will be known as the people who rebuild their walls and cities.', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 13, '"Keep the Sabbath day holy. Don''t pursue your own interests on that day, but enjoy the Sabbath and speak of it with delight as the LORD''s holy day. Honor the LORD in everything you do, and don''t follow your own desires or talk idly. If you do this,', 'NLT'),
(27, 58, 14, 'the LORD will be your delight. I will give you great honor and give you your full share of the inheritance I promised to Jacob, your ancestor. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 1, 'Listen! The LORD is not too weak to save you, and he is not becoming deaf. He can hear you when you call.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 2, 'But there is a problem--your sins have cut you off from God. Because of your sin, he has turned away and will not listen anymore.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 3, 'Your hands are the hands of murderers, and your fingers are filthy with sin. Your mouth is full of lies, and your lips are tainted with corruption.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 4, 'No one cares about being fair and honest. Their lawsuits are based on lies. They spend their time plotting evil deeds and then doing them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 5, 'They spend their time and energy spinning evil plans that end up in deadly actions.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 6, 'They cheat and shortchange everyone. Nothing they do is productive; all their activity is filled with sin. Violence is their trademark.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 7, 'Their feet run to do evil, and they rush to commit murder. They think only about sinning. Wherever they go, misery and destruction follow them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 8, 'They do not know what true peace is or what it means to be just and good. They continually do wrong, and those who follow them cannot experience a moment''s peace.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 9, 'It is because of all this evil that deliverance is far from us. That is why God doesn''t punish those who injure us. No wonder we are in darkness when we expected light. No wonder we are walking in the gloom.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 10, 'No wonder we grope like blind people and stumble along. Even at brightest noontime, we fall down as though it were dark. No wonder we are like corpses when compared to vigorous young men!', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 11, 'We growl like hungry bears; we moan like mournful doves. We look for justice, but it is nowhere to be found. We look to be rescued, but it is far away from us.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 12, 'For our sins are piled up before God and testify against us. Yes, we know what sinners we are.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 13, 'We know that we have rebelled against the LORD. We have turned our backs on God. We know how unfair and oppressive we have been, carefully planning our deceitful lies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 14, 'Our courts oppose people who are righteous, and justice is nowhere to be found. Truth falls dead in the streets, and fairness has been outlawed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 15, 'Yes, truth is gone, and anyone who tries to live a godly life is soon attacked. The LORD looked and was displeased to find that there was no justice.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 16, 'He was amazed to see that no one intervened to help the oppressed. So he himself stepped in to save them with his mighty power and justice.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 17, 'He put on righteousness as his body armor and placed the helmet of salvation on his head. He clothed himself with the robes of vengeance and godly fury.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 18, 'He will repay his enemies for their evil deeds. His fury will fall on his foes in distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 19, 'Then at last they will respect and glorify the name of the LORD throughout the world. For he will come like a flood tide driven by the breath of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 20, '"The Redeemer will come to Jerusalem, "says the LORD, "to buy back those in Israel who have turned from their sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 59, 21, 'And this is my covenant with them," says the LORD. "My Spirit will not leave them, and neither will these words I have given you. They will be on your lips and on the lips of your children and your children''s children forever. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 1, '"Arise, Jerusalem! Let your light shine for all the nations to see! For the glory of the LORD is shining upon you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 2, 'Darkness as black as night will cover all the nations of the earth, but the glory of the LORD will shine over you.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 3, 'All nations will come to your light. Mighty kings will come to see your radiance.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 4, '"Look and see, for everyone is coming home! Your sons are coming from distant lands; your little daughters will be carried home.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 5, 'Your eyes will shine, and your hearts will thrill with joy, for merchants from around the world will come to you. They will bring you the wealth of many lands.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 6, 'Vast caravans of camels will converge on you, the camels of Midian and Ephah. From Sheba they will bring gold and incense for the worship of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 7, 'The flocks of Kedar will be given to you, and the rams of Nebaioth will be brought for my altars. In that day I will make my Temple glorious.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 8, '"And what do I see flying like clouds to Israel, like doves to their nests?', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 9, 'They are the ships of Tarshish, reserved to bring the people of Israel home. They will bring their wealth with them, and it will bring great honor to the LORD your God, the Holy One of Israel, for he will fill you with splendor.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 10, '"Foreigners will come to rebuild your cities. Kings and rulers will send you aid. For though I have destroyed you in my anger, I will have mercy on you through my grace.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 11, 'Your gates will stay open around the clock to receive the wealth of many lands. The kings of the world will be led as captives in a victory procession.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 12, 'For the nations that refuse to be your allies will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 13, 'The glory of Lebanon will be yours--the forests of cypress, fir, and pine--to beautify my sanctuary. My Temple will be glorious!', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 14, '"The children of your tormentors will come and bow before you. Those who despised you will kiss your feet. They will call you the City of the LORD, and Zion of the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 15, '"Though you were once despised and hated and rebuffed by all, you will be beautiful forever. You will be a joy to all generations, for I will make you so.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 16, 'Powerful kings and mighty nations will bring the best of their goods to satisfy your every need. You will know at last that I, the LORD, am your Savior and Redeemer, the Mighty One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 17, 'I will exchange your bronze for gold, your iron for silver, your wood for bronze, and your stones for iron. Peace and righteousness will be your leaders!', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 18, 'Violence will disappear from your land; the desolation and destruction of war will end. Salvation will surround you like city walls, and praise will be on the lips of all who enter there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 19, '"No longer will you need the sun or moon to give you light, for the LORD your God will be your everlasting light, and he will be your glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 20, 'The sun will never set; the moon will not go down. For the LORD will be your everlasting light. Your days of mourning will come to an end.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 21, 'All your people will be righteous. They will possess their land forever, for I will plant them there with my own hands in order to bring myself glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 60, 22, 'The smallest family will multiply into a large clan. The tiniest group will become a mighty nation. I, the LORD, will bring it all to pass at the right time."', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 1, 'The Spirit of the Sovereign LORD is upon me, because the LORD has appointed me to bring good news to the poor. He has sent me to comfort the brokenhearted and to announce that captives will be released and prisoners will be freed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 2, 'He has sent me to tell those who mourn that the time of the LORD''s favor has come, and with it, the day of God''s anger against their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 3, 'To all who mourn in Israel, he will give beauty for ashes, joy instead of mourning, praise instead of despair. For the LORD has planted them like strong and graceful oaks for his own glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 4, 'They will rebuild the ancient ruins, repairing cities long ago destroyed. They will revive them, though they have been empty for many generations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 5, 'Foreigners will be your servants. They will feed your flocks and plow your fields and tend your vineyards.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 6, 'You will be called priests of the LORD, ministers of our God. You will be fed with the treasures of the nations and will boast in their riches.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 7, 'Instead of shame and dishonor, you will inherit a double portion of prosperity and everlasting joy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 8, '"For I, the LORD, love justice. I hate robbery and wrongdoing. I will faithfully reward my people for their suffering and make an everlasting covenant with them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 9, 'Their descendants will be known and honored among the nations. Everyone will realize that they are a people the LORD has blessed."', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 10, 'I am overwhelmed with joy in the LORD my God! For he has dressed me with the clothing of salvation and draped me in a robe of righteousness. I am like a bridegroom in his wedding suit or a bride with her jewels.', 'NLT'),
(27, 61, 11, 'The Sovereign LORD will show his justice to the nations of the world. Everyone will praise him! His righteousness will be like a garden in early spring, filled with young plants springing up everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 1, 'Because I love Zion, because my heart yearns for Jerusalem, I cannot remain silent. I will not stop praying for her until her righteousness shines like the dawn, and her salvation blazes like a burning torch.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 2, 'The nations will see your righteousness. Kings will be blinded by your glory. And the LORD will give you a new name.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 3, 'The LORD will hold you in his hands for all to see--a splendid crown in the hands of God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 4, 'Never again will you be called the Godforsaken City or the Desolate Land. Your new name will be the City of God''s Delight and the Bride of God, for the LORD delights in you and will claim you as his own.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 5, 'Your children will care for you with joy, O Jerusalem, just as a young man cares for his bride. Then God will rejoice over you as a bridegroom rejoices over his bride.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 6, 'O Jerusalem, I have posted watchmen on your walls; they will pray to the LORD day and night for the fulfillment of his promises. Take no rest, all you who pray.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 7, 'Give the LORD no rest until he makes Jerusalem the object of praise throughout the earth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 8, 'The LORD has sworn to Jerusalem by his own strength: "I will never again hand you over to your enemies. Never again will foreign warriors come and take away your grain and wine.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 9, 'You raised it, and you will keep it, praising the LORD. Within the courtyards of the Temple, you yourselves will drink the wine that you have pressed."', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 10, 'Go out! Prepare the highway for my people to return! Smooth out the road; pull out the boulders; raise a flag for all the nations to see.', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 11, 'The LORD has sent this message to every land: "Tell the people of Israel, `Look, your Savior is coming. See, he brings his reward with him as he comes.''"', 'NLT'),
(27, 62, 12, 'They will be called the Holy People and the People Redeemed by the LORD. And Jerusalem will be known as the Desirable Place and the City No Longer Forsaken.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 1, 'Who is this who comes from Edom, from the city of Bozrah, with his clothing stained red? Who is this in royal robes, marching in the greatness of his strength? "It is I, the LORD, announcing your salvation! It is I, the LORD, who is mighty to save!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 2, 'Why are your clothes so red, as if you have been treading out grapes?', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 3, '"I have trodden the winepress alone; no one was there to help me. In my anger I have trampled my enemies as if they were grapes. In my fury I have trampled my foes. It is their blood that has stained my clothes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 4, 'For the time has come for me to avenge my people, to ransom them from their oppressors.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 5, 'I looked, but no one came to help my people. I was amazed and appalled at what I saw. So I executed vengeance alone; unaided, I passed down judgment.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 6, 'I crushed the nations in my anger and made them stagger and fall to the ground."', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 7, 'I will tell of the LORD''s unfailing love. I will praise the LORD for all he has done. I will rejoice in his great goodness to Israel, which he has granted according to his mercy and love.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 8, 'He said, "They are my very own people. Surely they will not be false again." And he became their Savior.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 9, 'In all their suffering he also suffered, and he personally rescued them. In his love and mercy he redeemed them. He lifted them up and carried them through all the years.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 10, 'But they rebelled against him and grieved his Holy Spirit. That is why he became their enemy and fought against them.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 11, 'Then they remembered those days of old when Moses led his people out of Egypt. They cried out, "Where is the one who brought Israel through the sea, with Moses as their shepherd? Where is the one who sent his Holy Spirit to be among his people?', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 12, 'Where is the one whose power divided the sea before them, when Moses lifted up his hand, establishing his reputation forever?', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 13, 'Where is the one who led them through the bottom of the sea? They were like fine stallions racing through the desert, never stumbling.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 14, 'As with cattle going down into a peaceful valley, the Spirit of the LORD gave them rest. You led your people, LORD, and gained a magnificent reputation."', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 15, 'LORD, look down from heaven and see us from your holy, glorious home. Where is the passion and the might you used to show on our behalf? Where are your mercy and compassion now?', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 16, 'Surely you are still our Father! Even if Abraham and Jacob would disown us, LORD, you would still be our Father. You are our Redeemer from ages past.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 17, 'LORD, why have you allowed us to turn from your path? Why have you given us stubborn hearts so we no longer fear you? Return and help us, for we are your servants and your special possession.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 18, 'How briefly your holy people possessed the holy place, and now our enemies have destroyed it.', 'NLT'),
(27, 63, 19, 'LORD, why do you treat us as though we never belonged to you? Why do you act as though we had never been known as your people?', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 1, 'Oh, that you would burst from the heavens and come down! How the mountains would quake in your presence!', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 2, 'As fire causes wood to burn and water to boil, your coming would make the nations tremble. Then your enemies would learn the reason for your fame!', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 3, 'When you came down long ago, you did awesome things beyond our highest expectations. And oh, how the mountains quaked!', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 4, 'For since the world began, no ear has heard, and no eye has seen a God like you, who works for those who wait for him!', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 5, 'You welcome those who cheerfully do good, who follow godly ways. But we are not godly. We are constant sinners, so your anger is heavy on us. How can people like us be saved?', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 6, 'We are all infected and impure with sin. When we proudly display our righteous deeds, we find they are but filthy rags. Like autumn leaves, we wither and fall. And our sins, like the wind, sweep us away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 7, 'Yet no one calls on your name or pleads with you for mercy. Therefore, you have turned away from us and turned us over to our sins.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 8, 'And yet, LORD, you are our Father. We are the clay, and you are the potter. We are all formed by your hand.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 9, 'Oh, don''t be so angry with us, LORD. Please don''t remember our sins forever. Look at us, we pray, and see that we are all your people.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 10, 'Your holy cities are destroyed; even Jerusalem is a desolate wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 11, 'The holy, beautiful Temple where our ancestors praised you has been burned down, and all the things of beauty are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 64, 12, 'After all this, LORD, must you still refuse to help us? Will you continue to be silent and punish us?', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 1, 'The LORD says, "People who never before inquired about me are now asking about me. I am being found by people who were not looking for me. To them I have said, `I am here!''', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 2, '"I opened my arms to my own people all day long, but they have rebelled. They follow their own evil paths and thoughts.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 3, 'All day long they insult me to my face by worshiping idols in their sacred gardens. They burn incense on the rooftops of their homes.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 4, 'At night they go out among the graves and secret places to worship evil spirits. They also eat pork and other forbidden foods.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 5, 'Yet they say to each other, `Don''t come too close or you will defile me! I am holier than you!'' They are a stench in my nostrils, an acrid smell that never goes away.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 6, '"Look, my decree is written out in front of me: I will not stand silent; I will repay them in full! Yes, I will repay them--', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 7, 'both for their own sins and for those of their ancestors," says the LORD. "For they also burned incense on the mountains and insulted me on the hills. I will pay them back in full!', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 8, '"But I will not destroy them all," says the LORD. "For just as good grapes are found among a cluster of bad ones (and someone will say, `Don''t throw them all away--there are some good grapes there!''), so I will not destroy all Israel. For I still have true servants there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 9, 'I will preserve a remnant of the people of Israel and of Judah to possess my land. Those I choose will inherit it and serve me there.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 10, 'For my people who have searched for me, the plain of Sharon will again be filled with flocks, and the valley of Achor will be a place to pasture herds.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 11, '"But because the rest of you have forsaken the LORD and his Temple and worship the gods of Fate and Destiny,', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 12, 'I will `destine'' you to the sword. All of you will bow before the executioner, for when I called, you did not answer. When I spoke, you did not listen. You deliberately sinned--before my very eyes--and chose to do what you know I despise."', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 13, 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: "You will starve, but my servants will eat. You will be thirsty, but they will drink. You will be sad and ashamed, but they will rejoice.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 14, 'You will cry in sorrow and despair, while my servants sing for joy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 15, 'Your name will be a curse word among my people, for the Sovereign LORD will destroy you and call his true servants by another name.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 16, 'All who invoke a blessing or take an oath will do so by the God of truth. For I will put aside my anger and forget the evil of earlier days.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 17, '"Look! I am creating new heavens and a new earth--so wonderful that no one will even think about the old ones anymore.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 18, 'Be glad; rejoice forever in my creation! And look! I will create Jerusalem as a place of happiness. Her people will be a source of joy.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 19, 'I will rejoice in Jerusalem and delight in my people. And the sound of weeping and crying will be heard no more.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 20, '"No longer will babies die when only a few days old. No longer will adults die before they have lived a full life. No longer will people be considered old at one hundred! Only sinners will die that young!', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 21, 'In those days, people will live in the houses they build and eat the fruit of their own vineyards.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 22, 'It will not be like the past, when invaders took the houses and confiscated the vineyards. For my people will live as long as trees and will have time to enjoy their hard-won gains.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 23, 'They will not work in vain, and their children will not be doomed to misfortune. For they are people blessed by the LORD, and their children, too, will be blessed.', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 24, 'I will answer them before they even call to me. While they are still talking to me about their needs, I will go ahead and answer their prayers!', 'NLT'),
(27, 65, 25, 'The wolf and lamb will feed together. The lion will eat straw like the ox. Poisonous snakes will strike no more. In those days, no one will be hurt or destroyed on my holy mountain. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 1, 'This is what the LORD says: "Heaven is my throne, and the earth is my footstool. Could you ever build me a temple as good as that? Could you build a dwelling place for me?', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 2, 'My hands have made both heaven and earth, and they are mine. I, the LORD, have spoken! "I will bless those who have humble and contrite hearts, who tremble at my word.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 3, 'But those who choose their own ways, delighting in their sins, are cursed. Their offerings will not be accepted. When such people sacrifice an ox, it is no more acceptable than a human sacrifice. When they sacrifice a lamb or bring an offering of grain, it is as bad as putting a dog or the blood of a pig on the altar! When they burn incense, it is as if they had blessed an idol.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 4, 'I will send great troubles against them--all the things they feared. For when I called, they did not answer. When I spoke, they did not listen. They deliberately sinned--before my very eyes--and chose to do what they know I despise."', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 5, 'Hear this message from the LORD, and tremble at his words: "Your close relatives hate you and throw you out for being loyal to my name. `Let the LORD be honored!'' they scoff. `Be joyful in him!'' But they will be put to shame.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 6, 'What is all the commotion in the city? What is that terrible noise from the Temple? It is the voice of the LORD taking vengeance against his enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 7, '"Before the birth pains even begin, Jerusalem gives birth to a son.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 8, 'Who has ever seen or heard of anything as strange as this? Has a nation ever been born in a single day? Has a country ever come forth in a mere moment? But by the time Jerusalem''s birth pains begin, the baby will be born; the nation will come forth.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 9, 'Would I ever bring this nation to the point of birth and then not deliver it?" asks the LORD. "No! I would never keep this nation from being born," says your God.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 10, '"Rejoice with Jerusalem! Be glad with her, all you who love her and mourn for her.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 11, 'Delight in Jerusalem! Drink deeply of her glory even as an infant drinks at its mother''s generous breasts.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 12, 'Peace and prosperity will overflow Jerusalem like a river," says the LORD. "The wealth of the nations will flow to her. Her children will be nursed at her breasts, carried in her arms, and treated with love.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 13, 'I will comfort you there as a child is comforted by its mother."', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 14, 'When you see these things, your heart will rejoice. Vigorous health will be yours! Everyone will see the good hand of the LORD on his people--and his anger against his enemies.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 15, 'See, the LORD is coming with fire, and his swift chariots of destruction roar like a whirlwind. He will bring punishment with the fury of his anger and the flaming fire of his hot rebuke.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 16, 'The LORD will punish the world by fire and by his sword, and many will be killed by the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 17, '"Those who `purify'' themselves in a sacred garden, feasting on pork and rats and other forbidden meats, will come to a terrible end," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 18, '"I can see what they are doing, and I know what they are thinking. So I will gather all nations and peoples together, and they will see my glory.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 19, 'I will perform a sign among them. And I will send those who survive to be messengers to the nations--to Tarshish, to the Libyans and Lydians (who are famous as archers), to Tubal and Greece, and to all the lands beyond the sea that have not heard of my fame or seen my glory. There they will declare my glory to the nations.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 20, 'They will bring the remnant of your people back from every nation. They will bring them to my holy mountain in Jerusalem as an offering to the LORD. They will ride on horses, in chariots and wagons, and on mules and camels," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 21, '"And I will appoint some of those who return to be my priests and Levites. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 22, '"As surely as my new heavens and earth will remain, so will you always be my people, with a name that will never disappear," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 23, '"All humanity will come to worship me from week to week and from month to month.', 'NLT'),
(27, 66, 24, 'And as they go out, they will see the dead bodies of those who have rebelled against me. For the worms that devour them will never die, and the fire that burns them will never go out. All who pass by will view them with utter horror."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 1, 'These are the words of Jeremiah son of Hilkiah, one of the priests from Anathoth, a town in the land of Benjamin.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 2, 'The LORD first gave messages to Jeremiah during the thirteenth year of King Josiah''s reign in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 3, 'He continued to give messages throughout the reign of Josiah''s son, King Jehoiakim, until the eleventh year of King Zedekiah''s reign in Judah. In August of that year, the people of Jerusalem were taken away as captives.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 4, 'The LORD gave me a message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 5, '"I knew you before I formed you in your mother''s womb. Before you were born I set you apart and appointed you as my spokesman to the world."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 6, '"O Sovereign LORD," I said, "I can''t speak for you! I''m too young!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 7, '"Don''t say that," the LORD replied, "for you must go wherever I send you and say whatever I tell you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 8, 'And don''t be afraid of the people, for I will be with you and take care of you. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 9, 'Then the LORD touched my mouth and said, "See, I have put my words in your mouth!', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 10, 'Today I appoint you to stand up against nations and kingdoms. You are to uproot some and tear them down, to destroy and overthrow them. You are to build others up and plant them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 11, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Look, Jeremiah! What do you see?" And I replied, "I see a branch from an almond tree."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 12, 'And the LORD said, "That''s right, and it means that I am watching, and I will surely carry out my threats of punishment."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 13, 'Then the LORD spoke to me again and asked, "What do you see now?" And I replied, "I see a pot of boiling water, tipping from the north."', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 14, '"Yes," the LORD said, "for terror from the north will boil out on the people of this land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 15, 'Listen! I am calling the armies of the kingdoms of the north to come to Jerusalem. They will set their thrones at the gates of the city. They will attack its walls and all the other towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 16, 'I will pronounce judgment on my people for all their evil--for deserting me and worshiping other gods. Yes, they worship idols that they themselves have made!', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 17, '"Get up and get dressed. Go out, and tell them whatever I tell you to say. Do not be afraid of them, or I will make you look foolish in front of them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 18, 'For see, today I have made you immune to their attacks. You are strong like a fortified city that cannot be captured, like an iron pillar or a bronze wall. None of the kings, officials, priests, or people of Judah will be able to stand against you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 1, 19, 'They will try, but they will fail. For I am with you, and I will take care of you. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 1, 'The LORD gave me another message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 2, '"Go and shout in Jerusalem''s streets: `This is what the LORD says: I remember how eager you were to please me as a young bride long ago, how you loved me and followed me even through the barren wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 3, 'In those days Israel was holy to the LORD, the first of my children. All who harmed my people were considered guilty, and disaster fell upon them. I, the LORD, have spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 4, 'Listen to the word of the LORD, people of Jacob--all you families of Israel!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 5, 'This is what the LORD says: "What sin did your ancestors find in me that led them to stray so far? They worshiped foolish idols, only to become foolish themselves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 6, 'They did not ask, `Where is the LORD who brought us safely out of Egypt and led us through the barren wilderness--a land of deserts and pits, of drought and death, where no one lives or even travels?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 7, '"And when I brought you into a fruitful land to enjoy its bounty and goodness, you defiled my land and corrupted the inheritance I had promised you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 8, 'The priests did not ask, `Where is the LORD?'' The judges ignored me, the rulers turned against me, and the prophets spoke in the name of Baal, wasting their time on nonsense.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 9, 'Therefore, I will bring my case against you and will keep on accusing you, even against your children''s children in the years to come. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 10, '"Go west to the land of Cyprus; go east to the land of Kedar. Think about what you see there. See if anyone has ever heard of anything as strange as this.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 11, 'Has any nation ever exchanged its gods for another god, even though its gods are nothing? Yet my people have exchanged their glorious God for worthless idols!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 12, 'The heavens are shocked at such a thing and shrink back in horror and dismay, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 13, 'For my people have done two evil things: They have forsaken me--the fountain of living water. And they have dug for themselves cracked cisterns that can hold no water at all!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 14, '"Why has Israel become a nation of slaves? Why has she been carried away as plunder?', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 15, 'Lions have roared against her. The land has been destroyed, and the cities are now in ruins. No one lives in them anymore.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 16, 'Egyptians, marching from their cities of Memphis and Tahpanhes, have utterly destroyed Israel''s glory and power.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 17, 'And you have brought this on yourselves by rebelling against the LORD your God when he wanted to lead you and show you the way!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 18, '"What have you gained by your alliances with Egypt and Assyria? What good to you are the waters of the Nile and the Euphrates?', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 19, 'Your own wickedness will punish you. You will see what an evil, bitter thing it is to forsake the LORD your God, having no fear of him. I, the Lord, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 20, 'Long ago I broke your yoke and tore away the chains of your slavery, but still you would not obey me. On every hill and under every green tree, you have prostituted yourselves by bowing down to idols.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 21, '"How could this happen? When I planted you, I chose a vine of the purest stock--the very best. How did you grow into this corrupt wild vine?', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 22, 'No amount of soap or lye can make you clean. You are stained with guilt that cannot be washed away. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 23, '"You say, `That''s not true! We haven''t worshiped the images of Baal!'' But how can you say that? Go and look in any valley in the land! Face the awful sins you have done. You are like a restless female camel, desperate for a male!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 24, 'You are like a wild donkey, sniffing the wind at mating time. Who can restrain your lust? Those who desire you do not even need to search, for you come running to them!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 25, 'Why do you refuse to turn from all this running after other gods? But you say, `Don''t waste your breath. I have fallen in love with these foreign gods, and I can''t stop loving them now!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 26, '"Like a thief, Israel feels shame only when she gets caught. Kings, officials, priests, and prophets--all are alike in this.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 27, 'To an image carved from a piece of wood they say, `You are my father.'' To an idol chiseled out of stone they say, `You are my mother.'' They turn their backs on me, but in times of trouble they cry out for me to save them!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 28, 'Why don''t you call on these gods you have made? When danger comes, let them save you if they can! For you have as many gods as there are cities and towns in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 29, 'Why do you accuse me of doing wrong? You are the ones who have rebelled, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 30, 'I have punished your children, but it did them no good. They still refuse to obey. You yourselves have killed your prophets as a lion kills its prey.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 31, '"O my people, listen to the words of the LORD! Have I been like a desert to Israel? Have I been to them a land of darkness? Why then do my people say, `At last we are free from God! We won''t have anything to do with him anymore!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 32, 'Does a young woman forget her jewelry? Does a bride hide her wedding dress? No! Yet for years on end my people have forgotten me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 33, '"How you plot and scheme to win your lovers. The most experienced prostitute could learn from you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 34, 'Your clothing is stained with the blood of the innocent and the poor. You killed them even though they didn''t break into your houses!', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 35, 'And yet you say, `I haven''t done anything wrong. Surely he isn''t angry with me!'' Now I will punish you severely because you claim you have not sinned.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 36, '"First here, then there--you flit from one ally to another asking for help. But your new friends in Egypt will let you down, just as Assyria did before.', 'NLT'),
(28, 2, 37, 'In despair, you will be led into exile with your hands on your heads, for the LORD has rejected the nations you trust. You will not succeed despite their help.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 1, '"If a man divorces a woman and she marries someone else, he is not to take her back again, for that would surely corrupt the land. But you have prostituted yourself with many lovers, says the LORD. Yet I am still calling you to come back to me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 2, '"Look all around you. Is there anywhere in the entire land where you have not been defiled by your adulteries? You sit like a prostitute beside the road waiting for a client. You sit alone like a nomad in the desert. You have polluted the land with your prostitution and wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 3, 'That is why even the spring rains have failed. For you are a prostitute and are completely unashamed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 4, 'Yet you say to me, `Father, you have been my guide since the days of my youth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 5, 'Surely you won''t be angry about such a little thing! Surely you can forget it!'' So you talk, and keep right on doing all the evil you can."', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 6, 'During the reign of King Josiah, the LORD said to me, "Have you seen what fickle Israel does? Like a wife who commits adultery, Israel has worshiped other gods on every hill and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 7, 'I thought that after she had done all this she would return to me. But she did not come back. And though her faithless sister Judah saw this,', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 8, 'she paid no attention. She saw that I had divorced faithless Israel and sent her away. But now Judah, too, has left me and given herself to prostitution.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 9, 'Israel treated it all so lightly--she thought nothing of committing adultery by worshiping idols made of wood and stone. So now the land has been greatly defiled.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 10, 'But in spite of all this, her faithless sister Judah has never sincerely returned to me. She has only pretended to be sorry," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 11, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Even faithless Israel is less guilty than treacherous Judah!', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 12, 'Therefore, go and say these words to Israel, `This is what the LORD says: O Israel, my faithless people, come home to me again, for I am merciful. I will not be angry with you forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 13, 'Only acknowledge your guilt. Admit that you rebelled against the LORD your God and committed adultery against him by worshiping idols under every green tree. Confess that you refused to follow me. I, the LORD, have spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 14, '"Return home, you wayward children," says the LORD, "for I am your husband. I will bring you again to the land of Israel--one from here and two from there, from wherever you are scattered.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 15, 'And I will give you leaders after my own heart, who will guide you with knowledge and understanding.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 16, '"And when your land is once more filled with people," says the LORD, "you will no longer wish for `the good old days'' when you possessed the Ark of the LORD''s covenant. Those days will not be missed or even thought about, and there will be no need to rebuild the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 17, 'In that day Jerusalem will be known as The Throne of the LORD. All nations will come there to honor the LORD. They will no longer stubbornly follow their own evil desires.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 18, 'In those days the people of Judah and Israel will return together from exile in the north. They will return to the land I gave their ancestors as an inheritance forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 19, '"I thought to myself, `I would love to treat you as my own children!'' I wanted nothing more than to give you this beautiful land--the finest inheritance in the world. I looked forward to your calling me `Father,'' and I thought you would never turn away from me again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 20, 'But you have betrayed me, you people of Israel! You have been like a faithless wife who leaves her husband," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 21, 'Voices are heard high on the windswept mountains, the weeping and pleading of Israel''s people. For they have forgotten the LORD their God and wandered far from his ways.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 22, '"My wayward children," says the LORD, "come back to me, and I will heal your wayward hearts.Yes, we will come," the people reply, "for you are the LORD our God.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 23, 'Our worship of idols and our religious orgies on the hills and mountains are completely false. Only in the LORD our God will Israel ever find salvation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 24, 'From childhood we have watched as everything our ancestors worked for--their flocks and herds, their sons and daughters--was squandered on a delusion.', 'NLT'),
(28, 3, 25, 'Let us now lie down in shame and dishonor, for we and our ancestors have always sinned against the LORD our God. We have never obeyed him."', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 1, '"O Israel, come back to me," says the LORD. "If you will throw away your detestable idols and go astray no more,', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 2, 'and if you will swear by my name alone, and begin to live good, honest lives and uphold justice, then you will be a blessing to the nations of the world, and all people will come and praise my name."', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 3, 'This is what the LORD says to the people of Judah and Jerusalem: "Plow up the hard ground of your hearts! Do not waste your good seed among thorns.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 4, 'Cleanse your minds and hearts before the LORD, or my anger will burn like an unquenchable fire because of all your sins.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 5, '"Shout to Jerusalem and to all Judah! Tell them to sound the alarm throughout the land: `Run for your lives! Flee to the fortified cities!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 6, 'Send a signal toward Jerusalem: `Flee now! Do not delay!'' For I am bringing terrible destruction upon you from the north."', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 7, 'A lion stalks from its den, a destroyer of nations. And it is headed for your land! Your towns will lie in ruins, empty of people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 8, 'So put on clothes of mourning and weep with broken hearts, for the fierce anger of the LORD is still upon us.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 9, '"In that day," says the LORD, "the king and the officials will tremble in fear. The priests and the prophets will be struck with horror."', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 10, 'Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, the people have been deceived by what you said, for you promised peace for Jerusalem. Yet the sword is even now poised to strike them dead!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 11, 'The time is coming when the LORD will say to the people of Jerusalem, "A burning wind is blowing in from the desert. It is not a gentle breeze useful for winnowing grain.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 12, 'It is a roaring blast sent by me! Now I will pronounce your destruction!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 13, 'Our enemy rushes down on us like a storm wind! His chariots are like whirlwinds; his horses are swifter than eagles. How terrible it will be! Our destruction is sure!', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 14, 'O Jerusalem, cleanse your hearts that you may be saved. How long will you harbor your evil thoughts?', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 15, 'From Dan and the hill country of Ephraim, your destruction has been announced.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 16, '"Warn the surrounding nations and announce to Jerusalem: `The enemy is coming from a distant land, raising a battle cry against the towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 17, 'They surround Jerusalem like watchmen surrounding a field, for my people have rebelled against me,''" says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 18, '"Your own actions have brought this upon you. This punishment is a bitter dose of your own medicine. It has pierced you to the heart!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 19, 'My heart, my heart--I writhe in pain! My heart pounds within me! I cannot be still. For I have heard the blast of enemy trumpets and the roar of their battle cries.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 20, 'Waves of destruction roll over the land, until it lies in complete desolation. Suddenly, every tent is destroyed; in a moment, every shelter is crushed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 21, 'How long must this go on? How long must I be surrounded by war and death?', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 22, '"My people are foolish and do not know me," says the LORD. "They are senseless children who have no understanding. They are clever enough at doing wrong, but they have no talent at all for doing right!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 23, 'I looked at the earth, and it was empty and formless. I looked at the heavens, and there was no light.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 24, 'I looked at the mountains and hills, and they trembled and shook.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 25, 'I looked, and all the people were gone. All the birds of the sky had flown away.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 26, 'I looked, and the fertile fields had become a wilderness. The cities lay in ruins, crushed by the LORD''s fierce anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 27, 'This is what the LORD says: "The whole land will be ruined, but I will not destroy it completely.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 28, 'The earth will mourn, the heavens will be draped in black, because of my decree against my people. I have made up my mind and will not change it."', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 29, 'At the noise of marching armies, the people flee in terror from the cities. They hide in the bushes and run for the mountains. All the cities have been abandoned--not a person remains!', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 30, 'What are you doing, you who have been plundered? Why do you dress up in your most beautiful clothing and jewelry? Why do you brighten your eyes with mascara? It will do you no good! Your allies despise you and will kill you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 4, 31, 'I hear a great cry, like that of a woman giving birth to her first child. It is the cry of Jerusalem''s people gasping for breath, pleading for help, prostrate before their murderers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 1, '"Run up and down every street in Jerusalem," says the LORD. "Look high and low; search throughout the city! If you can find even one person who is just and honest, I will not destroy the city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 2, 'Even when they are under oath, saying, `As surely as the LORD lives,'' they all tell lies!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 3, 'LORD, you are searching for honesty. You struck your people, but they paid no attention. You crushed them, but they refused to turn from sin. They are determined, with faces set like stone; they have refused to repent.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 4, 'Then I said, "But what can we expect from the poor and ignorant? They don''t know the ways of the LORD. They don''t understand what God expects of them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 5, 'I will go and speak to their leaders. Surely they will know the LORD''s ways and what God requires of them." But the leaders, too, had utterly rejected their God.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 6, 'So now a lion from the forest will attack them; a wolf from the desert will pounce on them. A leopard will lurk near their towns, tearing apart any who dare to venture out. For their rebellion is great, and their sins are many.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 7, '"How can I pardon you? For even your children have turned from me. They have sworn by gods that are not gods at all! I fed my people until they were fully satisfied. But they thanked me by committing adultery and lining up at the city''s brothels.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 8, 'They are well-fed, lusty stallions, each neighing for his neighbor''s wife.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 9, 'Should I not punish them for this?" asks the LORD. "Should I not avenge myself against a nation such as this?', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 10, '"Go down the rows of the vineyards and destroy them, but leave a scattered few alive. Strip the branches from the vine, for they do not belong to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 11, 'The people of Israel and Judah are full of treachery against me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 12, '"They have lied about the LORD and have said, `He won''t bother us! No disasters will come upon us! There will be no war or famine!', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 13, 'God''s prophets are windbags full of words with no divine authority. Their predictions of disaster will fall on themselves!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 14, 'Therefore, this is what the LORD God Almighty says: "Because the people are talking like this, I will give you messages that will burn them up as if they were kindling wood.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 15, 'O Israel, I will bring a distant nation against you," says the LORD. "It is a mighty nation, an ancient nation, a people whose language you do not know, whose speech you cannot understand.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 16, 'Their weapons are deadly; their warriors are mighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 17, 'They will eat your harvests and your children''s bread, your flocks of sheep and your herds of cattle. Yes, they will eat your grapes and figs. And they will destroy your fortified cities, which you think are so safe.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 18, '"Yet even in those days I will not blot you out completely," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 19, '"And when your people ask, `Why is the LORD our God doing this to us?'' you must reply, `You rejected him and gave yourselves to foreign gods in your own land. Now you will serve foreigners in a land that is not your own.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 20, '"Make this announcement to Israel and to Judah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 21, 'Listen, you foolish and senseless people--who have eyes but do not see, who have ears but do not hear.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 22, 'Do you have no respect for me? Why do you not tremble in my presence? I, the LORD, am the one who defines the ocean''s sandy shoreline, an everlasting boundary that the waters cannot cross. The waves may toss and roar, but they can never pass the bounds I set.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 23, '"But my people have stubborn and rebellious hearts. They have turned against me and have chosen to practice idolatry.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 24, 'They do not say from the heart, `Let us live in awe of the LORD our God, for he gives us rain each spring and fall, assuring us of plentiful harvests.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 25, 'Your wickedness has deprived you of these wonderful blessings. Your sin has robbed you of all these good things.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 26, '"Among my people are wicked men who lie in wait for victims like a hunter hiding in a blind. They are continually setting traps for other people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 27, 'Like a cage filled with birds, their homes are filled with evil plots. And the result? Now they are great and rich.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 28, 'They are well fed and well groomed, and there is no limit to their wicked deeds. They refuse justice to orphans and deny the rights of the poor.', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 29, 'Should I not punish them for this?" asks the LORD. "Should I not avenge myself against a nation such as this?', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 30, '"A horrible and shocking thing has happened in this land--', 'NLT'),
(28, 5, 31, 'the prophets give false prophecies, and the priests rule with an iron hand. And worse yet, my people like it that way! But what will you do when the end comes?', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 1, '"Run for your lives, you people of Benjamin! Flee from Jerusalem! Sound the alarm in Tekoa! Send up a signal at Beth-hakkerem! Warn everyone that a powerful army is coming from the north to destroy this nation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 2, 'O Jerusalem, you are my beautiful and delicate daughter--but I will destroy you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 3, 'Enemy shepherds will surround you. They will set up camp around the city and divide your pastures for their flocks.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 4, 'They shout, `Prepare for battle and attack at noon! But now the day is fading, and the evening shadows are falling.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 5, 'So let us attack by night and destroy her palaces!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 6, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "Cut down the trees for battering rams. Build ramps against the walls of Jerusalem. This is the city to be punished, for she is wicked through and through.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 7, 'She spouts evil like a fountain! Her streets echo with the sounds of violence and destruction. Her sickness and sores are ever before me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 8, 'This is your last warning, Jerusalem! If you do not listen, I will empty the land."', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 9, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "Disaster will fall upon you. Even the few who remain in Israel will be gleaned again, as when a harvester checks each vine a second time to pick the grapes that were missed."', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 10, 'To whom can I give warning? Who will listen when I speak? Their ears are closed, and they cannot hear. They scorn the word of the LORD. They don''t want to listen at all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 11, 'So now I am filled with the LORD''s fury. Yes, I am weary of holding it in! "I will pour out my fury over Jerusalem, even on children playing in the streets, on gatherings of young men, and on husbands and wives and grandparents.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 12, 'Their homes will be turned over to their enemies, and so will their fields and their wives. For I will punish the people of this land," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 13, '"From the least to the greatest, they trick others to get what does not belong to them. Yes, even my prophets and priests are like that!', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 14, 'They offer superficial treatments for my people''s mortal wound. They give assurances of peace when all is war.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 15, 'Are they ashamed when they do these disgusting things? No, not at all--they don''t even blush! Therefore, they will lie among the slaughtered. They will be humbled beneath my punishing anger," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 16, 'So now the LORD says, "Stop right where you are! Look for the old, godly way, and walk in it. Travel its path, and you will find rest for your souls. But you reply, `No, that''s not the road we want!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 17, 'I set watchmen over you who said, `Listen for the sound of the trumpet!'' But you replied, `No! We won''t pay attention!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 18, '"Therefore, listen to this, all you nations. Take note of my people''s condition.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 19, 'Listen, all the earth! I will bring disaster upon my people. It is the fruit of their own sin because they refuse to listen to me. They have rejected all my instructions.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 20, 'There is no use now in offering me sweet incense from Sheba. Keep your expensive perfumes! I cannot accept your burnt offerings. Your sacrifices have no sweet fragrance for me."', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 21, 'Therefore, this is what the LORD says: "I will put obstacles in my people''s path. Fathers and sons will both fall over them. Neighbors and friends will collapse together."', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 22, 'This is what the LORD says: "See a great army marching from the north! A great nation is rising against you from far-off lands.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 23, 'They are fully armed for slaughter. They are cruel and show no mercy. As they ride forward, the noise of their army is like a roaring sea. They are marching in battle formation to destroy you, Jerusalem. "', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 24, 'We have heard reports about the enemy, and we are weak with fright. Fear and pain have gripped us, like that of a woman about to give birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 25, 'Don''t go out to the fields! Don''t travel the roads! The enemy is everywhere, and they are ready to kill. We are terrorized at every turn!', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 26, 'Now my people, dress yourselves in sackcloth, and sit among the ashes. Mourn and weep bitterly, as for the loss of an only son. For suddenly, the destroying armies will be upon you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 27, '"Jeremiah, I have made you a tester of metals, that you may determine the quality of my people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 28, 'Are they not the worst of rebels, full of slander? They are as insolent as bronze, as hard and cruel as iron. All of them lead others into corruption.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 29, 'The bellows blow fiercely. The refining fire grows hotter. But it will never purify and cleanse them because there is no purity in them to refine.', 'NLT'),
(28, 6, 30, 'I will label them `Rejected Silver'' because I, the LORD, am discarding them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 1, 'The LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 2, '"Go to the entrance of the LORD''s Temple, and give this message to the people: `O Judah, listen to this message from the LORD! Listen to it, all of you who worship here!', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 3, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Even now, if you quit your evil ways, I will let you stay in your own land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 4, 'But do not be fooled by those who repeatedly promise your safety because the Temple of the LORD is here.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 5, 'I will be merciful only if you stop your wicked thoughts and deeds and are fair to others;', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 6, 'and if you stop exploiting foreigners, orphans, and widows; and if you stop your murdering; and if you stop worshiping idols as you now do to your own harm.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 7, 'Then I will let you stay in this land that I gave to your ancestors to keep forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 8, '" `Do you think that because the Temple is here you will never suffer? Don''t fool yourselves!', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 9, 'Do you really think you can steal, murder, commit adultery, lie, and worship Baal and all those other new gods of yours,', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 10, 'and then come here and stand before me in my Temple and chant, "We are safe!"--only to go right back to all those evils again?', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 11, 'Do you think this Temple, which honors my name, is a den of thieves? I see all the evil going on there, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 12, '" `Go to the place at Shiloh where I once put the Tabernacle to honor my name. See what I did there because of all the wickedness of my people, the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 13, 'While you were doing these wicked things, says the LORD, I spoke to you about it repeatedly, but you would not listen. I called out to you, but you refused to answer.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 14, 'So just as I destroyed Shiloh, I will now destroy this Temple that was built to honor my name, this Temple that you trust for help, this place that I gave to you and your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 15, 'And I will send you into exile, just as I did your relatives, the people of Israel. ''', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 16, '"Pray no more for these people, Jeremiah. Do not weep or pray for them, and don''t beg me to help them, for I will not listen to you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 17, 'Do you not see what they are doing throughout the towns of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 18, 'No wonder I am so angry! Watch how the children gather wood and the fathers build sacrificial fires. See how the women knead dough and make cakes to offer to the Queen of Heaven. And they give drink offerings to their other idol gods!', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 19, 'Am I the one they are hurting?" asks the LORD. "Most of all, they hurt themselves, to their own shame."', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 20, 'So the Sovereign LORD says: "I will pour out my terrible fury on this place. Its people, animals, trees, and crops will be consumed by the unquenchable fire of my anger."', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 21, 'This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "Away with your burnt offerings and sacrifices! Eat them yourselves!', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 22, 'When I led your ancestors out of Egypt, it was not burnt offerings and sacrifices I wanted from them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 23, 'This is what I told them: `Obey me, and I will be your God, and you will be my people. Only do as I say, and all will be well!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 24, '"But my people would not listen to me. They kept on doing whatever they wanted, following the stubborn desires of their evil hearts. They went backward instead of forward.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 25, 'From the day your ancestors left Egypt until now, I have continued to send my prophets--day in and day out.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 26, 'But my people have not listened to me or even tried to hear. They have been stubborn and sinful--even worse than their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 27, '"Tell them all this, but do not expect them to listen. Shout out your warnings, but do not expect them to respond.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 28, 'Say to them, `This is the nation whose people will not obey the LORD their God and who refuse to be taught. Truth has vanished from among them; it is no longer heard on their lips.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 29, 'O Jerusalem, shave your head in mourning, and weep alone on the mountains. For the LORD has rejected and forsaken this generation that has provoked his fury.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 30, '"The people of Judah have sinned before my very eyes," says the LORD. "They have set up their abominable idols right in my own Temple, defiling it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 31, 'They have built the pagan shrines of Topheth in the valley of the son of Hinnom, where they sacrifice their little sons and daughters in the fire. I have never commanded such a horrible deed; it never even crossed my mind to command such a thing!', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 32, 'So beware, for the time is coming," says the LORD, "when that place will no longer be called Topheth or the valley of the son of Hinnom, but the Valley of Slaughter. They will bury so many bodies in Topheth that there won''t be room for all the graves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 33, 'The corpses of my people will be food for the vultures and wild animals, and no one will be left to scare them away.', 'NLT'),
(28, 7, 34, 'I will put an end to the happy singing and laughter in the streets of Jerusalem. The joyful voices of bridegrooms and brides will no longer be heard in the towns of Judah. The land will lie in complete desolation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 1, '"In that day," says the LORD, "the enemy will break open the graves of the kings and officials of Judah, and the graves of the priests, prophets, and common people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 2, 'They will dig out their bones and spread them out on the ground before the sun, moon, and stars--the gods my people have loved, served, and worshiped. Their bones will not be gathered up again or buried but will be scattered on the ground like dung.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 3, 'And the people of this evil nation who survive will wish to die rather than live where I will send them. I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 4, '"Jeremiah, say to the people, `This is what the LORD says: When people fall down, don''t they get up again? When they start down the wrong road and discover their mistake, don''t they turn back?', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 5, 'Then why do these people keep going along their self-destructive path, refusing to turn back, even though I have warned them?', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 6, 'I listen to their conversations, and what do I hear? Is anyone sorry for sin? Does anyone say, "What a terrible thing I have done"? No! All are running down the path of sin as swiftly as a horse rushing into battle!', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 7, 'The stork knows the time of her migration, as do the turtledove, the swallow, and the crane. They all return at the proper time each year. But not my people! They do not know what the LORD requires of them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 8, '" `How can you say, "We are wise because we have the law of the LORD," when your teachers have twisted it so badly?', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 9, 'These wise teachers will be shamed by exile for their sin, for they have rejected the word of the LORD. Are they so wise after all?', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 10, 'I will give their wives and their farms to others. From the least to the greatest, they trick others to get what does not belong to them. Yes, even my prophets and priests are like that.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 11, 'They offer superficial treatments for my people''s mortal wound. They give assurances of peace when all is war.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 12, 'Are they ashamed when they do these disgusting things? No, not at all--they don''t even blush! Therefore, they will lie among the slaughtered. They will be humbled when they are punished, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 13, 'I will take away their rich harvests of figs and grapes. Their fruit trees will all die. All the good things I prepared for them will soon be gone. I, the LORD, have spoken!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 14, '"Then the people will say, `Why should we wait here to die? Come, let''s go to the fortified cities to die there. For the LORD our God has decreed our destruction and has given us a cup of poison to drink because we sinned against the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 15, 'We hoped for peace, but no peace came. We hoped for a time of healing, but found only terror.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 16, 'The snorting of the enemies'' warhorses can be heard all the way from the land of Dan in the north! The whole land trembles at the approach of the terrible army, for it is coming to devour the land and everything in it--cities and people alike.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 17, '"I will send these enemy troops among you like poisonous snakes you cannot charm," says the LORD. "No matter what you do, they will bite you, and you will die."', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 18, 'My grief is beyond healing; my heart is broken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 19, 'Listen to the weeping of my people; it can be heard all across the land. "Has the LORD abandoned Jerusalem?" the people ask. "Is her King no longer there?Oh, why have they angered me with their carved idols and worthless gods?" asks the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 20, '"The harvest is finished, and the summer is gone," the people cry, "yet we are not saved!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 21, 'I weep for the hurt of my people. I am stunned and silent, mute with grief.', 'NLT'),
(28, 8, 22, 'Is there no medicine in Gilead? Is there no physician there? Why is there no healing for the wounds of my people?', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 1, 'Oh, that my eyes were a fountain of tears; I would weep forever! I would sob day and night for all my people who have been slaughtered.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 2, 'Oh, that I could go away and forget them and live in a shack in the desert, for they are all adulterous and treacherous.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 3, '"My people bend their tongues like bows to shoot lies. They refuse to stand up for the truth. And they only go from bad to worse! They care nothing for me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 4, '"Beware of your neighbor! Beware of your brother! They all take advantage of one another and spread their slanderous lies.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 5, 'They all fool and defraud each other; no one tells the truth. With practiced tongues they tell lies; they wear themselves out with all their sinning.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 6, 'They pile lie upon lie and utterly refuse to come to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 7, 'Therefore, the LORD Almighty says, "See, I will melt them in a crucible and test them like metal. What else can I do with them?', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 8, 'For their tongues aim lies like poisoned arrows. They promise peace to their neighbors while planning to kill them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 9, 'Should I not punish them for this?" asks the LORD. "Should I not avenge myself against a nation such as this?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 10, 'I will weep for the mountains and wail for the desert pastures. For they are desolate and empty of life; the lowing of cattle is heard no more; the birds and wild animals all have fled.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 11, '"I will make Jerusalem into a heap of ruins," says the LORD. "It will be a place haunted by jackals. The towns of Judah will be ghost towns, with no one living in them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 12, 'Who is wise enough to understand all this? Who has been instructed by the LORD and can explain it to others? Why has the land been ruined so completely that no one even dares to travel through it?', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 13, 'The LORD replies, "This has happened because my people have abandoned the instructions I gave them; they have refused to obey my law.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 14, 'Instead, they have stubbornly followed their own desires and worshiped the images of Baal, as their ancestors taught them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 15, 'So now, listen to what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Look! I will feed them with bitterness and give them poison to drink.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 16, 'I will scatter them around the world, and they will be strangers in distant lands. Their enemies will chase them with the sword until I have destroyed them completely."', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 17, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "Think about what is going on! Call for the mourners to come.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 18, 'Quick! Begin your weeping! Let the tears flow from your eyes.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 19, 'Hear the people of Jerusalem crying in despair, `We are ruined! Disaster has come upon us! We must leave our land, because our homes have been torn down.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 20, 'Listen, you women, to the words of the LORD; open your ears to what he has to say. Teach your daughters to wail; teach one another how to lament.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 21, 'For death has crept in through our windows and has entered our mansions. It has killed off the flower of our youth: Children no longer play in the streets, and young men no longer gather in the squares.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 22, 'And the LORD says, "Bodies will be scattered across the fields like dung, or like bundles of grain after the harvest. No one will be left to bury them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 23, 'This is what the LORD says: "Let not the wise man gloat in his wisdom, or the mighty man in his might, or the rich man in his riches.', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 24, 'Let them boast in this alone: that they truly know me and understand that I am the LORD who is just and righteous, whose love is unfailing, and that I delight in these things. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 25, '"A time is coming," says the LORD, "when I will punish all those who are circumcised in body but not in spirit--', 'NLT'),
(28, 9, 26, 'the Egyptians, Edomites, Ammonites, Moabites, the people who live in distant places, and yes, even the people of Judah. Like all these pagan nations, the people of Israel also have uncircumcised hearts."', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 1, 'Hear the word of the LORD, O Israel!', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 2, 'This is what the LORD says: "Do not act like other nations who try to read their future in the stars. Do not be afraid of their predictions, even though other nations are terrified by them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 3, 'Their ways are futile and foolish. They cut down a tree and carve an idol.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 4, 'They decorate it with gold and silver and then fasten it securely with hammer and nails so it won''t fall over.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 5, 'There stands their god like a helpless scarecrow in a garden! It cannot speak, and it needs to be carried because it cannot walk. Do not be afraid of such gods, for they can neither harm you nor do you any good."', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 6, 'LORD, there is no one like you! For you are great, and your name is full of power.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 7, 'Who would not fear you, O King of nations? That title belongs to you alone! Among all the wise people of the earth and in all the kingdoms of the world, there is no one like you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 8, 'The wisest of people who worship idols are stupid and foolish. The things they worship are made of wood!', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 9, 'They bring beaten sheets of silver from Tarshish and gold from Uphaz, and they give these materials to skillful craftsmen who make their idols. Then they dress these gods in royal purple robes made by expert tailors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 10, 'But the LORD is the only true God, the living God. He is the everlasting King! The whole earth trembles at his anger. The nations hide before his wrath.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 11, 'Say this to those who worship other gods: "Your so-called gods, who did not make the heavens and earth, will vanish from the earth."', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 12, 'But God made the earth by his power, and he preserves it by his wisdom. He has stretched out the heavens by his understanding.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 13, 'When he speaks, there is thunder in the heavens. He causes the clouds to rise over the earth. He sends the lightning with the rain and releases the wind from his storehouses.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 14, 'Compared to him, all people are foolish and have no knowledge at all! They make idols, but the idols will disgrace their makers, for they are frauds. They have no life or power in them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 15, 'Idols are worthless; they are lies! The time is coming when they will all be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 16, 'But the God of Israel is no idol! He is the Creator of everything that exists, including Israel, his own special possession. The LORD Almighty is his name!', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 17, '"Pack your bag and prepare to leave; the siege is about to begin,"', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 18, 'says the LORD. "For suddenly, I will fling you from this land and pour great troubles upon you. At last you will feel my anger."', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 19, 'My wound is desperate, and my grief is great. My sickness is incurable, but I must bear it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 20, 'My home is gone, and no one is left to help me rebuild it. My children have been taken away, and I will never see them again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 21, 'The shepherds of my people have lost their senses. They no longer follow the LORD or ask what he wants of them. Therefore, they fail completely, and their flocks are scattered.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 22, 'Listen! Hear the terrifying roar of great armies as they roll down from the north. The towns of Judah will be destroyed and will become a haunt for jackals.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 23, 'I know, LORD, that a person''s life is not his own. No one is able to plan his own course.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 24, 'So correct me, LORD, but please be gentle. Do not correct me in anger, for I would die.', 'NLT'),
(28, 10, 25, 'Pour out your wrath on the nations that refuse to recognize you--on nations that do not call upon your name. For they have utterly devoured your people Israel, making the land a desolate wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 1, 'The LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 2, '"Remind the people of Judah and Jerusalem about the terms of their covenant with me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 3, 'Say to them, `This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Cursed is anyone who does not obey the terms of my covenant!', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 4, 'For I said to your ancestors when I brought them out of slavery in Egypt, "If you obey me and do whatever I command you, then you will be my people, and I will be your God."', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 5, 'I said this so I could keep my promise to your ancestors to give you a land flowing with milk and honey--the land you live in today.''" Then I replied, "So be it, LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 6, 'Then the LORD said, "Broadcast this message in the streets of Jerusalem. Go from town to town throughout the land and say, `Remember the covenant your ancestors made, and do everything they promised.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 7, 'For I solemnly warned your ancestors when I brought them out of Egypt, repeating over and over again to this day: "Obey me!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 8, 'But your ancestors did not pay any attention; they would not even listen. Instead, they stubbornly followed their own evil desires. And because they refused to obey, I brought upon them all the curses described in our covenant.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 9, 'Again the LORD spoke to me and said, "I have discovered a conspiracy against me among the people of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 10, 'They have returned to the sins of their forefathers. They have refused to listen to me and are worshiping idols. Israel and Judah have both broken the covenant I made with their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 11, 'Therefore, says the LORD, I am going to bring calamity upon them, and they will not escape. Though they beg for mercy, I will not listen to their cries.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 12, 'Then the people of Judah and Jerusalem will pray to their idols and offer incense before them. But the idols will not save them when disaster strikes!', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 13, 'Look now, people of Judah, you have as many gods as there are cities and towns. Your altars of shame--altars for burning incense to your god Baal--are along every street in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 14, '"Pray no more for these people, Jeremiah. Do not weep or pray for them, for I will not listen to them when they cry out to me in distress.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 15, 'What right do my beloved people have to come to my Temple, where they have done so many immoral things? Can their sacrifices avert their destruction? They actually rejoice in doing evil!', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 16, '"I, the LORD, once called them a thriving olive tree, beautiful to see and full of good fruit. But now I have sent the fury of their enemies to burn them with fire, leaving them charred and broken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 17, 'I, the LORD Almighty, who planted this olive tree, have ordered it destroyed. For the people of Israel and Judah have done evil, provoking my anger by offering incense to Baal."', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 18, 'Then the LORD told me about the plots my enemies were making against me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 19, 'I had been as unaware as a lamb on the way to its slaughter. I had no idea that they were planning to kill me! "Let''s destroy this man and all his words," they said. "Let''s kill him, so his name will be forgotten forever."', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 20, 'O LORD Almighty, you are just, and you examine the deepest thoughts of hearts and minds. Let me see your vengeance against them, for I have committed my cause to you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 21, 'The men of Anathoth wanted me dead. They said they would kill me if I did not stop speaking in the LORD''s name.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 22, 'So this is what the LORD Almighty says about them: "I will punish them! Their young men will die in battle, and their little boys and girls will starve.', 'NLT'),
(28, 11, 23, 'Not one of these plotters from Anathoth will survive, for I will bring disaster upon them when their time of punishment comes."', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 1, 'LORD, you always give me justice when I bring a case before you. Now let me bring you this complaint: Why are the wicked so prosperous? Why are evil people so happy?', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 2, 'You have planted them, and they have taken root and prospered. Your name is on their lips, but in their hearts they give you no credit at all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 3, 'But as for me, LORD, you know my heart. You see me and test my thoughts. Drag these people away like helpless sheep to be butchered! Set them aside to be slaughtered!', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 4, 'How long must this land weep? Even the grass in the fields has withered. The wild animals and birds have disappeared because of the evil in the land. Yet the people say, "The LORD won''t do anything!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 5, 'Then the LORD replied to me, "If racing against mere men makes you tired, how will you race against horses? If you stumble and fall on open ground, what will you do in the thickets near the Jordan?', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 6, 'Even your own brothers, members of your own family, have turned on you. They have plotted, raising a cry against you. Do not trust them, no matter how pleasantly they speak.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 7, '"I have abandoned my people, my special possession. I have surrendered my dearest ones to their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 8, 'My chosen people have roared at me like a lion of the forest, so I have treated them as though I hated them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 9, 'My chosen people have become as disgusting to me as a vulture. And indeed, they are surrounded by vultures. Bring on the wild beasts to pick their corpses clean!', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 10, '"Many rulers have ravaged my vineyard, trampling down the vines and turning all its beauty into a barren wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 11, 'They have made it an empty wasteland; I hear its mournful cry. The whole land is desolate, and no one even cares.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 12, 'Destroying armies plunder the land. The sword of the LORD kills people from one end of the nation to the other. No one will escape!', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 13, 'My people have planted wheat but are harvesting thorns. They have worked hard, but it has done them no good. They will harvest a crop of shame, for the fierce anger of the LORD is upon them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 14, 'Now this is what the LORD says: "As for all the evil nations reaching out for the inheritance I gave my people Israel, I will uproot them from their lands just as Judah will be uprooted from hers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 15, 'But afterward I will return and have compassion on all of them. I will bring them home to their own lands again, each nation to its own inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 16, 'And if these nations quickly learn the ways of my people, and if they learn to swear by my name, saying, `As surely as the LORD lives'' (just as they taught my people to swear by the name of Baal), then they will be given a place among my people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 12, 17, 'But any nation who refuses to obey me will be uprooted and destroyed. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 1, 'This is what the LORD said to me: "Go and buy a linen belt and put it around your waist, but do not wash it."', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 2, 'So I bought the belt as the LORD directed me and put it around my waist.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 3, 'Then the LORD gave me another message:', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 4, '"Take the linen belt you are wearing, and go to the Euphrates River. Hide it there in a hole in the rocks."', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 5, 'So I went and hid it at the Euphrates as the LORD had instructed me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 6, 'A long time afterward, the LORD said to me, "Go back to the Euphrates and get the linen belt that I told you to hide there."', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 7, 'So I went to the Euphrates and dug it out of the hole where I had hidden it. But now it was mildewed and falling apart. The belt was useless.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 8, 'Then I received this message from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 9, '"The LORD says: This illustrates how I will rot away the pride of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 10, 'These wicked people refuse to listen to me. They stubbornly follow their own desires and worship idols. Therefore, they will become like this linen belt--good for nothing!', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 11, 'As a belt clings to a person''s waist, so I created Judah and Israel to cling to me," says the LORD. "They were to be my people, my pride, my glory--an honor to my name. But they would not listen to me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 12, '"So tell them, `The LORD, the God of Israel, says: All your wineskins will be full of wine.'' And they will reply, `Of course, you don''t need to tell us how prosperous we will be!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 13, 'Then tell them, `No, this is what the LORD means: I will make everyone in this land so confused that they will seem drunk--from the king sitting on David''s throne and from the priests and the prophets, right on down to the common people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 14, 'I will smash them one against the other, even parents against children, says the LORD. I will not let my pity or mercy or compassion keep me from destroying them.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 15, 'Listen! Do not be proud, for the LORD has spoken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 16, 'Give glory to the LORD your God before it is too late. Acknowledge him before he brings darkness upon you, causing you to stumble and fall on the dark mountains. For then, when you look for light, you will find only terrible darkness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 17, 'And if you still refuse to listen, I will weep alone because of your pride. My eyes will overflow with tears because the LORD''s flock will be led away into exile.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 18, 'Say to the king and his mother, "Come down from your thrones and sit in the dust, for your glorious crowns will soon be snatched from your heads."', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 19, 'The towns of the Negev will close their gates, and no one will be able to open them. The people of Judah will be taken away as captives. They will all be carried into exile.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 20, 'See the armies marching down from the north! Where is your flock--your beautiful flock--that he gave you to care for?', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 21, 'How will you feel when the LORD sets your foreign allies over you as rulers? You will writhe in pain like a woman giving birth!', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 22, 'You may ask yourself, "Why is all this happening to me?" It is because of your many sins! That is why you have been raped and destroyed by invading armies.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 23, 'Can an Ethiopian change the color of his skin? Can a leopard take away its spots? Neither can you start doing good, for you always do evil.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 24, '"I will scatter you, just as chaff is scattered by the winds blowing in from the desert.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 25, 'This is your allotment, that which is due you," says the LORD. "I have measured it out especially for you, because you have forgotten me and put your trust in false gods.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 26, 'I myself will expose you to shame.', 'NLT'),
(28, 13, 27, 'I am keenly aware of your adultery and lust, and your abominable idol worship out in the fields and on the hills. Your destruction is sure, Jerusalem! How long will it be before you are pure?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 1, 'This message came to Jeremiah from the LORD, explaining why he was holding back the rain:', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 2, '"Judah wilts; her businesses have ground to a halt. All the people sit on the ground in mourning, and a great cry rises from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 3, 'The nobles send servants to get water, but all the wells are dry. The servants return with empty pitchers, confused and desperate, covering their heads in grief.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 4, 'The ground is parched and cracked for lack of rain. The farmers are afraid; they, too, cover their heads.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 5, 'The deer abandons her newborn fawn because there is no grass.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 6, 'The wild donkeys stand on the bare hills panting like thirsty jackals. They strain their eyes looking for grass to eat, but there is none to be found."', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 7, 'The people say, "LORD, our wickedness has caught up with us. We have sinned against you. So please, help us for the sake of your own reputation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 8, 'O Hope of Israel, our Savior in times of trouble! Why are you like a stranger to us? Why are you like someone passing through the land, stopping only for the night?', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 9, 'Are you also confused? Are you helpless to save us? You are right here among us, LORD. We are known as your people. Please don''t abandon us now!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 10, 'So the LORD replies to his people, "You love to wander far from me and do not follow in my paths. Now I will no longer accept you as my people. I will remember all your wickedness and will punish you for your sins."', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 11, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Do not pray for these people anymore.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 12, 'When they fast in my presence, I will pay no attention. When they present their burnt offerings and grain offerings to me, I will not accept them. In return, I will give them only war, famine, and disease."', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 13, 'Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, their prophets are telling them, `All is well--no war or famine will come. The LORD will surely send you peace.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 14, 'Then the LORD said, "These prophets are telling lies in my name. I did not send them or tell them to speak. I did not give them any messages. They prophesy of visions and revelations they have never seen or heard. They speak foolishness made up in their own lying hearts.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 15, 'Therefore, says the LORD, I will punish these lying prophets, for they have spoken in my name even though I never sent them. They say that no war or famine will come, but they themselves will die by war and famine!', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 16, 'As for the people to whom they prophesy--their bodies will be thrown out into the streets of Jerusalem, victims of famine and war. There will be no one left to bury them. Husbands, wives, sons, and daughters--all will be gone. For I will pour out their own wickedness on them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 17, '"Now, Jeremiah, say this to them: `Night and day my eyes overflow with tears. I cannot stop weeping, for my virgin daughter--my precious people--has been run through with a sword and lies mortally wounded on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 18, 'If I go out into the fields, I see the bodies of people slaughtered by the enemy. If I walk the city streets, there I see people who have died of starvation. The prophets and priests continue with their work, but they do not know what they are doing.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 19, 'LORD, have you completely rejected Judah? Do you really hate Jerusalem? Why have you wounded us past all hope of healing? We hoped for peace, but no peace came. We hoped for a time of healing but found only terror.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 20, 'LORD, we confess our wickedness and that of our ancestors, too. We all have sinned against you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 21, 'For the sake of your own name, LORD, do not abandon us. Do not disgrace yourself and the throne of your glory. Do not break your covenant with us. Please don''t forget us!', 'NLT'),
(28, 14, 22, 'Can any of the foreign gods send us rain? Does it fall from the sky by itself? No, it comes from you, the LORD our God! Only you can do such things. So we will wait for you to help us.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 1, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Even if Moses and Samuel stood before me pleading for these people, I wouldn''t help them. Away with them! Get them out of my sight!', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 2, 'And if they say to you, `But where can we go?'' tell them, `This is what the LORD says: Those who are destined for death, to death; those who are destined for war, to war; those who are destined for famine, to famine; those who are destined for captivity, to captivity.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 3, '"I will send four kinds of destroyers against them," says the LORD. "I will send the sword to kill, the dogs to drag away, the vultures to devour, and the wild animals to finish up what is left.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 4, 'Because of the wicked things Manasseh son of Hezekiah, king of Judah, did in Jerusalem, I will make my people an object of horror to all the kingdoms of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 5, '"Who will feel sorry for you, Jerusalem? Who will weep for you? Who will even bother to ask how you are?', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 6, 'You have forsaken me and turned your back on me," says the LORD. "Therefore, I will raise my clenched fists to destroy you. I am tired of always giving you another chance.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 7, 'I will winnow you like grain at the gates of your cities and take away everything you hold dear. I will destroy my own people, because they refuse to turn back to me from all their evil ways.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 8, '"There will be more widows than the grains of sand along the seashore. At noontime I will bring a destroyer against the mothers of young men. I will cause anguish and terror to come upon them suddenly.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 9, 'The mother of seven grows faint and gasps for breath; her sun has gone down while it is yet day. She sits childless now, disgraced and humiliated. And those who are left, I will hand over to the enemy to be killed," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 10, 'Then I said, "What sadness is mine, my mother. Oh, that I had died at birth! I am hated everywhere I go. I am neither a lender who has threatened to foreclose nor a borrower who refuses to pay--yet they all curse me."', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 11, 'The LORD replied, "All will be well with you, Jeremiah. Your enemies will ask you to plead on their behalf in times of trouble and distress.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 12, 'Can a man break a bar of iron from the north, or a bar of bronze?', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 13, 'Because of all my people''s sins against me, I will hand over their wealth and treasures as plunder to the enemy.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 14, 'I will tell their enemies to take them as captives to a foreign land. For my anger blazes forth like fire, and it will consume them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 15, 'Then I said, "LORD, you know I am suffering for your sake. Punish my persecutors! Don''t let them kill me! Be merciful to me and give them what they deserve!', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 16, 'Your words are what sustain me. They bring me great joy and are my heart''s delight, for I bear your name, O LORD God Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 17, 'I never joined the people in their merry feasts. I sat alone because your hand was on me. I burst with indignation at their sins.', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 18, 'Why then does my suffering continue? Why is my wound so incurable? Your help seems as uncertain as a seasonal brook. It is like a spring that has gone dry."', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 19, 'The LORD replied, "If you return to me, I will restore you so you can continue to serve me. If you speak words that are worthy, you will be my spokesman. You are to influence them; do not let them influence you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 20, 'They will fight against you like an attacking army, but I will make you as secure as a fortified wall. They will not conquer you, for I will protect and deliver you. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 15, 21, 'Yes, I will certainly keep you safe from these wicked men. I will rescue you from their cruel hands."', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 1, 'The LORD gave me another message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 2, '"Do not marry or have children in this place.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 3, 'For this is what the LORD says about the children born here in this city and about their mothers and fathers:', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 4, 'They will die from terrible diseases. No one will mourn for them or bury them, and they will lie scattered on the ground like dung. They will die from war and famine, and their bodies will be food for the vultures and wild animals.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 5, '"Do not go to their funerals to mourn and show sympathy for them," says the LORD, "for I have removed my protection and peace from them. I have taken away my unfailing love and my mercy.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 6, 'Both the great and the lowly will die in this land. No one will bury them or mourn for them. Their friends will not cut themselves or shave their heads in sadness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 7, 'No one will offer a meal to comfort those who mourn for the dead--not even for the death of a mother or a father. No one will send a cup of wine to console them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 8, '"And do not go to their feasts and parties. Do not eat and drink with them at all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 9, 'For the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: In your own lifetime, before your very eyes, I will put an end to the happy singing and laughter in this land. The joyful voices of bridegrooms and brides will no longer be heard.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 10, '"When you tell the people all these things, they will ask, `Why has the LORD decreed such terrible things against us? What have we done to deserve such treatment? What is our sin against the LORD our God?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 11, 'Tell them that this is the LORD''s reply: It is because your ancestors were unfaithful to me. They worshiped other gods and served them. They abandoned me. They did not keep my law.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 12, 'And you are even worse than your ancestors! You stubbornly follow your own evil desires and refuse to listen to me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 13, 'So I will throw you out of this land and send you into a foreign land where you and your ancestors have never been. There you can worship idols all you like--and I will grant you no favors!', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 14, '"But the time is coming," says the LORD, "when people who are taking an oath will no longer say, `As surely as the LORD lives, who rescued the people of Israel from the land of Egypt.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 15, 'Instead, they will say, `As surely as the LORD lives, who brought the people of Israel back to their own land from the land of the north and from all the countries to which he had exiled them.'' For I will bring them back to this land that I gave their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 16, '"But now I am sending for many fishermen who will catch them," says the LORD. "I am sending for hunters who will search for them in the forests and caves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 17, 'I am watching them closely, and I see every sin. They cannot hope to hide from me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 18, 'I will punish them doubly for all their sins, because they have defiled my land with lifeless images of their detestable gods and filled my inheritance with their evil deeds."', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 19, 'LORD, you are my strength and fortress, my refuge in the day of trouble! Nations from around the world will come to you and say, "Our ancestors were foolish, for they worshiped worthless idols.', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 20, 'Can people make their own god? The gods they make are not real gods at all!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 16, 21, '"So now I will show them my power and might," says the LORD. "At last they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 1, 'The LORD says, "My people act as though their evil ways are laws to be obeyed, inscribed with a diamond point on their stony hearts, or with an iron chisel on the corners of their altars.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 2, 'Even their children go to worship at their sacred altars and Asherah poles, beneath every green tree and on every high hill.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 3, 'So I will give all your wealth and treasures--together with your pagan shrines--as plunder to your enemies, for sin runs rampant in your land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 4, 'The wonderful inheritance I have reserved for you will slip out of your hands, and I will send you away as captives to a foreign land. For you have kindled my anger into a roaring fire that will burn forever."', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 5, 'This is what the LORD says: "Cursed are those who put their trust in mere humans and turn their hearts away from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 6, 'They are like stunted shrubs in the desert, with no hope for the future. They will live in the barren wilderness, on the salty flats where no one lives.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 7, '"But blessed are those who trust in the LORD and have made the LORD their hope and confidence.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 8, 'They are like trees planted along a riverbank, with roots that reach deep into the water. Such trees are not bothered by the heat or worried by long months of drought. Their leaves stay green, and they go right on producing delicious fruit.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 9, '"The human heart is most deceitful and desperately wicked. Who really knows how bad it is?', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 10, 'But I know! I, the LORD, search all hearts and examine secret motives. I give all people their due rewards, according to what their actions deserve."', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 11, 'Like a bird that hatches eggs she has not laid, so are those who get their wealth by unjust means. Sooner or later they will lose their riches and, at the end of their lives, will become poor old fools.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 12, 'But we worship at your throne--eternal, high, and glorious!', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 13, 'O LORD, the hope of Israel, all who turn away from you will be disgraced and shamed. They will be buried in a dry and dusty grave, for they have forsaken the LORD, the fountain of living water.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 14, 'O LORD, you alone can heal me; you alone can save. My praises are for you alone!', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 15, 'People scoff at me and say, "What is this `message from the LORD'' you keep talking about? Why don''t your predictions come true?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 16, 'LORD, I have not abandoned my job as a shepherd for your people. I have not urged you to send disaster. It is your message I have given them, not my own.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 17, 'LORD, do not desert me now! You alone are my hope in the day of disaster.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 18, 'Bring shame and terror on all who persecute me, but give me peace. Yes, bring double destruction upon them!', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 19, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Go and stand in the gates of Jerusalem, first at the gate where the king goes out, and then at each of the other gates.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 20, 'Say to all the people, `Listen to this message from the LORD, you kings of Judah and all you people of Judah and everyone living in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 21, 'This is what the LORD says: Listen to my warning and live! Stop carrying on your trade at Jerusalem''s gates on the Sabbath day.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 22, 'Do not do your work on the Sabbath, but make it a holy day. I gave this command to your ancestors,', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 23, 'but they did not listen or obey. They stubbornly refused to pay attention and would not respond to discipline.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 24, '" `But if you obey me, says the LORD, and do not carry on your trade or work on the Sabbath day, and if you keep it holy,', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 25, 'then this nation will continue forever. There will always be a descendant of David sitting on the throne here in Jerusalem. Kings and their officials will always ride among the people of Judah in chariots and on horses, and this city will remain forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 26, 'And from all around Jerusalem, from the towns of Judah and Benjamin, from the western foothills and the hill country and the Negev, the people will come with their burnt offerings and sacrifices. They will bring their grain offerings, incense, and thanksgiving offerings to the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 17, 27, '" `But if you do not listen to me and refuse to keep the Sabbath holy, and if on the Sabbath day you bring loads of merchandise through the gates of Jerusalem just as on other days, then I will set fire to these gates. The fire will spread to the palaces, and no one will be able to put out the roaring flames.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 1, 'The LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 2, '"Go down to the shop where clay pots and jars are made. I will speak to you while you are there."', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 3, 'So I did as he told me and found the potter working at his wheel.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 4, 'But the jar he was making did not turn out as he had hoped, so the potter squashed the jar into a lump of clay and started again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 5, 'Then the LORD gave me this message:', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 6, '"O Israel, can I not do to you as this potter has done to his clay? As the clay is in the potter''s hand, so are you in my hand.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 7, 'If I announce that a certain nation or kingdom is to be uprooted, torn down, and destroyed,', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 8, 'but then that nation renounces its evil ways, I will not destroy it as I had planned.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 9, 'And if I announce that I will build up and plant a certain nation or kingdom, making it strong and great,', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 10, 'but then that nation turns to evil and refuses to obey me, I will not bless that nation as I had said I would.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 11, '"Therefore, Jeremiah, go and warn all Judah and Jerusalem. Say to them, `This is what the LORD says: I am planning disaster against you instead of good. So turn from your evil ways, each of you, and do what is right.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 12, 'But they replied, "Don''t waste your breath. We will continue to live as we want to, following our own evil desires."', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 13, 'Then the LORD said, "Has anyone ever heard of such a thing, even among the pagan nations? My virgin Israel has done something too terrible to understand!', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 14, 'Does the snow ever melt high up in the mountains of Lebanon? Do the cold, flowing streams from the crags of Mount Hermon ever run dry?', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 15, 'These can be counted on, but not my people! For they have deserted me and turned to worthless idols. They have stumbled off the ancient highways of good, and they walk the muddy paths of sin.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 16, 'Therefore, their land will become desolate, a monument to their stupidity. All who pass by will be astonished and shake their heads in amazement at its utter desolation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 17, 'I will scatter my people before their enemies as the east wind scatters dust. And in all their trouble I will turn my back on them and refuse to notice their distress."', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 18, 'Then the people said, "Come on, let''s find a way to stop Jeremiah. We have our own priests and wise men and prophets. We don''t need him to teach the law and give us advice and prophecies. Let''s spread rumors about him and ignore what he says."', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 19, 'LORD, help me! Listen to what they are planning to do to me!', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 20, 'Should they repay evil for good? They have set a trap to kill me, though I pleaded for them and tried to protect them from your anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 21, 'So let their children starve! Let the sword pour out their blood! Let their wives become widows without any children! Let their old men die in a plague, and let their young men be killed in battle!', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 22, 'Let screaming be heard from their homes as warriors come suddenly upon them. For they have dug a pit for me, and they have hidden traps along my path.', 'NLT'),
(28, 18, 23, 'LORD, you know all about their murderous plots against me. Don''t forgive their crimes and blot out their sins. Let them die before you. Deal with them in your anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 1, 'The LORD said to me, "Go and buy a clay jar. Then ask some of the leaders of the people and of the priests to follow you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 2, 'Go out into the valley of the son of Hinnom by the entrance to the Potsherd Gate, and repeat to them the words that I give you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 3, 'Say to them, `Listen to this message from the LORD, you kings of Judah and citizens of Jerusalem! This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I will bring such a terrible disaster on this place that the ears of those who hear about it will ring!', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 4, '" `For Israel has forsaken me and turned this valley into a place of wickedness. The people burn incense to foreign gods--idols never before worshiped by this generation, by their ancestors, or by the kings of Judah. And they have filled this place with the blood of innocent children.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 5, 'They have built pagan shrines to Baal, and there they burn their sons as sacrifices to Baal. I have never commanded such a horrible deed; it never even crossed my mind to command such a thing!', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 6, 'So beware, for the time is coming, says the LORD, when this place will no longer be called Topheth or the valley of the son of Hinnom, but the Valley of Slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 7, 'For I will upset the battle plans of Judah and Jerusalem and let invading armies slaughter them. The enemy will leave the dead bodies as food for the vultures and wild animals.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 8, 'I will wipe Jerusalem from the face of the earth, making it a monument to their stupidity. All who pass by will be appalled and will gasp at the destruction they see there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 9, 'I will see to it that your enemies lay siege to the city until all the food is gone. Then those trapped inside will have to eat their own sons and daughters and friends. They will be driven to utter despair.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 10, '"As these men watch, Jeremiah, smash the jar you brought with you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 11, 'Then say to them, `This is what the LORD Almighty says: As this jar lies shattered, so I will shatter the people of Judah and Jerusalem beyond all hope of repair. They will bury the bodies in Topheth until there is no more room.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 12, 'This is what I will do to this place and its people, says the LORD. I will cause this city to become defiled like Topheth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 13, 'Yes, all the houses in Jerusalem, including the palace of Judah''s kings, will become like Topheth--all the houses where you burned incense on the rooftops to your star gods, and where drink offerings were poured out to your idols.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 14, 'Then Jeremiah returned from Topheth where he had delivered this message, and he stopped in front of the Temple of the LORD. He said to the people there,', 'NLT'),
(28, 19, 15, '"This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I will bring disaster upon this city and its surrounding towns just as I promised, because you have stubbornly refused to listen to me."', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 1, 'Now Pashhur son of Immer, the priest in charge of the Temple of the LORD, heard what Jeremiah was saying.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 2, 'So he arrested Jeremiah the prophet and had him whipped and put in stocks at the Benjamin Gate of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 3, 'The next day, when Pashhur finally released him, Jeremiah said, "Pashhur, the LORD has changed your name. From now on you are to be called `The Man Who Lives in Terror.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 4, 'For this is what the LORD says: I will send terror upon you and all your friends, and you will watch as they are slaughtered by the swords of the enemy. I will hand the people of Judah over to the king of Babylon. He will take them captive to Babylon or run them through with the sword.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 5, 'And I will let your enemies plunder Jerusalem. All the famed treasures of the city--the precious jewels and gold and silver of your kings--will be carried off to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 6, 'As for you, Pashhur, you and all your household will go as captives to Babylon. There you will die and be buried, you and all your friends to whom you promised that everything would be all right."', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 7, 'O LORD, you persuaded me, and I allowed myself to be persuaded. You are stronger than I am, and you overpowered me. Now I am mocked by everyone in the city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 8, 'Whenever I speak, the words come out in a violent outburst. "Violence and destruction!" I shout. So these messages from the LORD have made me a household joke.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 9, 'And I can''t stop! If I say I''ll never mention the LORD or speak in his name, his word burns in my heart like a fire. It''s like a fire in my bones! I am weary of holding it in!', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 10, 'I have heard the many rumors about me. They call me "The Man Who Lives in Terror." And they say, "If you say anything, we will report it." Even my old friends are watching me, waiting for a fatal slip. "He will trap himself," they say, "and then we will get our revenge on him."', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 11, 'But the LORD stands beside me like a great warrior. Before him they will stumble. They cannot defeat me. They will be shamed and thoroughly humiliated. Their dishonor will never be forgotten.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 12, 'O LORD Almighty! You know those who are righteous, and you examine the deepest thoughts of hearts and minds. Let me see your vengeance against them, for I have committed my cause to you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 13, 'Now I will sing out my thanks to the LORD! Praise the LORD! For though I was poor and needy, he delivered me from my oppressors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 14, 'Yet I curse the day I was born! May the day of my birth not be blessed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 15, 'I curse the messenger who told my father, "Good news--you have a son!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 16, 'Let him be destroyed like the cities of old that the LORD overthrew without mercy. Terrify him all day long with battle shouts,', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 17, 'for he did not kill me at birth. Oh, that I had died in my mother''s womb, that her body had been my grave!', 'NLT'),
(28, 20, 18, 'Why was I ever born? My entire life has been filled with trouble, sorrow, and shame.', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 1, 'The LORD spoke through Jeremiah when King Zedekiah sent Pashhur son of Malkijah and Zephaniah son of Maaseiah, the priest, to speak with him. They begged Jeremiah,', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 2, '"Please ask the LORD to help us. King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon has begun his attack on Judah. Perhaps the LORD will be gracious and do a mighty miracle as he has done in the past. Perhaps he will force Nebuchadnezzar to withdraw his armies."', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 3, 'Jeremiah replied, "Go back to King Zedekiah and tell him,', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 4, '`This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I will make your weapons useless against the king of Babylon and the Babylonians who are attacking you. Yes, I will bring your enemies right into the heart of this city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 5, 'I myself will fight against you with great power, for I am very angry. You have made me furious!', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 6, 'I will send a terrible plague upon this city, and both people and animals will die.', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 7, 'And then, says the LORD, even after King Zedekiah, his officials, and everyone else in the city have survived war, famine, and disease, I will hand them over to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon. He will slaughter them all without mercy, pity, or compassion.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 8, '"Tell all the people, `This is what the LORD says: Take your choice of life or death!', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 9, 'Everyone who stays in Jerusalem will die from war, famine, or disease, but those who go out and surrender to the Babylonians will live.', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 10, 'For I have decided to bring disaster and not good upon this city, says the LORD. It will be captured by the king of Babylon, and he will reduce it to ashes.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 11, '"Say to the royal family of Judah, `Listen to this message from the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 12, 'This is what the LORD says to the dynasty of David: Give justice to the people you judge! Help those who have been robbed; rescue them from their oppressors. Do what is right, or my anger will burn like an unquenchable fire because of all your sins.', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 13, 'I will fight against this city of Jerusalem that boasts, "We are safe on our mountain! No one can touch us here."', 'NLT'),
(28, 21, 14, 'And I myself will punish you for your sinfulness, says the LORD. I will light a fire in your forests that will burn up everything around you.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 1, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Go over and speak directly to the king of Judah. Say to him,', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 2, '`Listen to this message from the LORD, you king of Judah, sitting on David''s throne. Let your officials and your people listen, too.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 3, 'This is what the LORD says: Be fair-minded and just. Do what is right! Help those who have been robbed; rescue them from their oppressors. Quit your evil deeds! Do not mistreat foreigners, orphans, and widows. Stop murdering the innocent!', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 4, 'If you obey me, there will always be a descendant of David sitting on the throne here in Jerusalem. The king will ride through the palace gates in chariots and on horses, with his parade of officials and subjects.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 5, 'But if you refuse to pay attention to this warning, I swear by my own name, says the LORD, that this palace will become a pile of rubble.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 6, 'Now this is what the LORD says concerning the royal palace: "You are as beloved to me as fruitful Gilead and the green forests of Lebanon. But I will destroy you and leave you deserted, with no one living within your walls.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 7, 'I will call for wreckers, who will bring out their tools to dismantle you. They will tear out all your fine cedar beams and throw them on the fire.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 8, 'People from many nations will pass by the ruins of this city and say to one another, `Why did the LORD destroy such a great city?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 9, 'And the answer will be, `Because they violated their covenant with the LORD their God by worshiping other gods.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 10, 'Do not weep for the dead king or mourn his loss. Instead, weep for the captive king being led away! For he will never return to see his native land again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 11, 'For this is what the LORD says about Jehoahaz, who succeeded his father, King Josiah, and was taken away as a captive: "He will never return.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 12, 'He will die in a distant land and never again see his own country."', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 13, 'And the LORD says, "Destruction is certain for Jehoiakim, who builds his palace with forced labor. By not paying wages, he builds injustice into its walls and oppression into its doorframes and ceilings.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 14, 'He says, `I will build a magnificent palace with huge rooms and many windows, paneled throughout with fragrant cedar and painted a lovely red.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 15, '"But a beautiful palace does not make a great king! Why did your father, Josiah, reign so long? Because he was just and right in all his dealings. That is why God blessed him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 16, 'He made sure that justice and help were given to the poor and needy, and everything went well for him. Isn''t that what it means to know me?" asks the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 17, '"But you! You are full of selfish greed and dishonesty! You murder the innocent, oppress the poor, and reign ruthlessly."', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 18, 'Therefore, this is the LORD''s decree of punishment against King Jehoiakim, who succeeded his father, Josiah, on the throne: "His family will not weep for him when he dies. His subjects will not even care that he is dead.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 19, 'He will be buried like a dead donkey--dragged out of Jerusalem and dumped outside the gate!', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 20, 'Weep, for your allies are all gone. Search for them in Lebanon. Shout for them at Bashan. Search for them in the regions east of the river. See, they are all destroyed. Not one is left to help you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 21, '"When you were prosperous, I warned you, but you replied, `Don''t bother me.'' Since childhood you have been that way--you simply will not listen!', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 22, 'And now your allies have all disappeared with a puff of wind. All your friends have been taken away as captives. Surely at last you will see your wickedness and be ashamed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 23, 'It may be nice to live in a beautiful palace lined with lumber from the cedars of Lebanon, but soon you will cry and groan in anguish--anguish like that of a woman about to give birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 24, '"And as surely as I live," says the LORD, "I will abandon you, Jehoiachin son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah. Even if you were the signet ring on my right hand, I would pull you off.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 25, 'I will hand you over to those who seek to kill you, of whom you are so desperately afraid--to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon and the mighty Babylonian army.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 26, 'I will expel you and your mother from this land, and you will die in a foreign country.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 27, 'You will never again return to the land of your desire.', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 28, '"Why is this man Jehoiachin like a discarded, broken dish? Why are he and his children to be exiled to distant lands?', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 29, 'O earth, earth, earth! Listen to this message from the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(28, 22, 30, 'This is what the LORD says: Let the record show that this man Jehoiachin was childless, for none of his children will ever sit on the throne of David to rule in Judah. His life will amount to nothing."', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 1, '"I will send disaster upon the leaders of my people--the shepherds of my sheep--for they have destroyed and scattered the very ones they were expected to care for," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 2, 'This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says to these shepherds: "Instead of leading my flock to safety, you have deserted them and driven them to destruction. Now I will pour out judgment on you for the evil you have done to them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 3, 'But I will gather together the remnant of my flock from wherever I have driven them. I will bring them back into their own fold, and they will be fruitful and increase in number.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 4, 'Then I will appoint responsible shepherds to care for them, and they will never be afraid again. Not a single one of them will be lost or missing," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 5, '"For the time is coming," says the LORD, "when I will place a righteous Branch on King David''s throne. He will be a King who rules with wisdom. He will do what is just and right throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 6, 'And this is his name: `The LORD Is Our Righteousness.'' In that day Judah will be saved, and Israel will live in safety.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 7, '"In that day," says the LORD, "when people are taking an oath, they will no longer say, `As surely as the LORD lives, who rescued the people of Israel from the land of Egypt.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 8, 'Instead, they will say, `As surely as the LORD lives, who brought the people of Israel back to their own land from the land of the north and from all the countries to which he had exiled them.'' Then they will live in their own land."', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 9, 'My heart is broken because of the false prophets, and I tremble uncontrollably. I stagger like a drunkard, like someone overcome by wine, because of the holy words the LORD has spoken against them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 10, 'For the land is full of adultery, and it lies under a curse. The land itself is in mourning--its pastures are dried up. For the prophets do evil and abuse their power.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 11, '"The priests are like the prophets, all ungodly, wicked men. I have seen their despicable acts right here in my own Temple," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 12, '"Therefore, their paths will be dark and slippery. They will be chased down dark and treacherous trails, where they will fall. For I will bring disaster upon them when their time of punishment comes. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 13, '"I saw that the prophets of Samaria were terribly evil, for they prophesied by Baal and led my people of Israel into sin.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 14, 'But now I see that the prophets of Jerusalem are even worse! They commit adultery, and they love dishonesty. They encourage those who are doing evil instead of turning them away from their sins. These prophets are as wicked as the people of Sodom and Gomorrah once were."', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 15, 'Therefore, this is what the LORD Almighty says concerning the prophets: "I will feed them with bitterness and give them poison to drink. For it is because of Jerusalem''s prophets that wickedness fills this land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 16, 'This is my warning to my people," says the LORD Almighty. "Do not listen to these prophets when they prophesy to you, filling you with futile hopes. They are making up everything they say. They do not speak for the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 17, 'They keep saying to these rebels who despise my word, `Don''t worry! The LORD says you will have peace!'' And to those who stubbornly follow their own evil desires, they say, `No harm will come your way!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 18, '"But can you name even one of these prophets who knows the LORD well enough to hear what he is saying? Has even one of them cared enough to listen?', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 19, 'Look! The LORD''s anger bursts out like a storm, a whirlwind that swirls down on the heads of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 20, 'The anger of the LORD will not diminish until it has finished all his plans. In the days to come, you will understand all this very clearly.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 21, '"I have not sent these prophets, yet they claim to speak for me. I have given them no message, yet they prophesy.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 22, 'If they had listened to me, they would have spoken my words and turned my people from their evil ways.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 23, 'Am I a God who is only in one place?" asks the LORD. "Do they think I cannot see what they are doing?', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 24, 'Can anyone hide from me? Am I not everywhere in all the heavens and earth?" asks the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 25, '"I have heard these prophets say, `Listen to the dream I had from God last night.'' And then they proceed to tell lies in my name.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 26, 'How long will this go on? If they are prophets, they are prophets of deceit, inventing everything they say.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 27, 'By telling these false dreams, they are trying to get my people to forget me, just as their ancestors did by worshiping the idols of Baal.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 28, 'Let these false prophets tell their dreams, but let my true messengers faithfully proclaim my every word. There is a difference between chaff and wheat!', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 29, 'Does not my word burn like fire?" asks the LORD. "Is it not like a mighty hammer that smashes rock to pieces?', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 30, '"Therefore," says the LORD, "I stand against these prophets who get their messages from each other--', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 31, 'these smooth-tongued prophets who say, `This prophecy is from the LORD!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 32, 'Their imaginary dreams are flagrant lies that lead my people into sin. I did not send or appoint them, and they have no message at all for my people," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 33, '"Suppose one of the people or one of the prophets or priests asks you, `What prophecy has the LORD burdened you with now?'' You must reply, `You are the burden! The LORD says he will abandon you!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 34, 'If any prophet, priest, or anyone else says, `I have a prophecy from the LORD,'' I will punish that person along with his entire family.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 35, 'You should keep asking each other, `What is the LORD''s answer?'' or `What is the LORD saying?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 36, 'But stop using this phrase, `prophecy from the LORD.'' For people are using it to give authority to their own ideas, turning upside down the words of our God, the living God, the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 37, '"This is what you should say to the prophets: `What is the LORD''s answer?'' or `What is the LORD saying?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 38, 'But suppose they respond, `This is a prophecy from the LORD!'' Then you should say, `This is what the LORD says: Because you have used this phrase, "prophecy from the LORD," even though I warned you not to use it,', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 39, 'I will forget you completely. I will expel you from my presence, along with this city that I gave to you and your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 23, 40, 'And I will make you an object of ridicule, and your name will be infamous throughout the ages.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 1, 'After King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon exiled Jehoiachin son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, to Babylon along with the princes of Judah and all the skilled craftsmen, the LORD gave me this vision. I saw two baskets of figs placed in front of the LORD''s Temple in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 2, 'One basket was filled with fresh, ripe figs, while the other was filled with figs that were spoiled and could not be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 3, 'Then the LORD said to me, "What do you see, Jeremiah?" I replied, "Figs, some very good and some very bad."', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 4, 'Then the LORD gave me this message:', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 5, '"This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: The good figs represent the exiles I sent from Judah to the land of the Babylonians.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 6, 'I have sent them into captivity for their own good. I will see that they are well treated, and I will bring them back here again. I will build them up and not tear them down. I will plant them and not uproot them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 7, 'I will give them hearts that will recognize me as the LORD. They will be my people, and I will be their God, for they will return to me wholeheartedly.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 8, '"But the rotten figs," the LORD said, "represent King Zedekiah of Judah, his officials, all the people left in Jerusalem, and those who live in Egypt. I will treat them like spoiled figs, too rotten to eat.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 9, 'I will make them an object of horror and evil to every nation on earth. They will be disgraced and mocked, taunted and cursed, wherever I send them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 24, 10, 'I will send war, famine, and disease until they have vanished from the land of Israel, which I gave to them and their ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 1, 'This message for all the people of Judah came to Jeremiah from the LORD during the fourth year of Jehoiakim''s reign over Judah. This was the year when King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon began his reign.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 2, 'Jeremiah the prophet said to the people in Judah and Jerusalem,', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 3, '"For the past twenty-three years--from the thirteenth year of Josiah son of Amon, king of Judah, until now--the LORD has been giving me his messages. I have faithfully passed them on to you, but you have not listened.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 4, '"Again and again, the LORD has sent you his prophets, but you have not listened or even tried to hear.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 5, 'Each time the message was this: `Turn from the evil road you are traveling and from the evil things you are doing. Only then will I let you live in this land that the LORD gave to you and your ancestors forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 6, 'Do not make me angry by worshiping the idols you have made. Then I will not harm you.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 7, '"But you would not listen to me," says the LORD. "You made me furious by worshiping your idols, bringing on yourselves all the disasters you now suffer.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 8, 'And now the LORD Almighty says: Because you have not listened to me,', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 9, 'I will gather together all the armies of the north under King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon, whom I have appointed as my deputy. I will bring them all against this land and its people and against the other nations near you. I will completely destroy you and make you an object of horror and contempt and a ruin forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 10, 'I will take away your happy singing and laughter. The joyful voices of bridegrooms and brides will no longer be heard. Your businesses will fail, and all your homes will stand silent and dark.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 11, 'This entire land will become a desolate wasteland. Israel and her neighboring lands will serve the king of Babylon for seventy years.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 12, '"Then, after the seventy years of captivity are over, I will punish the king of Babylon and his people for their sins, says the LORD. I will make the country of the Babylonians an everlasting wasteland.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 13, 'I will bring upon them all the terrors I have promised in this book--all the penalties announced by Jeremiah against the nations.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 14, 'Many nations and great kings will enslave the Babylonians, just as they enslaved my people. I will punish them in proportion to the suffering they cause my people."', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 15, 'Then the LORD, the God of Israel, said to me, "Take from my hand this cup filled to the brim with my anger, and make all the nations to whom I send you drink from it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 16, 'When they drink from it, they will stagger, crazed by the warfare I will send against them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 17, 'So I took the cup of anger from the LORD and made all the nations drink from it--every nation the LORD sent me to.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 18, 'I went to Jerusalem and the other towns of Judah, and their kings and officials drank from the cup. From that day until this, they have been a desolate ruin, an object of horror, contempt, and cursing.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 19, 'I went to Egypt and spoke to Pharaoh, his officials, his princes, and his people. They, too, drank from that terrible cup,', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 20, 'along with all the foreigners living in that land. So did all the kings of the land of Uz and the kings of the Philistine cities of Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron, and what remains of Ashdod.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 21, 'Then I went to the nations of Edom, Moab, and Ammon,', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 22, 'and the kings of Tyre and Sidon, and the kings of the regions across the sea.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 23, 'I went to Dedan, Tema, and Buz, and to the people who live in distant places.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 24, 'I went to the kings of Arabia, the kings of the nomadic tribes of the desert,', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 25, 'and to the kings of Zimri, Elam, and Media.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 26, 'And I went to the kings of the northern countries, far and near, one after the other--all the kingdoms of the world. And finally, the king of Babylon himself drank from the cup of the LORD''s anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 27, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Now tell them, `The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Drink from this cup of my anger. Get drunk and vomit, and you will fall to rise no more, for I am sending terrible wars against you.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 28, 'And if they refuse to accept the cup, tell them, `The LORD Almighty says: You must drink from it. You cannot escape!', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 29, 'I have begun to punish Jerusalem, the city where my own name is honored. Now should I let you go unpunished? No, you will not escape disaster. I will call for war against all the nations of the earth. I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 30, '"Now prophesy all these things, and say to them, `The LORD will roar loudly against his own land from his holy dwelling in heaven. He will shout against everyone on the earth, like the harvesters do as they crush juice from the grapes.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 31, 'His cry of judgment will reach the ends of the earth, for the LORD will bring his case against all the nations. He will judge all the people of the earth, slaughtering the wicked with his sword. The LORD has spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 32, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "Look! Disaster will fall upon nation after nation! A great whirlwind of fury is rising from the most distant corners of the earth!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 33, 'In that day those the LORD has slaughtered will fill the earth from one end to the other. No one will mourn for them or gather up their bodies to bury them. They will be scattered like dung on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 34, 'Weep and moan, you evil shepherds! Roll in the dust, you leaders of the flock! The time of your slaughter has arrived; you will fall and shatter like fragile pottery.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 35, 'You will find no place to hide; there will be no way to escape.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 36, 'Listen to the frantic cries of the shepherds, to the leaders of the flock shouting in despair, for the LORD is spoiling their pastures.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 37, 'Peaceful meadows will be turned into a wasteland by the LORD''s fierce anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 25, 38, 'He has left his den like a lion seeking its prey, and their land will be made desolate by the sword of the enemy and the LORD''s fierce anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 1, 'This message came to Jeremiah from the LORD early in the reign of Jehoiakim son of Josiah, king of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 2, 'The LORD said, "Stand out in front of the Temple of the LORD, and make an announcement to the people who have come there to worship from all over Judah. Give them my entire message; include every word.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 3, 'Perhaps they will listen and turn from their evil ways. Then I will be able to withhold the disaster I am ready to pour out on them because of their sins.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 4, '"Say to them, `This is what the LORD says: If you will not listen to me and obey the law I have given you,', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 5, 'and if you will not listen to my servants, the prophets--for I sent them again and again to warn you, but you would not listen to them--', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 6, 'then I will destroy this Temple as I destroyed Shiloh, the place where the Tabernacle was located. And I will make Jerusalem an object of cursing in every nation on earth.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 7, 'The priests, the prophets, and all the people listened to Jeremiah as he spoke in front of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 8, 'But when Jeremiah had finished his message, saying everything the LORD had told him to say, the priests and prophets and all the people at the Temple mobbed him. "Kill him!" they shouted.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 9, '"What right do you have to prophesy in the LORD''s name that this Temple will be destroyed like Shiloh? What do you mean, saying that Jerusalem will be destroyed?" And all the people threatened him as he stood in front of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 10, 'When the officials of Judah heard what was happening, they rushed over from the palace and sat down at the New Gate of the Temple to hold court.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 11, 'The priests and prophets presented their accusations to the officials and the people. "This man should die!" they said. "You have heard with your own ears what a traitor he is, for he has prophesied against this city."', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 12, 'Then Jeremiah spoke in his own defense. "The LORD sent me to prophesy against this Temple and this city," he said. "The LORD gave me every word that I have spoken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 13, 'But if you stop your sinning and begin to obey the LORD your God, he will cancel this disaster that he has announced against you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 14, 'As for me, I am helpless and in your power--do with me as you think best.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 15, 'But if you kill me, rest assured that you will be killing an innocent man! The responsibility for such a deed will lie on you, on this city, and on every person living in it. For it is absolutely true that the LORD sent me to speak every word you have heard."', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 16, 'Then the officials and the people said to the priests and prophets, "This man does not deserve the death sentence, for he has spoken to us in the name of the LORD our God."', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 17, 'Then some of the wise old men stood and spoke to the people there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 18, 'They said, "Think back to the days when Micah of Moresheth prophesied during the reign of King Hezekiah of Judah. He told the people of Judah, `This is what the LORD Almighty says: Mount Zion will be plowed like an open field; Jerusalem will be reduced to rubble! A great forest will grow on the hilltop, where the Temple now stands.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 19, 'But did King Hezekiah and the people kill him for saying this? No, they turned from their sins and worshiped the LORD. They begged him to have mercy on them. Then the LORD held back the terrible disaster he had pronounced against them. If we kill Jeremiah, who knows what will happen to us?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 20, '(At this time, Uriah son of Shemaiah from Kiriath-jearim was also prophesying for the LORD. And he predicted the same terrible disaster against the city and nation as Jeremiah did.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 21, 'When King Jehoiakim and the army officers and officials heard what he was saying, the king sent someone to kill him. But Uriah heard about the plot and escaped to Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 22, 'Then King Jehoiakim sent Elnathan son of Acbor to Egypt along with several other men to capture Uriah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 23, 'They took him prisoner and brought him back to King Jehoiakim. The king then killed Uriah with a sword and had him buried in an unmarked grave.)', 'NLT'),
(28, 26, 24, 'Ahikam son of Shaphan also stood with Jeremiah and persuaded the court not to turn him over to the mob to be killed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 1, 'This message came to Jeremiah from the LORD early in the reign of Zedekiah son of Josiah, king of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 2, 'The LORD said to me, "Make a yoke, and fasten it on your neck with leather thongs.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 3, 'Then send messages to the kings of Edom, Moab, Ammon, Tyre, and Sidon through their ambassadors to King Zedekiah in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 4, 'Give them this message for their masters: `This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says:', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 5, 'By my great power I have made the earth and all its people and every animal. I can give these things of mine to anyone I choose.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 6, 'Now I will give your countries to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon, who is my servant. I have put everything, even the wild animals, under his control.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 7, 'All the nations will serve him and his son and his grandson until his time is up. But then many nations and great kings will conquer and rule over Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 8, 'So you must submit to Babylon''s king and serve him; put your neck under Babylon''s yoke! I will punish any nation that refuses to be his slave, says the LORD. I will send war, famine, and disease upon that nation until Babylon has conquered it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 9, '" `Do not listen to your false prophets, fortune-tellers, interpreters of dreams, mediums, and sorcerers who say, "The king of Babylon will not conquer you."', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 10, 'They are all liars, and I will drive you from your land and send you far away to die.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 11, 'But the people of any nation that submits to the king of Babylon will be allowed to stay in their own country to farm the land as usual. I, the LORD, have spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 12, 'Then I repeated this same message to King Zedekiah of Judah. "If you want to live, submit to the king of Babylon and his people," I said.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 13, '"Why do you insist on dying--you and your people? Why should you choose war, famine, and disease, which the LORD will bring against every nation that refuses to submit to Babylon''s king?', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 14, 'Do not listen to the false prophets who keep telling you, `The king of Babylon will not conquer you.'' They are liars.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 15, 'This is what the LORD says: I have not sent these prophets! They are telling you lies in my name, so I will drive you from this land. You will all die--you and all these prophets, too."', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 16, 'Then I spoke to the priests and the people and said, "This is what the LORD says: Do not listen to your prophets who claim that soon the gold utensils taken from my Temple will be returned from Babylon. It is all a lie!', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 17, 'Do not listen to them. Surrender to the king of Babylon, and you will live. Why should this whole city be destroyed?', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 18, 'If they really are the LORD''s prophets, let them pray to the LORD Almighty about the gold utensils that are still left in the LORD''s Temple and in the king''s palace and in the palaces of Jerusalem. Let them pray that these remaining articles will not be carried away with you to Babylon!', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 19, '"For this is what the LORD Almighty says about the bronze pillars in front of the Temple, the bronze Sea in the Temple courtyard, the bronze water carts, and all the other ceremonial articles.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 20, 'King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon left them here when he exiled Jehoiachin son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, to Babylon, along with all the other important people of Judah and Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 21, 'Yes, this is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says about the precious things kept in the Temple and in the palace of Judah''s king:', 'NLT'),
(28, 27, 22, 'They will all be carried away to Babylon and will stay there until I send for them, says the LORD. But someday I will bring them back to Jerusalem again."', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 1, 'One day in late summer of that same year--the fourth year of the reign of Zedekiah, king of Judah--Hananiah son of Azzur, a prophet from Gibeon, addressed me publicly in the Temple while all the priests and people listened. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 2, '"The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I will remove the yoke of the king of Babylon from your necks.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 3, 'Within two years, I will bring back all the Temple treasures that King Nebuchadnezzar carried off to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 4, 'And I will bring back Jehoiachin son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, and all the other captives that were taken to Babylon. I will surely break the yoke that the king of Babylon has put on your necks. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 5, 'Jeremiah responded to Hananiah as they stood in front of all the priests and people at the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 6, 'He said, "Amen! May your prophecies come true! I hope the LORD does everything you say. I hope he does bring back from Babylon the treasures of this Temple and all our loved ones.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 7, 'But listen now to the solemn words I speak to you in the presence of all these people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 8, 'The ancient prophets who preceded you and me spoke against many nations, always warning of war, famine, and disease.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 9, 'So a prophet who predicts peace must carry the burden of proof. Only when his predictions come true can it be known that he is really from the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 10, 'Then Hananiah the prophet took the yoke off Jeremiah''s neck and broke it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 11, 'And Hananiah said again to the crowd that had gathered, "The LORD has promised that within two years he will break the yoke of oppression from all the nations now subject to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon." At that, Jeremiah left the Temple area.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 12, 'Soon afterward the LORD gave this message to Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 13, '"Go and tell Hananiah, `This is what the LORD says: You have broken a wooden yoke, but you have replaced it with a yoke of iron.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 14, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I have put a yoke of iron on the necks of all these nations, forcing them into slavery under King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon. I have put everything, even the wild animals, under his control.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 15, 'Then Jeremiah the prophet said to Hananiah, "Listen, Hananiah! The LORD has not sent you, but the people believe your lies.', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 16, 'Therefore, the LORD says you must die. Your life will end this very year because you have rebelled against the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(28, 28, 17, 'Two months later, Hananiah died.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 1, 'Jeremiah wrote a letter from Jerusalem to the elders, priests, prophets, and all the people who had been exiled to Babylon by King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 2, 'This was after King Jehoiachin, the queen mother, the court officials, the leaders of Judah, and all the craftsmen had been deported from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 3, 'He sent the letter with Elasah son of Shaphan and Gemariah son of Hilkiah, when they went to Babylon as King Zedekiah''s ambassadors to Nebuchadnezzar. This is what Jeremiah''s letter said:', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 4, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, sends this message to all the captives he has exiled to Babylon from Jerusalem:', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 5, '"Build homes, and plan to stay. Plant gardens, and eat the food you produce.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 6, 'Marry, and have children. Then find spouses for them, and have many grandchildren. Multiply! Do not dwindle away!', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 7, 'And work for the peace and prosperity of Babylon. Pray to the LORD for that city where you are held captive, for if Babylon has peace, so will you."', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 8, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says, "Do not let the prophets and mediums who are there in Babylon trick you. Do not listen to their dreams', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 9, 'because they prophesy lies in my name. I have not sent them," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 10, '"The truth is that you will be in Babylon for seventy years. But then I will come and do for you all the good things I have promised, and I will bring you home again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 11, 'For I know the plans I have for you," says the LORD. "They are plans for good and not for disaster, to give you a future and a hope.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 12, 'In those days when you pray, I will listen.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 13, 'If you look for me in earnest, you will find me when you seek me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 14, 'I will be found by you," says the LORD. "I will end your captivity and restore your fortunes. I will gather you out of the nations where I sent you and bring you home again to your own land."', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 15, 'You may claim that the LORD has raised up prophets for you in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 16, 'But this is what the LORD says about the king who sits on David''s throne and all those still living here in Jerusalem--your relatives who were not exiled to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 17, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "I will send war, famine, and disease upon them and make them like rotting figs--too bad to eat.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 18, 'Yes, I will pursue them with war, famine, and disease, and I will scatter them around the world. In every nation where I send them, I will make them an object of damnation, horror, contempt, and mockery.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 19, 'For they refuse to listen to me, though I have spoken to them repeatedly through my prophets. And you who are in exile have not listened either," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 20, 'Therefore, listen to this message from the LORD, all you captives there in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 21, 'This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says about your prophets--Ahab son of Kolaiah and Zedekiah son of Maaseiah--who are telling you lies in my name: "I will turn them over to Nebuchadnezzar for a public execution.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 22, 'Their terrible fate will become proverbial, so that whenever the Judean exiles want to curse someone they will say, `May the LORD make you like Zedekiah and Ahab, whom the king of Babylon burned alive!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 23, 'For these men have done terrible things among my people. They have committed adultery with their neighbors'' wives and have lied in my name. I am a witness to this," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 24, 'The LORD sent this message to Shemaiah the Nehelamite in Babylon:', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 25, '"This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: You wrote a letter on your own authority to Zephaniah son of Maaseiah, the priest, and you sent copies to the other priests and people in Jerusalem. You said to Zephaniah,', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 26, '`The LORD has appointed you to replace Jehoiada as the priest in charge of the house of the LORD. You are responsible to put anyone who claims to be a prophet in the stocks and neck irons.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 27, 'So why have you done nothing to stop Jeremiah from Anathoth, who pretends to be a prophet among you?', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 28, 'Jeremiah sent a letter here to Babylon, predicting that our captivity will be a long one. He said we should build homes and plan to stay for many years. He said we should plant fruit trees, because we will be here to eat the fruit for many years to come.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 29, 'But when Zephaniah the priest received Shemaiah''s letter, he took it to Jeremiah and read it to him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 30, 'Then the LORD gave this message to Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 31, '"Send an open letter to all the exiles in Babylon. Tell them, `This is what the LORD says concerning Shemaiah the Nehelamite: Since he has prophesied to you when I did not send him and has tricked you into believing his lies,', 'NLT'),
(28, 29, 32, 'I will punish him and his family. None of his descendants will see the good things I will do for my people, for he has taught you to rebel against me. I, the LORD, have spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 1, 'The LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 2, '"This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Write down for the record everything I have said to you, Jeremiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 3, 'For the time is coming when I will restore the fortunes of my people of Israel and Judah. I will bring them home to this land that I gave to their ancestors, and they will possess it and live here again. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 4, 'This is the message the LORD gave concerning Israel and Judah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 5, '"This is what the LORD says: I have heard the people crying; there is only fear and trembling.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 6, 'Now let me ask you a question: Do men give birth to babies? Then why do they stand there, ashen-faced, hands pressed against their sides like women about to give birth?', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 7, 'In all history there has never been such a time of terror. It will be a time of trouble for my people Israel. Yet in the end, they will be saved!', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 8, '"For in that day, says the LORD Almighty, I will break the yoke from their necks and snap their chains. Foreigners will no longer be their masters.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 9, 'For my people will serve the LORD their God and David their king, whom I will raise up for them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 10, '"So do not be afraid, Jacob, my servant; do not be dismayed, Israel, says the LORD. For I will bring you home again from distant lands, and your children will return from their exile. Israel will return and will have peace and quiet in their own land, and no one will make them afraid.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 11, 'For I am with you and will save you, says the LORD. I will completely destroy the nations where I have scattered you, but I will not destroy you. But I must discipline you; I cannot let you go unpunished.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 12, '"This is what the LORD says: Yours is an incurable bruise, a terrible wound.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 13, 'There is no one to help you or bind up your injury. You are beyond the help of any medicine.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 14, 'All your allies have left you and do not care about you anymore. I have wounded you cruelly, as though I were your enemy. For your sins are many, and your guilt is great.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 15, 'Why do you protest your punishment--this wound that has no cure? I have had to punish you because your sins are many and your guilt is great.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 16, '"But in that coming day, all who destroy you will be destroyed, and all your enemies will be sent into exile. Those who plunder you will be plundered, and those who attack you will be attacked.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 17, 'I will give you back your health and heal your wounds, says the LORD. "Now you are called an outcast--`Jerusalem for whom nobody cares.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 18, 'But the LORD says this: When I bring you home again from your captivity and restore your fortunes, Jerusalem will be rebuilt on her ruins. The palace will be reconstructed as it was before.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 19, 'There will be joy and songs of thanksgiving, and I will multiply my people and make of them a great and honored nation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 20, 'Their children will prosper as they did long ago. I will establish them as a nation before me, and I will punish anyone who hurts them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 21, 'They will have their own ruler again, and he will not be a foreigner. I will invite him to approach me, says the LORD, for who would dare to come unless invited?', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 22, 'You will be my people, and I will be your God."', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 23, 'Look! The LORD''s anger bursts out like a storm, a driving wind that swirls down on the heads of the wicked.', 'NLT'),
(28, 30, 24, 'The fierce anger of the LORD will not diminish until it has finished all his plans. In the days to come, you will understand all this.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 1, '"In that day," says the LORD, "I will be the God of all the families of Israel, and they will be my people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 2, 'I will care for the survivors as they travel through the wilderness. I will again come to give rest to the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 3, 'Long ago the LORD said to Israel: "I have loved you, my people, with an everlasting love. With unfailing love I have drawn you to myself.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 4, 'I will rebuild you, my virgin Israel. You will again be happy and dance merrily with tambourines.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 5, 'Again you will plant your vineyards on the mountains of Samaria and eat from your own gardens there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 6, 'The day will come when watchmen will shout from the hill country of Ephraim, `Come, let us go up to Jerusalem to worship the LORD our God.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 7, 'Now this is what the LORD says: "Sing with joy for Israel! Shout for the greatest of nations! Shout out with praise and joy: `Save your people, O LORD, the remnant of Israel!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 8, 'For I will bring them from the north and from the distant corners of the earth. I will not forget the blind and lame, the expectant mothers and women about to give birth. A great company will return!', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 9, 'Tears of joy will stream down their faces, and I will lead them home with great care. They will walk beside quiet streams and not stumble. For I am Israel''s father, and Ephraim is my oldest child.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 10, '"Listen to this message from the LORD, you nations of the world; proclaim it in distant coastlands: The LORD, who scattered his people, will gather them together and watch over them as a shepherd does his flock.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 11, 'For the LORD has redeemed Israel from those too strong for them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 12, 'They will come home and sing songs of joy on the heights of Jerusalem. They will be radiant because of the many gifts the LORD has given them--the good crops of wheat, wine, and oil, and the healthy flocks and herds. Their life will be like a watered garden, and all their sorrows will be gone.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 13, 'The young women will dance for joy, and the men--old and young--will join in the celebration. I will turn their mourning into joy. I will comfort them and exchange their sorrow for rejoicing.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 14, 'I will supply the priests with an abundance of offerings. I will satisfy my people with my bounty. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 15, 'This is what the LORD says: "A cry of anguish is heard in Ramah--mourning and weeping unrestrained. Rachel weeps for her children, refusing to be comforted--for her children are dead."', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 16, 'But now the LORD says, "Do not weep any longer, for I will reward you. Your children will come back to you from the distant land of the enemy.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 17, 'There is hope for your future," says the LORD. "Your children will come again to their own land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 18, 'I have heard Israel saying, `You disciplined me severely, but I deserved it. I was like a calf that needed to be trained for the yoke and plow. Turn me again to you and restore me, for you alone are the LORD my God.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 19, 'I turned away from God, but then I was sorry. I kicked myself for my stupidity! I was thoroughly ashamed of all I did in my younger days.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 20, '"Is not Israel still my son, my darling child?" asks the LORD. "I had to punish him, but I still love him. I long for him and surely will have mercy on him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 21, '"Set up road signs; put up guideposts. Mark well the path by which you came. Come back again, my virgin Israel; return to your cities here.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 22, 'How long will you wander, my wayward daughter? For the LORD will cause something new and different to happen--Israel will embrace her God. "', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 23, 'This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "When I bring them back again, the people of Judah and its cities will again say, `The LORD bless you--O righteous home, O holy mountain!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 24, 'And city dwellers and farmers and shepherds alike will live together in peace and happiness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 25, 'For I have given rest to the weary and joy to the sorrowing."', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 26, 'At this, I woke up and looked around. My sleep had been very sweet.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 27, '"The time will come," says the LORD, "when I will greatly increase the population and multiply the number of cattle here in Israel and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 28, 'In the past I uprooted and tore down this nation. I overthrew it, destroyed it, and brought disaster upon it. But in the future I will plant it and build it up," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 29, '"The people will no longer quote this proverb: `The parents eat sour grapes, but their children''s mouths pucker at the taste.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 30, 'All people will die for their own sins--those who eat the sour grapes will be the ones whose mouths will pucker.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 31, '"The day will come," says the LORD, "when I will make a new covenant with the people of Israel and Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 32, 'This covenant will not be like the one I made with their ancestors when I took them by the hand and brought them out of the land of Egypt. They broke that covenant, though I loved them as a husband loves his wife," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 33, '"But this is the new covenant I will make with the people of Israel on that day," says the LORD. "I will put my laws in their minds, and I will write them on their hearts. I will be their God, and they will be my people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 34, 'And they will not need to teach their neighbors, nor will they need to teach their family, saying, `You should know the LORD.'' For everyone, from the least to the greatest, will already know me," says the LORD. "And I will forgive their wickedness and will never again remember their sins."', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 35, 'It is the LORD who provides the sun to light the day and the moon and stars to light the night. It is he who stirs the sea into roaring waves. His name is the LORD Almighty, and this is what he says:', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 36, '"I am as likely to reject my people Israel as I am to do away with the laws of nature!', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 37, 'Just as the heavens cannot be measured and the foundation of the earth cannot be explored, so I will not consider casting them away forever for their sins. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 38, '"The time is coming," says the LORD, "when all Jerusalem will be rebuilt for me, from the Tower of Hananel to the Corner Gate.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 39, 'A measuring line will be stretched out over the hill of Gareb and across to Goah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 31, 40, 'And the entire area--including the graveyard and ash dump in the valley, and all the fields out to the Kidron Valley on the east as far as the Horse Gate--will be holy to the LORD. The city will never again be captured or destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 1, 'The following message came to Jeremiah from the LORD in the tenth year of the reign of Zedekiah, king of Judah. This was also the eighteenth year of the reign of King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 2, 'Jerusalem was under siege from the Babylonian army, and Jeremiah was imprisoned in the courtyard of the guard in the royal palace.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 3, 'King Zedekiah had put him there because he continued to give this prophecy: "This is what the LORD says: I am about to hand this city over to the king of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 4, 'King Zedekiah will be captured by the Babylonians and taken to the king of Babylon to be judged and sentenced.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 5, 'I will take Zedekiah to Babylon and will deal with him there. If you fight against the Babylonians, you will never succeed."', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 6, 'At that time the LORD sent me a message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 7, '"Your cousin Hanamel son of Shallum will come and say to you, `Buy my field at Anathoth. By law you have the right to buy it before it is offered to anyone else.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 8, 'Then, just as the LORD had said he would, Hanamel came and visited me in the prison. He said, "Buy my field at Anathoth in the land of Benjamin. By law you have the right to buy it before it is offered to anyone else, so buy it for yourself." Then I knew for sure that the message I had heard was from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 9, 'So I bought the field at Anathoth, paying Hanamel seventeen pieces of silver for it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 10, 'I signed and sealed the deed of purchase before witnesses, weighed out the silver, and paid him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 11, 'Then I took the sealed deed and an unsealed copy of the deed, which contained the terms and conditions of the purchase,', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 12, 'and I handed them to Baruch son of Neriah and grandson of Mahseiah. I did all this in the presence of my cousin Hanamel, the witnesses who had signed the deed, and all the men of Judah who were there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 13, 'Then I said to Baruch as they all listened,', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 14, '"The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Take both this sealed deed and the unsealed copy, and put them into a pottery jar to preserve them for a long time.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 15, 'For the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Someday people will again own property here in this land and will buy and sell houses and vineyards and fields."', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 16, 'Then after I had given the papers to Baruch, I prayed to the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 17, '"O Sovereign LORD! You have made the heavens and earth by your great power. Nothing is too hard for you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 18, 'You are loving and kind to thousands, though children suffer for their parents'' sins. You are the great and powerful God, the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 19, 'You have all wisdom and do great and mighty miracles. You are very aware of the conduct of all people, and you reward them according to their deeds.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 20, 'You performed miraculous signs and wonders in the land of Egypt--things still remembered to this day! And you have continued to do great miracles in Israel and all around the world. You have made your name very great, as it is today.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 21, '"You brought Israel out of Egypt with mighty signs and wonders, with great power and overwhelming terror.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 22, 'You gave the people of Israel this land that you had promised their ancestors long before--a land flowing with milk and honey.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 23, 'Our ancestors came and conquered it and lived in it, but they refused to obey you or follow your law. They have hardly done one thing you told them to! That is why you have sent this terrible disaster upon them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 24, '"See how the siege ramps have been built against the city walls! Because of war, famine, and disease, the city has been handed over to the Babylonians, who will conquer it. Everything has happened just as you said it would.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 25, 'And yet, O Sovereign LORD, you have told me to buy the field--paying good money for it before these witnesses--even though the city will soon belong to the Babylonians."', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 26, 'Then this message came to Jeremiah from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 27, '"I am the LORD, the God of all the peoples of the world. Is anything too hard for me?', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 28, 'I will hand this city over to the Babylonians and to Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, and he will capture it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 29, 'The Babylonians outside the walls will come in and set fire to the city. They will burn down all these houses, where the people caused my fury to rise by offering incense to Baal on the rooftops and by pouring out drink offerings to other gods.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 30, 'Israel and Judah have done nothing but wrong since their earliest days. They have infuriated me with all their evil deeds," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 31, '"From the time this city was built until now, it has done nothing but anger me, so I am determined to get rid of it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 32, '"The sins of Israel and Judah--the sins of the people of Jerusalem, the kings, the officials, the priests, and the prophets--stir up my anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 33, 'My people have turned their backs on me and have refused to return. Day after day, year after year, I taught them right from wrong, but they would not listen or obey.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 34, 'They have set up their abominable idols right in my own Temple, defiling it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 35, 'They have built pagan shrines to Baal in the valley of the son of Hinnom, and there they sacrifice their sons and daughters to Molech. I have never commanded such a horrible deed; it never even crossed my mind to command such a thing. What an incredible evil, causing Judah to sin so greatly!', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 36, '"Now I want to say something more about this city. You have been saying, `It will fall to the king of Babylon through war, famine, and disease.'' But this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says:', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 37, 'I will surely bring my people back again from all the countries where I will scatter them in my fury. I will bring them back to this very city and let them live in peace and safety.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 38, 'They will be my people, and I will be their God.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 39, 'And I will give them one heart and mind to worship me forever, for their own good and for the good of all their descendants.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 40, '"And I will make an everlasting covenant with them, promising not to stop doing good for them. I will put a desire in their hearts to worship me, and they will never leave me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 41, 'I will rejoice in doing good to them and will faithfully and wholeheartedly replant them in this land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 42, 'Just as I have sent all these calamities upon them, so I will do all the good I have promised them. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 43, '"Fields will again be bought and sold in this land about which you now say, `It has been ravaged by the Babylonians, a land where people and animals have all disappeared.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 32, 44, 'Yes, fields will once again be bought and sold--deeds signed and sealed and witnessed--in the land of Benjamin and here in Jerusalem, in the towns of Judah and in the hill country, in the foothills of Judah and in the Negev, too. For someday I will restore prosperity to them. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 1, 'While Jeremiah was still confined in the courtyard of the guard, the LORD gave him this second message:', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 2, '"The LORD, the Maker of the heavens and earth--the LORD is his name--says this:', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 3, 'Ask me and I will tell you some remarkable secrets about what is going to happen here.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 4, 'For this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Though you have torn down the houses of this city and even the king''s palace to get materials to strengthen the walls against the siege weapons of the enemy,', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 5, 'the Babylonians will still enter. The men of this city are already as good as dead, for I have determined to destroy them in my terrible anger. I have abandoned them because of all their wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 6, '"Nevertheless, the time will come when I will heal Jerusalem''s damage and give her prosperity and peace.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 7, 'I will restore the fortunes of Judah and Israel and rebuild their cities.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 8, 'I will cleanse away their sins against me, and I will forgive all their sins of rebellion.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 9, 'Then this city will bring me joy, glory, and honor before all the nations of the earth! The people of the world will see the good I do for my people and will tremble with awe!', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 10, '"This is what the LORD says: You say, `This land has been ravaged, and the people and animals have all disappeared.'' Yet in the empty streets of Jerusalem and Judah''s other towns, there will be heard once more', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 11, 'the sounds of joy and laughter. The joyful voices of bridegrooms and brides will be heard again, along with the joyous songs of people bringing thanksgiving offerings to the LORD. They will sing, `Give thanks to the LORD Almighty, for the LORD is good. His faithful love endures forever!'' For I will restore the prosperity of this land to what it was in the past, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 12, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: This land--though it is now desolate and the people and animals have all disappeared--will once more see shepherds leading sheep and lambs.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 13, 'Once again their flocks will prosper in the towns of the hill country, the foothills of Judah, the Negev, the land of Benjamin, the vicinity of Jerusalem, and all the towns of Judah. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 14, '"The day will come, says the LORD, when I will do for Israel and Judah all the good I have promised them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 15, 'At that time I will bring to the throne of David a righteous descendant, and he will do what is just and right throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 16, 'In that day Judah will be saved, and Jerusalem will live in safety. And their motto will be `The LORD is our righteousness!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 17, 'For this is what the LORD says: David will forever have a descendant sitting on the throne of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 18, 'And there will always be Levitical priests to offer burnt offerings and grain offerings and sacrifices to me."', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 19, 'Then this message came to Jeremiah from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 20, '"If you can break my covenant with the day and the night so that they do not come on their usual schedule,', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 21, 'only then will my covenant with David, my servant, be broken. Only then will he no longer have a descendant to reign on his throne. The same is true for my covenant with the Levitical priests who minister before me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 22, 'And as the stars cannot be counted and the sand on the seashores cannot be measured, so I will multiply the descendants of David, my servant, and the Levites who minister before me."', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 23, 'The LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 24, '"Have you heard what people are saying?--`The LORD chose Judah and Israel and then abandoned them!'' They are sneering and saying that Israel is not worthy to be counted as a nation.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 25, 'But this is the LORD''s reply: I would no more reject my people than I would change my laws of night and day, of earth and sky.', 'NLT'),
(28, 33, 26, 'I will never abandon the descendants of Jacob or David, my servant, or change the plan that David''s descendants will rule the descendants of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. Instead, I will restore them to their land and have mercy on them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 1, 'King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came with all the armies from the kingdoms he ruled, and he fought against Jerusalem and the towns of Judah. At that time this message came to Jeremiah from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 2, '"Go to King Zedekiah of Judah, and tell him, `This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I am about to hand this city over to the king of Babylon, and he will burn it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 3, 'You will not escape his grasp but will be taken into captivity. You will stand before the king of Babylon to be judged and sentenced. Then you will be exiled to Babylon.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 4, '"But listen to this promise from the LORD, O Zedekiah, king of Judah. This is what the LORD says: `You will not be killed in war', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 5, 'but will die peacefully among your people. They will burn incense in your memory, just as they did for your ancestors. They will weep for you and say, "Alas, our king is dead!" This I have decreed, says the LORD.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 6, 'So Jeremiah the prophet delivered the message to King Zedekiah of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 7, 'At this time the Babylonian army was besieging Jerusalem, Lachish, and Azekah--the only cities of Judah with their walls still standing.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 8, 'This message came to Jeremiah from the LORD after King Zedekiah made a covenant with the people, proclaiming freedom for the slaves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 9, 'He had ordered all the people to free their Hebrew slaves--both men and women. No one was to keep a fellow Judean in bondage.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 10, 'The officials and all the people had obeyed the king''s command,', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 11, 'but later they changed their minds. They took back the people they had freed, making them slaves again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 12, 'So the LORD gave them this message through Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 13, '"This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I made a covenant with your ancestors long ago when I rescued them from their slavery in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 14, 'I told them that every Hebrew slave must be freed after serving six years. But this was never done.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 15, 'Recently you repented and did what was right, following my command. You freed your slaves and made a solemn covenant with me in my Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 16, 'But now you have shrugged off your oath and defiled my name by taking back the men and women you had freed, making them slaves once again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 17, '"Therefore, this is what the LORD says: Since you have not obeyed me by setting your countrymen free, I will set you free to be destroyed by war, famine, and disease. You will be considered a disgrace by all the nations of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 18, 'Because you have refused the terms of our covenant, I will cut you apart just as you cut apart the calf when you walked between its halves to solemnize your vows.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 19, 'Yes, I will cut you apart, whether you are officials of Judah or Jerusalem, court officials, priests, or common people--for you have broken your oath.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 20, 'I will give you to your enemies, and they will kill you. Your bodies will be food for the vultures and wild animals.', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 21, 'I will hand over King Zedekiah of Judah and his officials to the army of the king of Babylon. And though Babylon''s king has left this city for a while,', 'NLT'),
(28, 34, 22, 'I will call the Babylonian armies back again. They will fight against this city and will capture and burn it. I will see to it that all the towns of Judah are destroyed and left completely empty."', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 1, 'This is the message the LORD gave Jeremiah when Jehoiakim son of Josiah was king of Judah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 2, '"Go to the settlement where the families of the Recabites live, and invite them to the LORD''s Temple. Take them into one of the inner rooms, and offer them some wine."', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 3, 'So I went to see Jaazaniah son of Jeremiah and grandson of Habazziniah and all his brothers and sons--representing all the Recabite families.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 4, 'I took them to the Temple, and we went into the room assigned to the sons of Hanan son of Igdaliah, a man of God. This room was located next to the one used by the palace officials, directly above the room of Maaseiah son of Shallum, the Temple gatekeeper.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 5, 'I set cups and jugs of wine before them and invited them to have a drink,', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 6, 'but they refused. "No," they said. "We don''t drink wine, because Jehonadab son of Recab, our ancestor, gave us this command: `You and your descendants must never drink wine.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 7, 'And do not build houses or plant crops or vineyards, but always live in tents. If you follow these commands, you will live long, good lives in the land.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 8, 'So we have obeyed him in all these things. We have never had a drink of wine since then, nor have our wives, our sons, or our daughters.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 9, 'We haven''t built houses or owned vineyards or farms or planted crops.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 10, 'We have lived in tents and have fully obeyed all the commands of Jehonadab, our ancestor.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 11, 'But when King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon arrived in this country, we were afraid of the Babylonian and Aramean armies. So we decided to move to Jerusalem. That is why we are here."', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 12, 'Then the LORD gave this message to Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 13, '"The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Go and say to the people in Judah and Jerusalem, `Come and learn a lesson about how to obey me.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 14, 'The Recabites do not drink wine because their ancestor Jehonadab told them not to. But I have spoken to you again and again, and you refuse to listen or obey.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 15, 'I have sent you prophet after prophet to tell you to turn from your wicked ways and to stop worshiping other gods, so that you might live in peace here in the land I gave to you and your ancestors. But you would not listen to me or obey.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 16, 'The families of Recab have obeyed their ancestor completely, but you have refused to listen to me.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 17, '"Therefore, the LORD God Almighty, the God of Israel, says: Because you refuse to listen or answer when I call, I will send upon Judah and Jerusalem all the disasters I have threatened."', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 18, 'Then Jeremiah turned to the Recabites and said, "This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: You have obeyed your ancestor Jehonadab in every respect, following all his instructions.', 'NLT'),
(28, 35, 19, 'Because of this, Jehonadab son of Recab will always have descendants who serve me. I, the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 1, 'During the fourth year that Jehoiakim son of Josiah was king in Judah, the LORD gave this message to Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 2, '"Get a scroll, and write down all my messages against Israel, Judah, and the other nations. Begin with the first message back in the days of Josiah, and write down every message you have given, right up to the present time.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 3, 'Perhaps the people of Judah will repent if they see in writing all the terrible things I have planned for them. Then I will be able to forgive their sins and wrongdoings."', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 4, 'So Jeremiah sent for Baruch son of Neriah, and as Jeremiah dictated, Baruch wrote down all the prophecies that the LORD had given him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 5, 'Then Jeremiah said to Baruch, "I am a prisoner here and unable to go to the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 6, 'So you go to the Temple on the next day of fasting, and read the messages from the LORD that are on this scroll. On that day people will be there from all over Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 7, 'Perhaps even yet they will turn from their evil ways and ask the LORD''s forgiveness before it is too late. For the LORD''s terrible anger has been pronounced against them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 8, 'Baruch did as Jeremiah told him and read these messages from the LORD to the people at the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 9, 'This happened on the day of sacred fasting held in late autumn, during the fifth year of the reign of Jehoiakim son of Josiah. People from all over Judah came to attend the services at the Temple on that day.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 10, 'Baruch read Jeremiah''s words to all the people from the Temple room of Gemariah son of Shaphan. This room was just off the upper courtyard of the Temple, near the New Gate entrance.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 11, 'When Micaiah son of Gemariah and grandson of Shaphan heard the messages from the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 12, 'he went down to the secretary''s room in the palace where the administrative officials were meeting. Elishama the secretary was there, along with Delaiah son of Shemaiah, Elnathan son of Acbor, Gemariah son of Shaphan, Zedekiah son of Hananiah, and all the others with official responsibilities.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 13, 'When Micaiah told them about the messages Baruch was reading to the people,', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 14, 'the officials sent Jehudi son of Nethaniah, grandson of Shelemiah, and great-grandson of Cushi, to ask Baruch to come and read the messages to them, too. So Baruch took the scroll and went to them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 15, '"Sit down and read the scroll to us," the officials said, and Baruch did as they requested.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 16, 'By the time Baruch had finished reading, they were badly frightened. "We must tell the king what we have heard," they said.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 17, '"But first, tell us how you got these messages. Did they come directly from Jeremiah?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 18, 'So Baruch explained, "Jeremiah dictated them to me word by word, and I wrote down his words with ink on this scroll."', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 19, '"You and Jeremiah should both hide," the officials told Baruch. "Don''t tell anyone where you are!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 20, 'Then the officials left the scroll for safekeeping in the room of Elishama the secretary and went to tell the king.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 21, 'The king sent Jehudi to get the scroll. Jehudi brought it from Elishama''s room and read it to the king as all his officials stood by.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 22, 'It was late autumn, and the king was in a winterized part of the palace, sitting in front of a fire to keep warm.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 23, 'Whenever Jehudi finished reading three or four columns, the king took his knife and cut off that section of the scroll. He then threw it into the fire, section by section, until the whole scroll was burned up.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 24, 'Neither the king nor his officials showed any signs of fear or repentance at what they heard.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 25, 'Even when Elnathan, Delaiah, and Gemariah begged the king not to burn the scroll, he wouldn''t listen.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 26, 'Then the king commanded his son Jerahmeel, Seraiah son of Azriel, and Shelemiah son of Abdeel to arrest Baruch and Jeremiah. But the LORD had hidden them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 27, 'After the king had burned Jeremiah''s scroll, the LORD gave Jeremiah another message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 28, '"Get another scroll, and write everything again just as you did on the scroll King Jehoiakim burned.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 29, 'Then say to the king, `This is what the LORD says: You burned the scroll because it said the king of Babylon would destroy this land and everything in it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 30, 'Now this is what the LORD says about King Jehoiakim of Judah: He will have no heirs to sit on the throne of David. His dead body will be thrown out to lie unburied--exposed to hot days and frosty nights.', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 31, 'I will punish him and his family and his officials because of their sins. I will pour out on them and on all the people of Judah and Jerusalem all the disasters I have promised, for they would not listen to my warnings.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 36, 32, 'Then Jeremiah took another scroll and dictated again to his secretary Baruch. He wrote everything that had been on the scroll King Jehoiakim had burned in the fire. Only this time, he added much more!', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 1, 'Zedekiah son of Josiah succeeded Jehoiachin son of Jehoiakim as the king of Judah. He was appointed by King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 2, 'But neither King Zedekiah nor his officials nor the people who were left in the land listened to what the LORD said through Jeremiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 3, 'Nevertheless, King Zedekiah sent Jehucal son of Shelemiah and Zephaniah the priest, son of Maaseiah, to ask Jeremiah, "Please pray to the LORD our God for us."', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 4, 'Jeremiah had not yet been imprisoned, so he could come and go as he pleased.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 5, 'At this time the army of Pharaoh Hophra of Egypt appeared at the southern border of Judah. When the Babylonian army heard about it, they withdrew from their siege of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 6, 'Then the LORD gave this message to Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 7, '"This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Tell the king of Judah, who sent you to ask me what is going to happen, that Pharaoh''s army is about to return to Egypt, though he came here to help you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 8, 'Then the Babylonians will come back and capture this city and burn it to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 9, 'The LORD says: Do not fool yourselves that the Babylonians are gone for good. They aren''t!', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 10, 'Even if you were to destroy the entire Babylonian army, leaving only a handful of wounded survivors, they would still stagger from their tents and burn this city to the ground!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 11, 'When the Babylonian army left Jerusalem because of Pharaoh''s approaching army,', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 12, 'Jeremiah started to leave the city on his way to the land of Benjamin, to see the property he had bought.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 13, 'But as he was walking through the Benjamin Gate, a sentry arrested him and said, "You are defecting to the Babylonians!" The sentry making the arrest was Irijah son of Shelemiah and grandson of Hananiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 14, '"That''s not true!" Jeremiah protested. "I had no intention of doing any such thing." But Irijah wouldn''t listen, and he took Jeremiah before the officials.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 15, 'They were furious with Jeremiah and had him flogged and imprisoned in the house of Jonathan the secretary. Jonathan''s house had been converted into a prison.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 16, 'Jeremiah was put into a dungeon cell, where he remained for many days.', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 17, 'Later King Zedekiah secretly requested that Jeremiah come to the palace, where the king asked him, "Do you have any messages from the LORD?Yes, I do!" said Jeremiah. "You will be defeated by the king of Babylon."', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 18, 'Then Jeremiah asked the king, "What crime have I committed? What have I done against you, your officials, or the people that I should be imprisoned like this?', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 19, 'Where are your prophets now who told you the king of Babylon would not attack you?', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 20, 'Listen, my lord the king, I beg you. Don''t send me back to the dungeon in the house of Jonathan the secretary, for I will die there."', 'NLT'),
(28, 37, 21, 'So King Zedekiah commanded that Jeremiah not be returned to the dungeon. Instead, he was imprisoned in the courtyard of the guard in the royal palace. The king also commanded that Jeremiah be given a loaf of fresh bread every day as long as there was any left in the city. So Jeremiah was put in the palace prison.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 1, 'Now Shephatiah son of Mattan, Gedaliah son of Pashhur, Jehucal son of Shelemiah, and Pashhur son of Malkijah heard what Jeremiah had been telling the people. He was saying,', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 2, '"This is what the LORD says: Everyone who stays in Jerusalem will die from war, famine, or disease, but those who surrender to the Babylonians will live.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 3, 'The LORD also says: The city of Jerusalem will surely be handed over to the army of the king of Babylon, who will capture it."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 4, 'So these officials went to the king and said, "Sir, this man must die! That kind of talk will undermine the morale of the few fighting men we have left, as well as that of all the people, too. This man is a traitor!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 5, 'So King Zedekiah agreed. "All right," he said. "Do as you like. I will do nothing to stop you."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 6, 'So the officials took Jeremiah from his cell and lowered him by ropes into an empty cistern in the prison yard. It belonged to Malkijah, a member of the royal family. There was no water in the cistern, but there was a thick layer of mud at the bottom, and Jeremiah sank down into it.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 7, 'But Ebed-melech the Ethiopian, an important palace official, heard that Jeremiah was in the cistern. At that time the king was holding court at the Benjamin Gate,', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 8, 'so Ebed-melech rushed from the palace to speak with him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 9, '"My lord the king," he said, "these men have done a very evil thing in putting Jeremiah the prophet into the cistern. He will soon die of hunger, for almost all the bread in the city is gone."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 10, 'So the king told Ebed-melech, "Take along thirty of my men, and pull Jeremiah out of the cistern before he dies."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 11, 'So Ebed-melech took the men with him and went to a room in the palace beneath the treasury, where he found some old rags and discarded clothing. He carried these to the cistern and lowered them to Jeremiah on a rope.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 12, 'Ebed-melech called down to Jeremiah, "Put these rags under your armpits to protect you from the ropes." Then when Jeremiah was ready,', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 13, 'they pulled him out. So Jeremiah was returned to the courtyard of the guard--the palace prison--where he remained.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 14, 'One day King Zedekiah sent for Jeremiah to meet him at the third entrance of the LORD''s Temple. "I want to ask you something," the king said. "And don''t try to hide the truth."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 15, 'Jeremiah said, "If I tell you the truth, you will kill me. And if I give you advice, you won''t listen to me anyway."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 16, 'So King Zedekiah secretly promised him, "As surely as the LORD our Creator lives, I will not kill you or hand you over to the men who want you dead."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 17, 'Then Jeremiah said to Zedekiah, "The LORD God Almighty, the God of Israel, says: If you surrender to Babylon, you and your family will live, and the city will not be burned.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 18, 'But if you refuse to surrender, you will not escape! This city will be handed over to the Babylonians, and they will burn it to the ground."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 19, '"But I am afraid to surrender," the king said, "for the Babylonians will hand me over to the Judeans who have defected to them. And who knows what they will do to me?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 20, 'Jeremiah replied, "You won''t be handed over to them if you choose to obey the LORD. Your life will be spared, and all will go well for you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 21, 'But if you refuse to surrender, this is what the LORD has revealed to me:', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 22, 'All the women left in your palace will be brought out and given to the officers of the Babylonian army. Then the women will taunt you, saying, `What fine friends you have! They have betrayed and misled you. When your feet sank in the mud, they left you to your fate!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 23, 'All your wives and children will be led out to the Babylonians, and you will not escape. You will be seized by the king of Babylon, and this city will be burned."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 24, 'Then Zedekiah said to Jeremiah, "Don''t tell anyone you told me this, or you will die!', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 25, 'My officials may hear that I spoke to you. Then they may say to you, `Tell us what you and the king were talking about. If you don''t tell us, we will kill you.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 26, 'If this happens, just tell them you begged me not to send you back to Jonathan''s dungeon, for fear you would die there."', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 27, 'Sure enough, it wasn''t long before the king''s officials came to Jeremiah and asked him why the king had called for him. But Jeremiah followed the king''s instructions, and they left without finding out the truth. No one had overheard the conversation between Jeremiah and the king.', 'NLT'),
(28, 38, 28, 'And Jeremiah remained a prisoner in the courtyard of the guard until the day Jerusalem was captured.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 1, 'It was in January during the ninth year of King Zedekiah''s reign that King Nebuchadnezzar and his army returned to besiege Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 2, 'Two and a half years later, on July 18, the Babylonians broke through the wall, and the city fell.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 3, 'All the officers of the Babylonian army came in and sat in triumph at the Middle Gate: Nergal-sharezer of Samgar, and Nebo-sarsekim, a chief officer, and Nergal-sharezer, the king''s adviser, and many others.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 4, 'King Zedekiah and his royal guard saw the Babylonians in the city gate, so they fled when the darkness of night arrived. They went out through a gate between the two walls behind the king''s garden and headed toward the Jordan Valley.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 5, 'But the Babylonians chased the king and caught him on the plains of Jericho. They took him to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon, who was at Riblah in the land of Hamath. There the king of Babylon pronounced judgment upon Zedekiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 6, 'He made Zedekiah watch as they killed his sons and all the nobles of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 7, 'Then he gouged out Zedekiah''s eyes, bound him in chains, and sent him away to exile in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 8, 'Meanwhile, the Babylonians burned Jerusalem, including the palace, and tore down the walls of the city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 9, 'Then Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, sent to Babylon the remnant of the population as well as those who had defected to him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 10, 'But Nebuzaradan left a few of the poorest people in Judah, and he assigned them fields and vineyards to care for.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 11, 'King Nebuchadnezzar had told Nebuzaradan to find Jeremiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 12, '"See that he isn''t hurt," he had said. "Look after him well, and give him anything he wants."', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 13, 'So Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, and Nebushazban, a chief officer, and Nergal-sharezer, the king''s adviser, and the other officers of Babylon''s king', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 14, 'sent messengers to bring Jeremiah out of the prison. They put him under the care of Gedaliah son of Ahikam and grandson of Shaphan, who was to take him back to his home. So Jeremiah stayed in Judah among his own people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 15, 'The LORD had given the following message to Jeremiah while he was still in prison:', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 16, '"Say to Ebed-melech the Ethiopian, `The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I will do to this city everything I have threatened. I will send disaster, not prosperity. You will see its destruction,', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 17, 'but I will rescue you from those you fear so much.', 'NLT'),
(28, 39, 18, 'Because you trusted me, I will preserve your life and keep you safe. I, the LORD, have spoken!''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 1, 'The LORD gave a message to Jeremiah after Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, had released him at Ramah. He had found Jeremiah bound in chains among the captives of Jerusalem and Judah who were being sent to exile in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 2, 'The captain of the guard called for Jeremiah and said, "The LORD your God has brought this disaster on this land,', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 3, 'just as he said he would. For these people have sinned against the LORD and disobeyed him. That is why it happened.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 4, 'Now I am going to take off your chains and let you go. If you want to come with me to Babylon, you are welcome. I will see that you are well cared for. But if you don''t want to come, you may stay here. The whole land is before you--go wherever you like.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 5, 'If you decide to stay, then return to Gedaliah son of Ahikam and grandson of Shaphan. He has been appointed governor of Judah by the king of Babylon. Stay there with the people he rules. But it''s up to you; go wherever you like." Then Nebuzaradan gave Jeremiah some food and money and let him go.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 6, 'So Jeremiah returned to Gedaliah son of Ahikam at Mizpah and lived in Judah with the few who were still left in the land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 7, 'The leaders of the Judean guerrilla bands in the countryside heard that the king of Babylon had appointed Gedaliah son of Ahikam as governor over the poor people who were left behind in Judah, and that he hadn''t exiled everyone to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 8, 'So they came to see Gedaliah at Mizpah. These are the names of the leaders who came: Ishmael son of Nethaniah, Johanan and Jonathan, sons of Kareah, Seraiah son of Tanhumeth, the sons of Ephai the Netophathite, Jaazaniah son of the Maacathite, and all their men.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 9, 'Gedaliah assured them that it would be safe for them to surrender to the Babylonians. "Stay here, and serve the king of Babylon," he said, "and all will go well for you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 10, 'As for me, I will stay at Mizpah to represent you before the Babylonians who come to meet with us. Settle in any town you wish, and live off the land. Harvest the grapes and summer fruits and olives, and store them away."', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 11, 'When the Judeans in Moab, Ammon, Edom, and the other nearby countries heard that the king of Babylon had left a few people in Judah and that Gedaliah was the governor,', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 12, 'they began to return to Judah from the places to which they had fled. They stopped at Mizpah to discuss their plans with Gedaliah and then went out into the Judean countryside to gather a great harvest of grapes and other crops.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 13, 'Soon after this, Johanan son of Kareah and the other guerrilla leaders came to Gedaliah at Mizpah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 14, 'They said to him, "Did you know that Baalis, king of Ammon, has sent Ishmael son of Nethaniah to assassinate you?" But Gedaliah refused to believe them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 15, 'Later Johanan had a private conference with Gedaliah and volunteered to kill Ishmael secretly. "Why should we let him come and murder you?" Johanan asked. "What will happen then to the Judeans who have returned? Why should the few of us who are still left be scattered and lost?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 40, 16, 'But Gedaliah said to Johanan, "I forbid you to do any such thing, for you are lying about Ishmael."', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 1, 'But in midautumn, Ishmael son of Nethaniah and grandson of Elishama, who was a member of the royal family, arrived in Mizpah accompanied by ten men. Gedaliah invited them to dinner. While they were eating,', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 2, 'Ishmael and his ten men suddenly drew their swords and killed Gedaliah, whom the king of Babylon had appointed governor.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 3, 'Then they went out and slaughtered all the Judean officials and Babylonian soldiers who were with Gedaliah at Mizpah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 4, 'The next day, before anyone had heard about Gedaliah''s murder,', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 5, 'eighty men arrived from Shechem, Shiloh, and Samaria. They had come to worship at the Temple of the LORD. They had shaved off their beards, torn their clothes, and cut themselves, and had brought along grain offerings and incense.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 6, 'Ishmael left Mizpah to meet them, weeping as he went. When he reached them, he said, "Oh, come and see what has happened to Gedaliah!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 7, 'But as soon as they were all inside the town, Ishmael and his men killed all but ten of them and threw their bodies into a cistern.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 8, 'The other ten had talked Ishmael into letting them go by promising to bring him their stores of wheat, barley, oil, and honey that they had hidden away.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 9, 'The cistern where Ishmael dumped the bodies of the men he murdered was the large one made by King Asa when he fortified Mizpah to protect himself against King Baasha of Israel. Ishmael son of Nethaniah filled it with corpses.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 10, 'Ishmael made captives of the king''s daughters and the other people who had been left under Gedaliah''s care in Mizpah by Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard. Taking them with him, he started back toward the land of Ammon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 11, 'But when Johanan son of Kareah and the rest of the guerrilla leaders heard what Ishmael had done,', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 12, 'they took all their men and set out to stop him. They caught up with him at the pool near Gibeon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 13, 'The people Ishmael had captured shouted for joy when they saw Johanan and his men.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 14, 'And all the captives from Mizpah escaped and began to help Johanan.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 15, 'Meanwhile, Ishmael and eight of his men escaped from Johanan into the land of Ammon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 16, 'Then Johanan son of Kareah and his officers led away all the people they had rescued--warriors, women, children, and palace officials.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 17, 'They took them all to the village of Geruth-kimham near Bethlehem, where they prepared to leave for Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(28, 41, 18, 'They were afraid of what the Babylonians would do when they heard that Ishmael had killed Gedaliah, the governor appointed by the Babylonian king.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 1, 'Then all the army officers, including Johanan son of Kareah and Jezaniah son of Hoshaiah, and all the people, from the least to the greatest, approached', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 2, 'Jeremiah the prophet. They said, "Please pray to the LORD your God for us. As you know, we are only a tiny remnant compared to what we were before.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 3, 'Beg the LORD your God to show us what to do and where to go."', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 4, '"All right," Jeremiah replied. "I will pray to the LORD your God, and I will tell you everything he says. I will hide nothing from you."', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 5, 'Then they said to Jeremiah, "May the LORD your God be a faithful witness against us if we refuse to obey whatever he tells us to do!', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 6, 'Whether we like it or not, we will obey the LORD our God to whom we send you with our plea. For if we obey him, everything will turn out well for us."', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 7, 'Ten days later, the LORD gave his reply to Jeremiah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 8, 'So he called for Johanan son of Kareah and the army officers, and for all the people, from the least to the greatest.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 9, 'He said to them, "You sent me to the LORD, the God of Israel, with your request, and this is his reply:', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 10, '`Stay here in this land. If you do, I will build you up and not tear you down; I will plant you and not uproot you. For I am sorry for all the punishment I have had to bring upon you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 11, 'Do not fear the king of Babylon anymore, says the LORD. For I am with you and will save you and rescue you from his power.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 12, 'I will be merciful to you by making him kind, so he will let you stay here in your land.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 13, '"But if you refuse to obey the LORD your God and say, `We will not stay here,''', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 14, 'and if you insist on going to live in Egypt where you think you will be free from war, famine, and alarms,', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 15, 'then this is what the LORD says to the remnant of Judah. The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: `If you insist on going to Egypt,', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 16, 'the war and famine you fear will follow close behind you, and you will die there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 17, 'That is the fate awaiting every one of you who insists on going to live in Egypt. Yes, you will die from war, famine, and disease. None of you will escape from the disaster I will bring upon you there.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 18, '"For the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: `Just as my anger and fury were poured out on the people of Jerusalem, so they will be poured out on you when you enter Egypt. You will become an object of damnation, horror, cursing, and mockery. And you will never see your homeland again.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 19, '"Listen, you remnant of Judah. The LORD has told you: `Do not go to Egypt!'' Don''t forget this warning I have given you today.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 20, 'For you were deceitful when you sent me to pray to the LORD your God for you, saying, `Just tell us what the LORD our God says, and we will do it!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 21, 'And today I have told you exactly what he said, but you will not obey the LORD your God any better now than you have in the past.', 'NLT'),
(28, 42, 22, 'So you can be sure that you will die from war, famine, and disease in Egypt, where you insist on going."', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 1, 'When Jeremiah had finished giving this message from the LORD their God to all the people,', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 2, 'Azariah son of Hoshaiah and Johanan son of Kareah and all the other proud men said to Jeremiah, "You lie! The LORD our God hasn''t forbidden us to go to Egypt!', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 3, 'Baruch son of Neriah has convinced you to say this, so we will stay here and be killed by the Babylonians or be carried off into exile."', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 4, 'So Johanan and all the army officers and all the people refused to obey the LORD''s command to stay in Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 5, 'Johanan and his officers took with them all the people who had returned from the nearby countries to which they had fled.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 6, 'In the crowd were men, women, and children, the king''s daughters, and all those whom Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, had left with Gedaliah. Also included were the prophet Jeremiah and Baruch.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 7, 'The people refused to obey the LORD and went to Egypt, going as far as the city of Tahpanhes.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 8, 'Then at Tahpanhes, the LORD gave another message to Jeremiah. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 9, '"While the people of Judah are watching, bury large rocks between the pavement stones at the entrance of Pharaoh''s palace here in Tahpanhes.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 10, 'Then say to the people of Judah, `The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I will surely bring my servant Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, here to Egypt. I will set his throne on these stones that I have hidden. He will spread his royal canopy over them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 11, 'And when he comes, he will destroy the land of Egypt. He will bring death to those destined for death; he will bring captivity to those destined for captivity; he will bring the sword against those destined for the sword.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 12, 'He will set fire to the temples of Egypt''s gods, burning all their idols and carrying away the people as captives. He will pick clean the land of Egypt as a shepherd picks fleas from his cloak. And he himself will leave unharmed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 43, 13, 'He will break down the sacred pillars standing in the temple of the sun in Egypt, and he will burn down the temples of Egypt''s gods.''"', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 1, 'This is the message Jeremiah received concerning the Judeans living in northern Egypt in the cities of Migdol, Tahpanhes, and Memphis, and throughout southern Egypt as well:', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 2, '"This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: You saw what I did to Jerusalem and to all the towns of Judah. They now lie in ruins, and no one lives in them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 3, 'Because of all their wickedness, my anger rose high against them. They burned incense and worshiped other gods--gods that neither they nor you nor any of your ancestors have ever known.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 4, '"Again and again I sent my servants, the prophets, to plead with them, `Don''t do these horrible things that I hate so much.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 5, 'But my people would not listen or turn back from their wicked ways. They kept right on burning incense to these gods.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 6, 'And so my fury boiled over and fell like fire on the towns of Judah and into the streets of Jerusalem, and now they are a desolate ruin.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 7, '"And now the LORD God Almighty, the God of Israel, asks you: Why are you destroying yourselves? For not one of you will survive--not a man, woman, or child among you who has come here from Judah, not even the babies in your arms.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 8, 'Why arouse my anger by burning incense to the idols you have made here in Egypt? You will only destroy yourselves and make yourselves an object of cursing and mockery for all the nations of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 9, 'Have you forgotten the sins of your ancestors, the sins of the kings and queens of Judah, and the sins you and your wives committed in Judah and Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 10, 'To this very hour you have shown no remorse or reverence. No one has chosen to follow my law and the decrees I gave to you and your ancestors before you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 11, '"Therefore, the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: I have made up my mind to destroy every one of you!', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 12, 'I will take this remnant of Judah that insisted on coming here to Egypt, and I will consume them. They will fall here in Egypt, killed by war and famine. All will die, from the least to the greatest. They will be an object of damnation, horror, cursing, and mockery.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 13, 'I will punish them in Egypt just as I punished them in Jerusalem, by war, famine, and disease.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 14, 'Of those who fled to Egypt with dreams of returning home to Judah, only a handful will escape."', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 15, 'Then all the women present and all the men who knew that their wives had burned incense to idols--a great crowd of all the Judeans living in Pathros, the southern region of Egypt--answered Jeremiah,', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 16, '"We will not listen to your messages from the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 17, 'We will do whatever we want. We will burn incense to the Queen of Heaven and sacrifice to her just as much as we like--just as we and our ancestors did before us, and as our kings and princes have always done in the towns of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem. For in those days we had plenty to eat, and we were well off and had no troubles!', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 18, 'But ever since we quit burning incense to the Queen of Heaven and stopped worshiping her, we have been in great trouble and have suffered the effects of war and famine."', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 19, '"And," the women added, "do you suppose that we were worshiping the Queen of Heaven, pouring out drink offerings to her, and making cakes marked with her image, without our husbands knowing it and helping us? Of course not!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 20, 'Then Jeremiah said to all of them, men and women alike, who had given him that answer,', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 21, '"Do you think the LORD did not know that you and your ancestors, your kings and officials, and all the people were burning incense to idols in the towns of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem?', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 22, 'It was because the LORD could no longer bear all the evil things you were doing that he made your land an object of cursing--a desolate ruin without a single inhabitant--as it is today.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 23, 'The very reason all these terrible things have happened to you is because you have burned incense to idols and sinned against the LORD, refusing to obey him and follow his instructions, laws, and stipulations."', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 24, 'Then Jeremiah said to them all, including the women, "Listen to this message from the LORD, all you citizens of Judah who live in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 25, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: You and your wives have said that you will never give up your devotion and sacrifices to the Queen of Heaven, and you have proved it by your actions. Then go ahead and carry out your promises and vows to her!', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 26, '"But listen to this message from the LORD, all you Judeans now living in Egypt: I have sworn by my great name, says the LORD, that my name will no longer be spoken by any of the Judeans in the land of Egypt. None of you may invoke my name or use this oath: `As surely as the Sovereign LORD lives!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 27, 'For I will watch over you to bring you disaster and not good. You will suffer war and famine until all of you are dead.', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 28, '"Only a small number will escape death and return to Judah from Egypt. Then all those who came to Egypt will find out whose words are true, mine or theirs!', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 29, 'And this is the proof I give you, says the LORD, that all I have threatened will happen to you and that I will punish you here:', 'NLT'),
(28, 44, 30, 'I will turn Pharaoh Hophra, king of Egypt, over to his enemies who want to kill him, just as I turned King Zedekiah of Judah over to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 45, 1, 'The prophet Jeremiah gave a message to Baruch son of Neriah in the fourth year of the reign of Jehoiakim son of Josiah, after Baruch had written down everything Jeremiah had dictated to him. He said,', 'NLT'),
(28, 45, 2, '"This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says to you, Baruch:', 'NLT'),
(28, 45, 3, 'You have said, `I am overwhelmed with trouble! Haven''t I had enough pain already? And now the LORD has added more! I am weary of my own sighing and can find no rest.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 45, 4, '"Baruch, this is what the LORD says: I will destroy this nation that I built. I will uproot what I planted.', 'NLT'),
(28, 45, 5, 'Are you seeking great things for yourself? Don''t do it! But don''t be discouraged. I will bring great disaster upon all these people, but I will protect you wherever you go. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 1, 'The following messages were given to Jeremiah the prophet from the LORD concerning foreign nations.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 2, 'This message concerning Egypt was given in the fourth year of the reign of Jehoiakim son of Josiah, the king of Judah, on the occasion of the battle of Carchemish when Pharaoh Neco, king of Egypt, and his army were defeated beside the Euphrates River by King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 3, '"Buckle on your armor and advance into battle!', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 4, 'Harness the horses, and prepare to mount them. Put on your helmets, sharpen your spears, and prepare your armor.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 5, 'But look! The Egyptian army flees in terror. The bravest of its fighting men run without a backward glance. They are terrorized at every turn, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 6, 'The swiftest cannot flee; the mightiest warriors cannot escape. By the Euphrates River to the north they stumble and fall.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 7, '"Who is this, rising like the Nile River at floodtime, overflowing all the land?', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 8, 'It is the Egyptian army, boasting that it will cover the earth like a flood, destroying every foe.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 9, 'Then come, you horses and chariots and mighty warriors of Egypt! Come, all you allies from Ethiopia, Libya, and Lydia who are skilled with the shield and bow!', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 10, 'For this is the day of the Lord, the LORD Almighty, a day of vengeance on his enemies. The sword will devour until it is satisfied, yes, drunk with your blood! The Lord, the LORD Almighty, will receive a sacrifice today in the north country beside the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 11, 'Go up to Gilead to get ointment, O virgin daughter of Egypt! But your many medicines will bring you no healing.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 12, 'The nations have heard of your shame. The earth is filled with your cries of despair. Your mightiest warriors will stumble across each other and fall together."', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 13, 'Then the LORD gave the prophet Jeremiah this message about King Nebuchadnezzar''s plans to attack Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 14, '"Shout it out in Egypt! Publish it in the cities of Migdol, Memphis, and Tahpanhes! Mobilize for battle, for the sword of destruction will devour everyone around you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 15, 'Why have your warriors fled in terror? They cannot stand because the LORD has driven them away.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 16, 'They stumble and fall over each other and say among themselves, `Come, let''s go back to our homeland where we were born. Let''s get away from the sword of the enemy!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 17, 'There they will say, `Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, is a loudmouth who missed his opportunity!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 18, '"As surely as I live," says the King, whose name is the LORD Almighty, "one is coming against Egypt who is as tall as Mount Tabor or Mount Carmel by the sea!', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 19, 'Pack up! Get ready to leave for exile, you citizens of Egypt! The city of Memphis will be destroyed, without a single person living there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 20, 'Egypt is as sleek as a young cow, but a gadfly from the north is on its way!', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 21, 'Egypt''s famed mercenaries have become like fattened calves. They turn and run, for it is a day of great disaster for Egypt, a time of great punishment.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 22, 'Silent as a serpent gliding away, Egypt flees. The invading army marches in; they come against her with axes like woodsmen.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 23, 'They will cut down her people like trees," says the LORD, "for they are more numerous than grasshoppers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 24, 'Egypt will be humiliated; she will be handed over to men from the north."', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 25, 'The LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "I will punish Amon, the god of Thebes, and all the other gods of Egypt. I will punish its rulers and Pharaoh, too, and all who trust in him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 26, 'I will hand them over to those who want them killed--to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon and his army. But afterward the land will recover from the ravages of war. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 27, '"But do not be afraid, Jacob, my servant; do not be dismayed, Israel. For I will bring you home again from distant lands, and your children will return from their exile. Israel will return and will have peace and quiet, and nothing will make them afraid.', 'NLT'),
(28, 46, 28, 'Fear not, Jacob, my servant," says the LORD, "for I am with you. I will destroy the nations to which I have exiled you, but I will not destroy you. But I must discipline you; I cannot let you go unpunished."', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 1, 'This is the LORD''s message to the prophet Jeremiah concerning the Philistines of Gaza, before it was captured by the Egyptian army.', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 2, 'This is what the LORD says: "A flood is coming from the north to overflow the land. It will destroy the land and everything in it--cities and people alike. People will scream in terror, and everyone in the land will weep.', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 3, 'Hear the clatter of hooves and the rumble of wheels as the chariots rush by. Terrified fathers run madly, without a backward glance at their helpless children.', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 4, '"The time has come for the Philistines to be destroyed, along with their allies from Tyre and Sidon. Yes, the LORD is destroying the Philistines, those colonists from Crete.', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 5, 'The city of Gaza will be demolished; Ashkelon will lie in ruins. You remnant of the Mediterranean plain, how long will you lament and mourn?', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 6, '"Now, O sword of the LORD, when will you be at rest again? Go back into your sheath; rest and be still!', 'NLT'),
(28, 47, 7, 'But how can it be still when the LORD has sent it on an errand? For the city of Ashkelon and the people living along the sea must be destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 1, 'This message was given concerning Moab. This is what the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "Destruction is certain for the city of Nebo; it will soon lie in ruins. The city of Kiriathaim will be humiliated and captured; the fortress will be humiliated and broken down.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 2, 'No one will ever brag about Moab again, for there is a plot against her life. In Heshbon plans have been completed to destroy her. `Come,'' they say, `we will cut her off from being a nation.'' The city of Madmen, too, will be silenced; the sword will follow you there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 3, 'And then the roar of battle will surge against Horonaim,', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 4, 'for all Moab is being destroyed. Her little ones will cry out.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 5, 'Her refugees will climb the hills of Luhith, weeping bitterly, while cries of terror rise from Horonaim below.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 6, 'Flee for your lives! Hide in the wilderness!', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 7, 'Because you have trusted in your wealth and skill, you will be taken captive. Your god Chemosh, with his priests and princes, will be exiled to distant lands!', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 8, '"All the towns will be destroyed, both on the plateaus and in the valleys, for the LORD has spoken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 9, 'Oh, that Moab had wings so she could fly away, for her cities will be left empty, with no one living in them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 10, 'Cursed be those who refuse to do the work the LORD has given them, who hold back their swords from shedding blood!', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 11, '"From her earliest history, Moab has lived in peace. She is like wine that has been allowed to settle. She has not been poured from flask to flask, and she is now fragrant and smooth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 12, 'But the time is coming soon," says the LORD, "when I will send troublemakers to pour her from her jar. They will pour her out, then shatter the jar!', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 13, 'At last Moab will be ashamed of her idol Chemosh, as Israel was ashamed of her gold calf at Bethel.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 14, '"You used to boast, `We are heroes, mighty men of war.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 15, 'But now Moab and her towns will be destroyed. Her most promising youth are doomed to slaughter," says the King, whose name is the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 16, '"Calamity is coming fast to Moab; it threatens ominously.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 17, '"You friends of Moab, weep for her and cry! See how the strong scepter is broken, how the beautiful staff is shattered!', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 18, 'Come down from your glory and sit in the dust, you people of Dibon, for those who destroy Moab will shatter Dibon, too. They will tear down all your towers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 19, 'The people of Aroer stand anxiously beside the road to watch. They shout to those who flee from Moab, `What has happened there?''', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 20, '"And the reply comes back, `Moab lies in ruins; weep and wail! Tell it by the banks of the Arnon River: Moab has been destroyed!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 21, 'All the cities of the plateau lie in ruins, too. Judgment has been poured out on them all--on Holon and Jahaz and Mephaath,', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 22, 'and on Dibon and Nebo and Beth-diblathaim,', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 23, 'and on Kiriathaim and Beth-gamul and Beth-meon,', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 24, 'and on Kerioth and Bozrah--all the cities of Moab, far and near.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 25, '"The strength of Moab has ended. Her horns have been cut off, and her arms have been broken," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 26, '"Let her stagger and fall like a drunkard, for she has rebelled against the LORD. Moab will wallow in her own vomit, ridiculed by all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 27, 'Did you not make Israel the object of your ridicule? Was she caught in the company of thieves that you should despise her as you do?', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 28, '"You people of Moab, flee from your cities and towns! Live in the caves like doves that nest in the clefts of the rocks.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 29, 'We have heard of the pride of Moab, for it is very great. We know of her loftiness, her arrogance, and her haughty heart.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 30, 'I know about her insolence," says the LORD, "but her boasts are false; they accomplish nothing.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 31, 'Yes, I wail for Moab; my heart is broken for the men of Kir-hareseth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 32, '"You people of Sibmah, rich in vineyards, I will weep for you even more than I did for Jazer. Your spreading vines once reached as far as the Dead Sea, but the destroyer has stripped you bare! He has harvested your grapes and summer fruits.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 33, 'Joy and gladness are gone from fruitful Moab. The presses yield no wine. No one treads the grapes with shouts of joy. There is shouting, yes, but not of joy.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 34, 'Instead, their awful cries of terror can be heard from Heshbon clear across to Elealeh and Jahaz; from Zoar all the way to Horonaim and Eglath-shelishiyah. Even the waters of Nimrim are dried up now.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 35, '"I will put an end to Moab," says the LORD, "for they offer sacrifices at the pagan shrines and burn incense to their false gods.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 36, 'My heart moans like a flute for Moab and Kir-hareseth, for all their wealth has disappeared.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 37, 'They shave their heads and beards in mourning. They slash their hands and put on clothes made of sackcloth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 38, 'Crying and sorrow will be in every Moabite home and on every street. For I have smashed Moab like an old, unwanted bottle.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 39, 'How it is broken! Hear the wailing! See the shame of Moab! She has become an object of ridicule, an example of ruin to all her neighbors.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 40, '"An eagle swoops down on the land of Moab," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 41, '"Her cities will fall; her strongholds will be seized. Even the mightiest warriors will be as frightened as a woman about to give birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 42, 'Moab will no longer be a nation, for she has boasted against the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 43, '"Terror and traps and snares will be your lot, O Moab," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 44, '"Those who flee in terror will fall into a trap, and those who escape the trap will step into a snare. I will see to it that you do not get away, for the time of your judgment has come," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 45, '"The people flee as far as Heshbon but are unable to go on. For a fire comes from Heshbon, King Sihon''s ancestral home, to devour the entire land with all its rebellious people.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 46, '"O Moab, your destruction is sure! The people of the god Chemosh are destroyed! Your sons and daughters have been taken away as captives.', 'NLT'),
(28, 48, 47, 'But in the latter days I will restore the fortunes of Moab," says the LORD. This is the end of Jeremiah''s prophecy concerning Moab.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 1, 'This message was given concerning the Ammonites. This is what the LORD says: "What are you doing? Are there no descendants of Israel to inherit the land of Gad? Why are you, who worship Molech, living in its towns?', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 2, 'I will punish you for this," says the LORD, "by destroying your city of Rabbah. It will become a desolate heap, and the neighboring towns will be burned. Then Israel will come and take back the land you took from her," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 3, '"Cry out, O Heshbon, for the town of Ai is destroyed. Weep, O people of Rabbah! Put on your clothes of mourning. Weep and wail, hiding in the hedges, for your god Molech will be exiled along with his princes and priests.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 4, 'You are proud of your fertile valleys, but they will soon be ruined. You rebellious daughter, you trusted in your wealth and thought no one could ever harm you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 5, 'But look! I will bring terror upon you," says the Lord, the LORD Almighty. "Your neighbors will chase you from your land, and no one will help your exiles as they flee.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 6, 'But afterward I will restore the fortunes of the Ammonites," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 7, 'This message was given concerning Edom. This is what the LORD Almighty says: "Where are all the wise men of Teman? Is there no one left to give wise counsel?', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 8, 'Turn and flee! Hide in deep caves, you people of Dedan! For when I bring disaster on Edom, I will punish you, too!', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 9, 'Those who harvest grapes always leave a few for the poor. If thieves came at night, even they would not take everything.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 10, 'But I will strip bare the land of Edom, and there will be no place left to hide. Its children, its brothers, and its neighbors--all will be destroyed--and Edom itself will be no more.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 11, 'But I will preserve the orphans who remain among you. Your widows, too, will be able to depend on me for help."', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 12, 'And this is what the LORD says: "If the innocent must suffer, how much more must you! You will not go unpunished! You must drink this cup of judgment!', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 13, 'For I have sworn by my own name," says the LORD, "that Bozrah will become an object of horror and a heap of rubble; it will be mocked and cursed. All its towns and villages will be desolate forever."', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 14, 'I have heard a message from the LORD that an ambassador was sent to the nations to say, "Form a coalition against Edom, and prepare for battle!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 15, 'This is what the LORD says: "I will cut you down to size among the nations, Edom. You will be despised by all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 16, 'You are proud that you inspire fear in others. And you are proud because you live in a rock fortress and hide high in the mountains. But don''t fool yourselves! Though you live among the peaks with the eagles, I will bring you crashing down," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 17, '"Edom will be an object of horror. All who pass by will be appalled and will gasp at the destruction they see there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 18, 'It will be like the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah and their neighboring towns," says the LORD. "No one will live there anymore.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 19, 'I will come like a lion from the thickets of the Jordan, leaping on the sheep in the pasture. I will chase Edom from its land, and I will appoint the leader of my choice. For who is like me, and who can challenge me? What ruler can oppose my will?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 20, 'Listen to the LORD''s plans for Edom and the people of Teman. Even the little children will be dragged off, and their homes will be empty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 21, 'The earth will shake with the noise of Edom''s fall, and its cry of despair will be heard all the way to the Red Sea.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 22, 'The enemy will come as swiftly as an eagle, and he will spread his wings against Bozrah. Even the mightiest warriors will be as frightened as a woman about to give birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 23, 'This message was given concerning Damascus. This is what the LORD says: "The towns of Hamath and Arpad are struck with fear, for they have heard the news of their destruction. Their hearts are troubled like a wild sea in a raging storm.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 24, 'Damascus has become feeble, and all her people turn to flee. Fear, anguish, and pain have gripped her as they do a woman giving birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 25, 'That famous city, a city of joy, will be forsaken!', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 26, 'Her young men will fall in the streets and die. Her warriors will all be killed," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 27, '"And I will start a fire at the edge of Damascus that will burn up the palaces of Ben-hadad."', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 28, 'This message was given concerning Kedar and the kingdoms of Hazor, which were attacked by King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon. This is what the LORD says: "Advance against Kedar! Blot out the warriors from the East!', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 29, 'Their flocks and tents will be captured, and their household goods and camels will be taken away. Everywhere shouts of panic will be heard: `We are terrorized at every turn!''', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 30, 'Flee for your lives," says the LORD. "Hide yourselves in deep caves, you people of Hazor, for King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon has plotted against you and is preparing to destroy you.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 31, '"Go up and attack those self-sufficient nomadic tribes," says the LORD. "They live alone in the desert without walls or gates.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 32, 'Their camels and cattle will all be yours. I will scatter to the winds these people who live in distant places. I will bring calamity upon them from every direction," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 33, '"Hazor will be inhabited by jackals, and it will be desolate forever. No one will live there anymore."', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 34, 'This message concerning Elam came to the prophet Jeremiah from the LORD at the beginning of the reign of King Zedekiah of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 35, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "I will destroy the archers of Elam--the best of their marksmen.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 36, 'I will bring enemies from all directions, and I will scatter the people of Elam to the four winds. They will be exiled to countries around the world.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 37, 'I myself will go with Elam''s enemies to shatter it. My fierce anger will bring great disaster upon the people of Elam," says the LORD. "Their enemies will chase them with the sword until I have destroyed them completely.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 38, 'I will set my throne in Elam," says the LORD, "and I will destroy its king and princes.', 'NLT'),
(28, 49, 39, 'But in the latter days I will restore the fortunes of Elam," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 1, 'The LORD gave Jeremiah the prophet this message concerning Babylon and the land of the Babylonians.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 2, 'This is what the LORD says: "Tell the whole world, and keep nothing back! Raise a signal flag so everyone will know that Babylon will fall! Her images and idols will be shattered. Her gods Bel and Marduk will be utterly disgraced.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 3, 'For a nation will attack her from the north and bring such destruction that no one will live in her again. Everything will be gone; both people and animals will flee.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 4, '"Then the people of Israel and Judah will join together," says the LORD, "weeping and seeking the LORD their God.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 5, 'They will ask the way to Jerusalem and will start back home again. They will bind themselves to the LORD with an eternal covenant that will never again be broken.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 6, '"My people have been lost sheep. Their shepherds have led them astray and turned them loose in the mountains. They have lost their way and cannot remember how to get back to the fold.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 7, 'All who found them devoured them. Their enemies said, `We are allowed to attack them freely, for they have sinned against the LORD, their place of rest, the hope of their ancestors.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 8, '"But now, flee from Babylon! Leave the land of the Babylonians. Lead my people home again.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 9, 'For look, I am raising up an army of great nations from the north. I will bring them against Babylon to attack her, and she will be captured. The enemies'' arrows will go straight to the mark; they will not miss!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 10, 'Babylonia will be plundered until the attackers are glutted with plunder," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 11, '"You rejoice and are glad, you plunderers of my chosen people. You frisk about like a calf in a meadow and neigh like a stallion.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 12, 'But your homeland will be overwhelmed with shame and disgrace. You will become the least of nations--a wilderness, a dry and desolate land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 13, 'Because of the LORD''s anger, Babylon will become a deserted wasteland. All who pass by will be horrified and will gasp at the destruction they see there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 14, '"Yes, prepare to attack Babylon, all you nations round about. Let your archers shoot at her. Spare no arrows, for she has sinned against the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 15, 'Shout against her from every side. Look! She surrenders! Her walls have fallen. The LORD has taken vengeance, so do not spare her. Do to her as she has done to others!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 16, 'Lead from Babylon all those who plant crops; send all the harvesters away. Let the captives escape the sword of the enemy and rush back to their own lands.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 17, '"The Israelites are like sheep that have been scattered by lions. First the king of Assyria ate them up. Then King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon cracked their bones."', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 18, 'Therefore, the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "Now I will punish the king of Babylon and his land, just as I punished the king of Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 19, 'And I will bring Israel home again to her own land, to feed in the fields of Carmel and Bashan, and to be satisfied once more on the hill country of Ephraim and Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 20, 'In those days," says the LORD, "no sin will be found in Israel or in Judah, for I will forgive the remnant I preserve.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 21, '"Go up, my warriors, against the land of Merathaim and against the people of Pekod. Yes, march against Babylon, the land of rebels, a land that I will judge! Pursue, kill, and completely destroy them, as I have commanded you," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 22, '"Let the battle cry be heard in the land, a shout of great destruction.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 23, 'Babylon, the mightiest hammer in all the earth, lies broken and shattered. Babylon is desolate among the nations!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 24, 'Listen, Babylon, for I have set a trap for you. You are caught, for you have fought against the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 25, '"The LORD has opened his armory and brought out weapons to vent his fury against his enemies. The terror that falls upon the Babylonians will be the work of the Sovereign LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 26, 'Yes, come against her from distant lands. Break open her granaries. Crush her walls and houses into heaps of rubble. Destroy her completely, and leave nothing!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 27, 'Even destroy her cattle--it will be terrible for them, too! Slaughter them all! For the time has come for Babylon to be devastated.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 28, 'Listen to the people who have escaped from Babylon, as they declare in Jerusalem how the LORD our God has taken vengeance against those who destroyed his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 29, '"Send out a call for archers to come to Babylon. Surround the city so none can escape. Do to her as she has done to others, for she has defied the LORD, the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 30, 'Her young men will fall in the streets and die. Her warriors will all be killed," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 31, '"See, I am your enemy, O proud people," says the Lord, the LORD Almighty. "Your day of reckoning has arrived.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 32, 'O land of pride, you will stumble and fall, and no one will raise you up. For I will light a fire in the cities of Babylon that will burn everything around them."', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 33, 'And now the LORD Almighty says this: "The people of Israel and Judah have been wronged. Their captors hold them and refuse to let them go.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 34, 'But the one who redeems them is strong. His name is the LORD Almighty. He will defend them and give them rest again in Israel. But the people of Babylon--there will be no rest for them!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 35, '"The sword of destruction will strike the Babylonians," says the LORD. "It will strike the people of Babylon--her princes and wise men, too.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 36, 'And when it strikes her wise counselors, they will become fools! When it strikes her mightiest warriors, panic will seize them!', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 37, 'When it strikes her horses and chariots, her allies from other lands will become as weak as women. When it strikes her treasures, they all will be plundered.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 38, 'It will even strike her water supply, causing it to dry up. And why? Because the whole land is filled with idols, and the people are madly in love with them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 39, '"Soon this city of Babylon will be inhabited by ostriches and jackals. It will be a home for the wild animals of the desert. Never again will people live there; it will lie desolate forever.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 40, 'I will destroy it just as I destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah and their neighboring towns," says the LORD. "No one will live there anymore.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 41, '"Look! A great army is marching from the north! A great nation and many kings are rising against you from far-off lands.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 42, 'They are fully armed for slaughter. They are cruel and show no mercy. As they ride forward, the noise of their army is like a roaring sea. They are marching in battle formation to destroy you, Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 43, 'The king of Babylon has received reports about the enemy, and he is weak with fright. Fear and pain have gripped him, like that of a woman about to give birth.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 44, '"I will come like a lion from the thickets of the Jordan, leaping on the sheep in the pasture. I will chase Babylon from its land, and I will appoint the leader of my choice. For who is like me, and who can challenge me? What ruler can oppose my will?"', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 45, 'Listen to the LORD''s plans against Babylon and the land of the Babylonians. Even little children will be dragged off, and their homes will be empty.', 'NLT'),
(28, 50, 46, 'The earth will shake with the noise of Babylon''s fall, and her cry of despair will be heard around the world.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 1, 'This is what the LORD says: "I will stir up a destroyer against Babylon and the people of Babylonia.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 2, 'Foreigners will come and winnow her, blowing her away as chaff. They will come from every side to rise against her in her day of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 3, 'Don''t let the archers put on their armor or draw their bows. No one will be spared! Young and old alike will be completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 4, 'They will fall dead in the land of the Babylonians, slashed to death in her streets.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 5, 'For the LORD Almighty has not forsaken Israel and Judah. He is still their God, even though their land was filled with sin against the Holy One of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 6, 'Flee from Babylon! Save yourselves! Don''t get trapped in her punishment! It is the LORD''s time for vengeance; he will fully repay her.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 7, 'Babylon has been like a golden cup in the LORD''s hands, a cup from which he made the whole earth drink and go mad.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 8, 'But now suddenly, Babylon, too, has fallen. Weep for her, and give her medicine. Perhaps she can yet be healed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 9, 'We would have helped her if we could, but nothing can save her now. Let her go; abandon her. Return now to your own land, for her judgment will be so great it cannot be measured.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 10, 'The LORD has vindicated us. Come, let us announce in Jerusalem everything the LORD our God has done.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 11, 'Sharpen the arrows! Lift up the shields! For the LORD has stirred up the spirit of the kings of the Medes to march against Babylon and destroy her. This is his vengeance against those who desecrated his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 12, 'Raise the battle flag against Babylon! Reinforce the guard and station the watchmen. Prepare an ambush, for the LORD will fulfill all his plans against Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 13, 'You are a city rich with water, a great center of commerce, but your end has come. The thread of your life is cut.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 14, 'The LORD Almighty has taken this vow and has sworn to it by his own name: "Your cities will be filled with enemies, like fields filled with locusts, and they will lift their shouts of triumph over you."', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 15, 'He made the earth by his power, and he preserves it by his wisdom. He has stretched out the heavens by his understanding.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 16, 'When he speaks, there is thunder in the heavens. He causes the clouds to rise over the earth. He sends the lightning with the rain and releases the wind from his storehouses.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 17, 'Compared to him, all people are foolish and have no knowledge at all! They make idols, but the idols will disgrace their makers, for they are frauds. They have no life or power in them.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 18, 'Idols are worthless; they are lies! The time is coming when they will all be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 19, 'But the God of Israel is no idol! He is the Creator of everything that exists, including his people, his own special possession. The LORD Almighty is his name!', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 20, '"You are my battle-ax and sword," says the LORD. "With you I will shatter nations and destroy many kingdoms.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 21, 'With you I will shatter armies, destroying the horse and rider, the chariot and charioteer.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 22, 'With you I will shatter men and women, old people and children, young men and maidens.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 23, 'With you I will shatter shepherds and flocks, farmers and oxen, captains and rulers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 24, '"As you watch, I will repay Babylon and the people of Babylonia for all the wrong they have done to my people in Jerusalem," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 25, '"Look, O mighty mountain, destroyer of the earth! I am your enemy," says the LORD. "I will raise my fist against you, to roll you down from the heights. When I am finished, you will be nothing but a heap of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 26, 'You will be desolate forever. Even your stones will never again be used for building. You will be completely wiped out," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 27, 'Signal many nations to mobilize for war against Babylon. Sound the battle cry! Bring out the armies of Ararat, Minni, and Ashkenaz. Appoint a leader, and bring a multitude of horses!', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 28, 'Bring against her the armies of the kings of the Medes and their generals, and the armies of all the countries they rule.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 29, 'Babylon trembles and writhes in pain, for everything the LORD has planned against her stands unchanged. Babylon will be left desolate without a single inhabitant.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 30, 'Her mightiest warriors no longer fight. They stay in their barracks. Their courage is gone. They have become as fearful as women. The invaders have burned the houses and broken down the city gates.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 31, 'Messengers from every side come running to the king to tell him all is lost!', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 32, 'All the escape routes are blocked. The fortifications are burning, and the army is in panic.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 33, 'For the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, says: "Babylon is like wheat on a threshing floor, about to be trampled. In just a little while her harvest will begin."', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 34, '"King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon has eaten and crushed us and emptied out our strength. He has swallowed us like a great monster and filled his belly with our riches. He has thrown us out of our own country.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 35, 'May Babylon be repaid for all the violence she did to us," say the people of Jerusalem. "May the people of Babylonia be paid in full for all the blood they spilled," says Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 36, 'The LORD says to Jerusalem, "I will be your lawyer to plead your case, and I will avenge you. I will dry up her river, her water supply,', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 37, 'and Babylon will become a heap of rubble, haunted by jackals. It will be an object of horror and contempt, without a single person living there.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 38, '"In their drunken feasts, the people of Babylon roar like lions.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 39, 'And while they lie inflamed with all their wine, I will prepare a different kind of feast for them. I will make them drink until they fall asleep, never again to waken," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 40, '"I will bring them like lambs to the slaughter, like rams and goats to be sacrificed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 41, '"How Babylon is fallen--great Babylon, praised throughout the earth! The world can scarcely believe its eyes at her fall!', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 42, 'The sea has risen over Babylon; she is covered by its waves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 43, 'Her cities now lie in ruins; she is a dry wilderness where no one lives or even passes by.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 44, 'And I will punish Bel, the god of Babylon, and pull from his mouth what he has taken. The nations will no longer come and worship him. The wall of Babylon has fallen.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 45, '"Listen, my people, flee from Babylon. Save yourselves! Run from the LORD''s fierce anger.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 46, 'But do not panic when you hear the first rumor of approaching forces. For rumors will keep coming year by year. Then there will be a time of violence as the leaders fight against each other.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 47, 'For the time is surely coming when I will punish this great city and all her idols. Her whole land will be disgraced, and her dead will lie in the streets.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 48, 'The heavens and earth will rejoice, for out of the north will come destroying armies against Babylon," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 49, '"Just as Babylon killed the people of Israel and others throughout the world, so must her people be killed.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 50, 'Go, you who escaped the sword! Do not stand and watch--flee while you can! Remember the LORD, even though you are in a far-off land, and think about your home in Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 51, '"We are ashamed," the people say. "We are insulted and disgraced because the LORD''s Temple has been defiled by foreigners."', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 52, '"Yes," says the LORD, "but the time is coming when Babylon''s idols will be destroyed. The groans of her wounded people will be heard throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 53, 'Though Babylon reaches as high as the heavens, and though she increases her strength immeasurably, I will send enemies to plunder her," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 54, 'Listen! Hear the cry of Babylon, the sound of great destruction from the land of the Babylonians.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 55, 'For the LORD is destroying Babylon. He will silence her. Waves of enemies pound against her; the noise of battle rings through the city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 56, 'Destroying armies come against Babylon. Her mighty men are captured, and their weapons break in their hands. For the LORD is a God who gives just punishment, and he is giving Babylon all she deserves.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 57, '"I will make drunk her officials, wise men, rulers, captains, and warriors," says the King, whose name is the LORD Almighty. "They will fall asleep and never wake up again!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 58, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: "The wide walls of Babylon will be leveled to the ground, and her high gates will be burned. The builders from many lands have worked in vain, for their work will be destroyed by fire!"', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 59, 'The prophet Jeremiah gave this message to Zedekiah''s staff officer, Seraiah son of Neriah and grandson of Mahseiah, when he went to Babylon with King Zedekiah of Judah. This was during the fourth year of Zedekiah''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 60, 'Jeremiah had recorded on a scroll all the terrible disasters that would soon come upon Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 61, 'He said to Seraiah, "When you get to Babylon, read aloud everything on this scroll.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 62, 'Then say, `LORD, you have said that you will destroy Babylon so that neither people nor animals will remain here. She will lie empty and abandoned forever.''', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 63, 'Then, when you have finished reading the scroll, tie it to a stone, and throw it into the Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(28, 51, 64, 'Then say, `In this same way Babylon and her people will sink, never again to rise, because of the disasters I will bring upon her.''" This is the end of Jeremiah''s messages.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 1, 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother''s name was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah from Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 2, 'But Zedekiah did what was evil in the LORD''s sight, just as Jehoiakim had done.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 3, 'So the LORD, in his anger, finally banished the people of Jerusalem and Judah from his presence and sent them into exile. Then Zedekiah rebelled against the king of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 4, 'So on January 15, during the ninth year of Zedekiah''s reign, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon led his entire army against Jerusalem. They surrounded the city and built siege ramps against its walls.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 5, 'Jerusalem was kept under siege until the eleventh year of King Zedekiah''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 6, 'By July 18 of Zedekiah''s eleventh year, the famine in the city had become very severe, with the last of the food entirely gone.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 7, 'Then a section of the city wall was broken down, and all the soldiers made plans to escape from the city. But since the city was surrounded by the Babylonians, they waited for nightfall and fled through the gate between the two walls behind the king''s gardens. They made a dash across the fields, in the direction of the Jordan Valley.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 8, 'But the Babylonians chased after them and caught King Zedekiah on the plains of Jericho, for by then his men had all abandoned him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 9, 'They brought him to the king of Babylon at Riblah, in the land of Hamath, where sentence was passed against him.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 10, 'There at Riblah, the king of Babylon made Zedekiah watch as all his sons were killed; they also killed all the other leaders of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 11, 'Then they gouged out Zedekiah''s eyes, bound him in bronze chains, and led him away to Babylon. Zedekiah remained there in prison for the rest of his life.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 12, 'On August 17 of that year, which was the nineteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar''s reign, Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, an official of the Babylonian king, arrived in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 13, 'He burned down the Temple of the LORD, the royal palace, and all the houses of Jerusalem. He destroyed all the important buildings in the city.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 14, 'Then the captain of the guard supervised the entire Babylonian army as they tore down the walls of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 15, 'Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, then took as exiles some of the poorest of the people and those who remained in the city, along with the rest of the craftsmen and the troops who had declared their allegiance to the king of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 16, 'But Nebuzaradan allowed some of the poorest people to stay behind in Judah to care for the vineyards and fields.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 17, 'The Babylonians broke up the bronze pillars, the bronze water carts, and the bronze Sea that were at the LORD''s Temple, and they carried all the bronze away to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 18, 'They also took all the pots, shovels, lamp snuffers, basins, dishes, and all the other bronze utensils used for making sacrifices at the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 19, 'Nebuzaradan, captain of the guard, also took the small bowls, firepans, basins, pots, lampstands, dishes, bowls used for drink offerings, and all the other utensils made of pure gold or silver.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 20, 'The bronze from the two pillars, the water carts, and the Sea with the twelve bulls beneath it was too great to be measured. These things had been made for the LORD''s Temple in the days of King Solomon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 21, 'Each of the pillars was 27 feet tall and 18 feet in circumference. They were hollow, with walls 3 inches thick.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 22, 'The bronze capital on top of each pillar was 7 1/2 feet high and was decorated with a network of bronze pomegranates all the way around.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 23, 'There were ninety-six pomegranates on the sides, and a total of one hundred on the network around the top.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 24, 'The captain of the guard took with him as prisoners Seraiah the chief priest, his assistant Zephaniah, and the three chief gatekeepers.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 25, 'And of the people still hiding in the city, he took an officer of the Judean army, seven of the king''s personal advisers, the army commander''s chief secretary, who was in charge of recruitment, and sixty other citizens.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 26, 'Nebuzaradan the commander took them all to the king of Babylon at Riblah.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 27, 'And there at Riblah in the land of Hamath, the king of Babylon had them all put to death. So the people of Judah were sent into exile from their land.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 28, 'The number of captives taken to Babylon in the seventh year of Nebuchadnezzar''s reign was 3,023.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 29, 'Then in Nebuchadnezzar''s eighteenth year he took 832 more.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 30, 'In his twenty-third year he sent Nebuzaradan, his captain of the guard, who took 745 more--a total of 4,600 captives in all.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 31, 'In the thirty-seventh year of King Jehoiachin''s exile in Babylon, Evil-merodach ascended to the Babylonian throne. He was kind to Jehoiachin and released him from prison on March 31 of that year.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 32, 'He spoke pleasantly to Jehoiachin and gave him preferential treatment over all the other exiled kings in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 33, 'He supplied Jehoiachin with new clothes to replace his prison garb and allowed him to dine at the king''s table for the rest of his life.', 'NLT'),
(28, 52, 34, 'The Babylonian king also gave him a regular allowance to cover his living expenses until the day of his death.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 1, 'Jerusalem''s streets, once bustling with people, are now silent. Like a widow broken with grief, she sits alone in her mourning. Once the queen of nations, she is now a slave.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 2, 'She sobs through the night; tears stream down her cheeks. Among all her lovers, there is no one left to help her. All her friends have betrayed her; they are now her enemies.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 3, 'Judah has been led away into captivity, afflicted and enslaved. She lives among foreign nations and has no place of rest. Her enemies have chased her down, and she has nowhere to turn.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 4, 'The roads to Jerusalem are in mourning, no longer filled with crowds on their way to celebrate the Temple festivals. The city gates are silent, her priests groan, her young women are crying--how bitterly Jerusalem weeps!', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 5, 'Her oppressors have become her masters, and her enemies prosper, for the LORD has punished Jerusalem for her many sins. Her children have been captured and taken away to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 6, 'All the beauty and majesty of Jerusalem are gone. Her princes are like starving deer searching for pasture, too weak to run from the pursuing enemy.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 7, 'And now in the midst of her sadness and wandering, Jerusalem remembers her ancient splendor. But then she fell to her enemy, and there was no one to help her. Her enemy struck her down and laughed as she fell.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 8, 'Jerusalem has sinned greatly, so she has been tossed away like a filthy rag. All who once honored her now despise her, for they have seen her stripped naked and humiliated. All she can do is groan and hide her face.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 9, 'She defiled herself with immorality with no thought of the punishment that would follow. Now she lies in the gutter with no one to lift her out. "LORD, see my deep misery," she cries. "The enemy has triumphed."', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 10, 'The enemy has plundered her completely, taking everything precious that she owns. She has seen foreigners violate her sacred Temple, the place the LORD had forbidden them to enter.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 11, 'Her people groan as they search for bread. They have sold their treasures for food to stay alive. "O LORD, look," she mourns, "and see how I am despised.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 12, '"Is it nothing to you, all you who pass by? Look around and see if there is any suffering like mine, which the LORD brought on me in the day of his fierce anger.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 13, '"He has sent fire from heaven that burns in my bones. He has placed a trap in my path and turned me back. He has made me desolate, racked with sickness all day long.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 14, '"He wove my sins into ropes to hitch me to a yoke of captivity. The Lord sapped my strength and gave me to my enemies; I am helpless in their hands.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 15, '"The Lord has treated my mighty men with contempt. At his command a great army has come to crush my young warriors. The Lord has trampled his beloved city as grapes are trampled in a winepress.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 16, '"For all these things I weep; tears flow down my cheeks. No one is here to comfort me; any who might encourage me are far away. My children have no future, for the enemy has conquered us."', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 17, 'Jerusalem pleads for help, but no one comforts her. Regarding his people, the LORD has said, "Let their neighbors be their enemies! Let them be thrown away like a filthy rag!"', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 18, '"And the LORD is right," she groans, "for I rebelled against him. Listen, people everywhere; look upon my anguish and despair, for my sons and daughters have been taken captive to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 19, '"I begged my allies for help, but they betrayed me. My priests and leaders starved to death in the city, even as they searched for food to save their lives.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 20, '"LORD, see my anguish! My heart is broken and my soul despairs, for I have rebelled against you. In the streets the sword kills, and at home there is only death.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 21, '"Others heard my groans, but no one turned to comfort me. When my enemies heard of my troubles, they were happy to see what you had done. Oh, bring the day you promised, when you will destroy them as you have destroyed me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 1, 22, '"Look at all their evil deeds, LORD. Punish them, as you have punished me for all my sins. My groans are many, and my heart is faint."', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 1, 'The Lord in his anger has cast a dark shadow over Jerusalem. The fairest of Israel''s cities lies in the dust, thrown down from the heights of heaven. In his day of awesome fury, the Lord has shown no mercy even to his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 2, 'Without mercy the Lord has destroyed every home in Israel. In his anger he has broken down the fortress walls of Jerusalem. He has brought to dust the kingdom and all its rulers.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 3, 'All the strength of Israel vanishes beneath his fury. The Lord has withdrawn his protection as the enemy attacks. He consumes the whole land of Israel like a raging fire.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 4, 'He bends his bow against his people as though he were their enemy. His strength is used against them to kill their finest youth. His fury is poured out like fire on beautiful Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 5, 'Yes, the Lord has vanquished Israel like an enemy. He has destroyed her forts and palaces. He has brought unending sorrow and tears to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 6, 'He has broken down his Temple as though it were merely a garden shelter. The LORD has blotted out all memory of the holy festivals and Sabbath days. Kings and priests fall together before his anger.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 7, 'The Lord has rejected his own altar; he despises his own sanctuary. He has given Jerusalem''s palaces to her enemies. They shout in the LORD''s Temple as though it were a day of celebration.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 8, 'The LORD was determined to destroy the walls of Jerusalem. He made careful plans for their destruction, then he went ahead and did it. Therefore, the ramparts and walls have fallen down before him.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 9, 'Jerusalem''s gates have sunk into the ground. All their locks and bars are destroyed, for he has smashed them. Her kings and princes have been exiled to distant lands; the law is no more. Her prophets receive no more visions from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 10, 'The leaders of Jerusalem sit on the ground in silence, clothed in sackcloth. They throw dust on their heads in sorrow and despair. The young women of Jerusalem hang their heads in shame.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 11, 'I have cried until the tears no longer come. My heart is broken, my spirit poured out, as I see what has happened to my people. Little children and tiny babies are fainting and dying in the streets.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 12, '"Mama, we want food," they cry, and then collapse in their mothers'' arms. Their lives ebb away like the life of a warrior wounded in battle.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 13, 'In all the world has there ever been such sorrow? O daughter of Jerusalem, to what can I compare your anguish? O virgin daughter of Zion, how can I comfort you? For your wound is as deep as the sea. Who can heal you?', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 14, 'Your "prophets" have said so many foolish things, false to the core. They did not try to hold you back from exile by pointing out your sins. Instead, they painted false pictures, filling you with false hope.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 15, 'All who pass by jeer at you. They scoff and insult Jerusalem, saying, "Is this the city called `Most Beautiful in All the World'' and `Joy of All the Earth''?"', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 16, 'All your enemies deride you. They scoff and grind their teeth and say, "We have destroyed her at last! Long have we awaited this day, and it is finally here!"', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 17, 'But it is the LORD who did it just as he warned. He has fulfilled the promises of disaster he made long ago. He has destroyed Jerusalem without mercy and caused her enemies to rejoice over her and boast of their power.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 18, 'Cry aloud before the Lord, O walls of Jerusalem! Let your tears flow like a river. Give yourselves no rest from weeping day or night.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 19, 'Rise during the night and cry out. Pour out your hearts like water to the Lord. Lift up your hands to him in prayer. Plead for your children as they faint with hunger in the streets.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 20, '"O LORD, think about this!" Jerusalem cries. "You are doing this to your own people! Should mothers eat their little children, those they once bounced on their knees? Should priests and prophets die within the Lord''s Temple?', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 21, '"See them lying in the streets--young and old, boys and girls, killed by the swords of the enemy. You have killed them in your anger, slaughtering them without mercy.', 'NLT'),
(29, 2, 22, '"You have invited terrors from all around as though you were calling them to a day of feasting. In the day of the LORD''s anger, no one has escaped or survived. The enemy has killed all the children I bore and raised."', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 1, 'I am the one who has seen the afflictions that come from the rod of the LORD''s anger.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 2, 'He has brought me into deep darkness, shutting out all light.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 3, 'He has turned against me. Day and night his hand is heavy upon me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 4, 'He has made my skin and flesh grow old. He has broken my bones.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 5, 'He has attacked me and surrounded me with anguish and distress.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 6, 'He has buried me in a dark place, like a person long dead.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 7, 'He has walled me in, and I cannot escape. He has bound me in heavy chains.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 8, 'And though I cry and shout, he shuts out my prayers.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 9, 'He has blocked my path with a high stone wall. He has twisted the road before me with many detours.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 10, 'He hid like a bear or a lion, waiting to attack me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 11, 'He dragged me off the path and tore me with his claws, leaving me helpless and desolate.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 12, 'He bent his bow and aimed it squarely at me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 13, 'He shot his arrows deep into my heart.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 14, 'My own people laugh at me. All day long they sing their mocking songs.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 15, 'He has filled me with bitterness. He has given me a cup of deep sorrow to drink.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 16, 'He has made me grind my teeth on gravel. He has rolled me in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 17, 'Peace has been stripped away, and I have forgotten what prosperity is.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 18, 'I cry out, "My splendor is gone! Everything I had hoped for from the LORD is lost!"', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 19, 'The thought of my suffering and homelessness is bitter beyond words.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 20, 'I will never forget this awful time, as I grieve over my loss.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 21, 'Yet I still dare to hope when I remember this:', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 22, 'The unfailing love of the LORD never ends! By his mercies we have been kept from complete destruction.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 23, 'Great is his faithfulness; his mercies begin afresh each day.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 24, 'I say to myself, "The LORD is my inheritance; therefore, I will hope in him!"', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 25, 'The LORD is wonderfully good to those who wait for him and seek him.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 26, 'So it is good to wait quietly for salvation from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 27, 'And it is good for the young to submit to the yoke of his discipline.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 28, 'Let them sit alone in silence beneath the LORD''s demands.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 29, 'Let them lie face down in the dust; then at last there is hope for them.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 30, 'Let them turn the other cheek to those who strike them. Let them accept the insults of their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 31, 'For the Lord does not abandon anyone forever.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 32, 'Though he brings grief, he also shows compassion according to the greatness of his unfailing love.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 33, 'For he does not enjoy hurting people or causing them sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 34, 'But the leaders of his people trampled prisoners underfoot.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 35, 'They deprived people of their God-given rights in defiance of the Most High.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 36, 'They perverted justice in the courts. Do they think the Lord didn''t see it?', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 37, 'Can anything happen without the Lord''s permission?', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 38, 'Is it not the Most High who helps one and harms another?', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 39, 'Then why should we, mere humans, complain when we are punished for our sins?', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 40, 'Instead, let us test and examine our ways. Let us turn again in repentance to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 41, 'Let us lift our hearts and hands to God in heaven and say,', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 42, '"We have sinned and rebelled, and you have not forgiven us.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 43, '"You have engulfed us with your anger, chased us down, and slaughtered us without mercy.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 44, 'You have hidden yourself in a cloud so our prayers cannot reach you.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 45, 'You have discarded us as refuse and garbage among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 46, '"All our enemies have spoken out against us.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 47, 'We are filled with fear, for we are trapped, desolate, and ruined."', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 48, 'Streams of tears flow from my eyes because of the destruction of my people!', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 49, 'My tears flow down endlessly. They will not stop', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 50, 'until the LORD looks down from heaven and sees.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 51, 'My heart is breaking over the fate of all the women of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 52, 'My enemies, whom I have never harmed, chased me like a bird.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 53, 'They threw me into a pit and dropped stones on me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 54, 'The water flowed above my head, and I cried out, "This is the end!"', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 55, 'But I called on your name, LORD, from deep within the well,', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 56, 'and you heard me! You listened to my pleading; you heard my weeping!', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 57, 'Yes, you came at my despairing cry and told me, "Do not fear."', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 58, 'Lord, you are my lawyer! Plead my case! For you have redeemed my life.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 59, 'You have seen the wrong they have done to me, LORD. Be my judge, and prove me right.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 60, 'You have seen the plots my enemies have laid against me.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 61, 'LORD, you have heard the vile names they call me. You know all about the plans they have made--', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 62, 'the plots my enemies whisper and mutter against me all day long.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 63, 'Look at them! In all their activities, they constantly mock me with their songs.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 64, 'Pay them back, LORD, for all the evil they have done.', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 65, 'Give them hard and stubborn hearts, and then let your curse fall upon them!', 'NLT'),
(29, 3, 66, 'Chase them down in your anger, destroying them from beneath the LORD''s heavens.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 1, 'How the gold has lost its luster! Even the finest gold has become dull. The sacred gemstones lie scattered in the streets!', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 2, 'See how the precious children of Jerusalem, worth their weight in gold, are now treated like pots of clay.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 3, 'Even the jackals feed their young, but not my people Israel. They ignore their children''s cries, like the ostriches of the desert.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 4, 'The parched tongues of their little ones stick with thirst to the roofs of their mouths. The children cry for bread, but no one has any to give them.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 5, 'The people who once ate only the richest foods now beg in the streets for anything they can get. Those who once lived in palaces now search the garbage pits for food.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 6, 'The guilt of my people is greater than that of Sodom, where utter disaster struck in a moment with no one to help them.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 7, 'Our princes were once glowing with health; they were as clean as snow and as elegant as jewels.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 8, 'But now their faces are blacker than soot. No one even recognizes them. Their skin sticks to their bones; it is as dry and hard as wood.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 9, 'Those killed by the sword are far better off than those who die of hunger, wasting away for want of food.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 10, 'Tenderhearted women have cooked their own children and eaten them in order to survive the siege.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 11, 'But now the anger of the LORD is satisfied. His fiercest anger has now been poured out. He started a fire in Jerusalem that burned the city to its foundations.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 12, 'Not a king in all the earth--no one in all the world--would have believed an enemy could march through the gates of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 13, 'Yet it happened because of the sins of her prophets and priests, who defiled the city by shedding innocent blood.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 14, 'They wandered blindly through the streets, so defiled by blood that no one dared to touch them.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 15, '"Get away!" the people shouted at them. "You are defiled! Don''t touch us!" So they fled to distant lands and wandered there among foreign nations, but none would let them stay.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 16, 'The LORD himself has scattered them, and he no longer helps them. The priests and leaders are no longer honored and respected.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 17, 'We looked in vain for our allies to come and save us, but we were looking to nations that could offer no help at all.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 18, 'We couldn''t go into the streets without danger to our lives. Our end was near; our days were numbered. We were doomed!', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 19, 'Our enemies were swifter than the eagles. If we fled to the mountains, they found us. If we hid in the wilderness, they were waiting for us there.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 20, 'Our king, the LORD''s anointed, the very life of our nation, was caught in their snares. We had foolishly boasted that under his protection we could hold our own against any nation on earth!', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 21, 'Are you rejoicing in the land of Uz, O people of Edom? But you, too, must drink from the cup of the LORD''s anger. You, too, will be stripped naked in your drunkenness.', 'NLT'),
(29, 4, 22, 'O Jerusalem, your punishment will end; you will soon return from exile. But Edom, your punishment is just beginning; soon your many sins will be revealed.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 1, 'LORD, remember everything that has happened to us. See all the sorrows we bear!', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 2, 'Our inheritance has been turned over to strangers, our homes to foreigners.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 3, 'We are orphaned and fatherless. Our mothers are widowed.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 4, 'We have to pay for water to drink, and even firewood is expensive.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 5, 'Those who pursue us are at our heels; we are exhausted but are given no rest.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 6, 'We submitted to Egypt and Assyria to get enough food to survive.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 7, 'It was our ancestors who sinned, but they died before the hand of judgment fell. We have suffered the punishment they deserved!', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 8, 'Slaves have now become our masters; there is no one left to rescue us.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 9, 'We must hunt for food in the wilderness at the risk of our lives.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 10, 'Because of the famine, our skin has been blackened as though baked in an oven.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 11, 'Our enemies rape the women and young girls in Jerusalem and throughout the towns of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 12, 'Our princes are being hanged by their thumbs, and the old men are treated with contempt.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 13, 'The young men are led away to work at millstones, and the children stagger under heavy loads of wood.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 14, 'The old men no longer sit in the city gates; the young men no longer dance and sing.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 15, 'The joy of our hearts has ended; our dancing has turned to mourning.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 16, 'The garlands have fallen from our heads. Disaster has fallen upon us because we have sinned.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 17, 'Our hearts are sick and weary, and our eyes grow dim with tears.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 18, 'For Jerusalem is empty and desolate, a place haunted by jackals.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 19, 'But LORD, you remain the same forever! Your throne continues from generation to generation.', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 20, 'Why do you continue to forget us? Why have you forsaken us for so long?', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 21, 'Restore us, O LORD, and bring us back to you again! Give us back the joys we once had!', 'NLT'),
(29, 5, 22, 'Or have you utterly rejected us? Are you angry with us still?', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 1, 'On July 31 of my thirtieth year, while I was with the Judean exiles beside the Kebar River in Babylon, the heavens were opened to me, and I saw visions of God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 2, 'This happened during the fifth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 3, 'The LORD gave a message to me, Ezekiel son of Buzi, a priest, there beside the Kebar River in the land of the Babylonians, and I felt the hand of the LORD take hold of me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 4, 'As I looked, I saw a great storm coming toward me from the north, driving before it a huge cloud that flashed with lightning and shone with brilliant light. The fire inside the cloud glowed like gleaming amber.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 5, 'From the center of the cloud came four living beings that looked human,', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 6, 'except that each had four faces and two pairs of wings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 7, 'Their legs were straight like human legs, but their feet were split like calves'' feet and shone like burnished bronze.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 8, 'Beneath each of their wings I could see human hands.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 9, 'The wings of each living being touched the wings of the two beings beside it. The living beings were able to fly in any direction without turning around.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 10, 'Each had a human face in the front, the face of a lion on the right side, the face of an ox on the left side, and the face of an eagle at the back.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 11, 'Each had two pairs of outstretched wings--one pair stretched out to touch the wings of the living beings on either side of it, and the other pair covered its body.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 12, 'They went in whatever direction the spirit chose, and they moved straight forward in all directions without having to turn around.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 13, 'The living beings looked like bright coals of fire or brilliant torches, and it looked as though lightning was flashing back and forth among them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 14, 'And the living beings darted to and fro like flashes of lightning.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 15, 'As I looked at these beings, I saw four wheels on the ground beneath them, one wheel belonging to each.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 16, 'The wheels sparkled as if made of chrysolite. All four wheels looked the same; each wheel had a second wheel turning crosswise within it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 17, 'The beings could move forward in any of the four directions they faced, without turning as they moved.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 18, 'The rims of the four wheels were awesomely tall, and they were covered with eyes all around the edges.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 19, 'When the four living beings moved, the wheels moved with them. When they flew upward, the wheels went up, too.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 20, 'The spirit of the four living beings was in the wheels. So wherever the spirit went, the wheels and the living beings went, too.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 21, 'When the living beings moved, the wheels moved. When the living beings stopped, the wheels stopped. When the living beings flew into the air, the wheels rose up. For the spirit of the living beings was in the wheels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 22, 'There was a surface spread out above them like the sky. It sparkled like crystal.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 23, 'Beneath this surface the wings of each living being stretched out to touch the others'' wings, and each had two wings covering its body.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 24, 'As they flew their wings roared like waves crashing against the shore, or like the voice of the Almighty, or like the shouting of a mighty army. When they stopped, they let down their wings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 25, 'As they stood with their wings lowered, a voice spoke from beyond the crystal surface above them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 26, 'Above the surface over their heads was what looked like a throne made of blue sapphire. And high above this throne was a figure whose appearance was like that of a man.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 27, 'From his waist up, he looked like gleaming amber, flickering like a fire. And from his waist down, he looked like a burning flame, shining with splendor.', 'NLT'),
(30, 1, 28, 'All around him was a glowing halo, like a rainbow shining through the clouds. This was the way the glory of the LORD appeared to me. When I saw it, I fell face down in the dust, and I heard someone''s voice speaking to me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 1, '"Stand up, son of man," said the voice. "I want to speak with you."', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 2, 'The Spirit came into me as he spoke and set me on my feet. I listened carefully to his words.', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 3, '"Son of man," he said, "I am sending you to the nation of Israel, a nation that is rebelling against me. Their ancestors have rebelled against me from the beginning, and they are still in revolt to this very day.', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 4, 'They are a hard-hearted and stubborn people. But I am sending you to say to them, `This is what the Sovereign LORD says!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 5, 'And whether they listen or not--for remember, they are rebels--at least they will know they have had a prophet among them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 6, '"Son of man, do not fear them. Don''t be afraid even though their threats are sharp as thorns and barbed like briers, and they sting like scorpions. Do not be dismayed by their dark scowls. For remember, they are rebels!', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 7, 'You must give them my messages whether they listen or not. But they won''t listen, for they are completely rebellious!', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 8, 'Son of man, listen to what I say to you. Do not join them in being a rebel. Open your mouth, and eat what I give you."', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 9, 'Then I looked and saw a hand reaching out to me, and it held a scroll.', 'NLT'),
(30, 2, 10, 'He unrolled it, and I saw that both sides were covered with funeral songs, other words of sorrow, and pronouncements of doom.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 1, 'The voice said to me, "Son of man, eat what I am giving you--eat this scroll! Then go and give its message to the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 2, 'So I opened my mouth, and he fed me the scroll.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 3, '"Eat it all," he said. And when I ate it, it tasted as sweet as honey.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 4, 'Then he said, "Son of man, go to the people of Israel with my messages.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 5, 'I am not sending you to some foreign people whose language you cannot understand.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 6, 'No, I am not sending you to people with strange and difficult speech. If I did, they would listen!', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 7, 'I am sending you to the people of Israel, but they won''t listen to you any more than they listen to me! For the whole lot of them are hard-hearted and stubborn.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 8, 'But look, I have made you as hard and stubborn as they are.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 9, 'I have made you as hard as rock! So don''t be afraid of them or fear their angry looks, even though they are such rebels."', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 10, 'Then he added, "Son of man, let all my words sink deep into your own heart first. Listen to them carefully for yourself.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 11, 'Then go to your people in exile and say to them, `This is what the Sovereign LORD says!'' Do this whether they listen to you or not."', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 12, 'Then the Spirit lifted me up, and I heard a loud rumbling sound behind me. (May the glory of the LORD be praised in his place!)', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 13, 'It was the sound of the wings of the living beings as they brushed against each other and the rumbling of their wheels beneath them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 14, 'The Spirit lifted me up and took me away. I went in bitterness and turmoil, but the LORD''s hold on me was strong.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 15, 'Then I came to the colony of Judean exiles in Tel-abib, beside the Kebar River. I sat there among them for seven days, overwhelmed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 16, 'At the end of the seven days, the LORD gave me a message. He said,', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 17, '"Son of man, I have appointed you as a watchman for Israel. Whenever you receive a message from me, pass it on to the people immediately.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 18, 'If I warn the wicked, saying, `You are under the penalty of death,'' but you fail to deliver the warning, they will die in their sins. And I will hold you responsible, demanding your blood for theirs.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 19, 'If you warn them and they keep on sinning and refuse to repent, they will die in their sins. But you will have saved your life because you did what you were told to do.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 20, 'If good people turn bad and don''t listen to my warning, they will die. If you did not warn them of the consequences, then they will die in their sins. Their previous good deeds won''t help them, and I will hold you responsible, demanding your blood for theirs.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 21, 'But if you warn them and they repent, they will live, and you will have saved your own life, too."', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 22, 'Then the LORD took hold of me, and he said to me, "Go out into the valley, and I will talk to you there."', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 23, 'So I got up and went, and there I saw the glory of the LORD, just as I had seen it in my first vision by the Kebar River. And I fell face down in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 24, 'Then the Spirit came into me and set me on my feet. He talked to me and said, "Go, shut yourself up in your house.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 25, 'There you will be bound with ropes so you cannot go out among the people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 26, 'And I will make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth so you won''t be able to pray for them, for they are rebellious.', 'NLT'),
(30, 3, 27, 'But whenever I give you a message, I will loosen your tongue and let you speak. Then you will say to them, `This is what the Sovereign LORD says!'' Some of them will listen, but some will ignore you, for they are rebels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 1, '"And now, son of man, take a large brick and set it down in front of you. Then draw a map of the city of Jerusalem on it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 2, 'Build siege ramps against the city walls. Surround it with enemy camps and battering rams.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 3, 'Then take an iron griddle and place it between you and the city. Turn toward it and demonstrate how the enemy will attack Jerusalem. This will be a warning to the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 4, '"Now lie on your left side and place the sins of Israel on yourself. You are to bear their sins for the number of days you lie there on your side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 5, 'You will bear Israel''s sins for 390 days--one day for each year of their sin.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 6, 'After that, turn over and lie on your right side for 40 days--one day for each year of Judah''s sin.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 7, '"Meanwhile, continue your demonstration of the siege of Jerusalem. Lie there with your arm bared and prophesy her destruction.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 8, 'I will tie you up with ropes so you won''t be able to turn from side to side until the days of your siege have been completed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 9, '"Now go and get some wheat, barley, beans, lentils, millet, and spelt, and mix them together in a storage jar. Use this food to make bread for yourself during the 390 days you will be lying on your side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 10, 'Ration this out to yourself, eight ounces of food for each day, and eat it at set times.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 11, 'Then measure out a jar of water for each day, and drink it at set times.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 12, 'Each day prepare your bread as you would barley cakes. While all the people are watching, bake it over a fire using dried human dung as fuel and then eat the bread.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 13, 'For this is what the LORD says: Israel will eat defiled bread in the Gentile lands, where I will banish them!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 14, 'Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, must I be defiled by using human dung? For I have never been defiled before. From the time I was a child until now I have never eaten any animal that died of sickness or that I found dead. And I have never eaten any of the animals that our laws forbid."', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 15, '"All right," the LORD said. "You may bake your bread with cow dung instead of human dung."', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 16, 'Then he told me, "Son of man, I will cause food to be very scarce in Jerusalem. It will be weighed out with great care and eaten fearfully. The water will be portioned out drop by drop, and the people will drink it with dismay.', 'NLT'),
(30, 4, 17, 'Food and water will be so scarce that the people will look at one another in terror, and they will waste away under their punishment.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 1, '"Son of man, take a sharp sword and use it as a razor to shave your head and beard. Use a scale to weigh the hair into three equal parts.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 2, 'Place a third of it at the center of your map of Jerusalem. After acting out the siege, burn it there. Scatter another third across your map and slash at it with a sword. Scatter the last third to the wind, for I will scatter my people with the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 3, 'Keep just a bit of the hair and tie it up in your robe.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 4, 'Then take a few of these hairs out and throw them into the fire, burning them up. A fire will then spread from this remnant and destroy all of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 5, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: This is an illustration of what will happen to Jerusalem. I placed her at the center of the nations,', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 6, 'but she has rebelled against my regulations and has been even more wicked than the surrounding nations. She has refused to obey the laws I gave her to follow.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 7, 'So this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Since you have refused to obey my laws and regulations and have behaved even worse than your neighbors,', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 8, 'I myself, the Sovereign LORD, am now your enemy. I will punish you publicly while all the nations watch.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 9, 'Because of your detestable idols, I will punish you more severely than I have punished anyone before or ever will again.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 10, 'Parents will eat their own children, and children will eat their parents. And I will punish you by scattering the few who survive to the far reaches of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 11, '"As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, I will cut you off completely. I will show you no pity at all because you have defiled my Temple with idols and vile practices.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 12, 'A third of your people will die in the city from famine and disease. A third of them will be slaughtered by the enemy outside the city walls. And I will scatter a third to the winds and chase them with my sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 13, 'Then at last my anger will be spent, and I will be satisfied. And when my fury against them has subsided, all Israel will know that I, the LORD, have spoken to them in my jealous anger.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 14, '"So I will turn you into a ruin, a mockery in the eyes of the surrounding nations and to everyone who travels by.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 15, 'You will become an object of mockery and taunting and horror. You will be a warning to all the nations around you. They will see what happens when the LORD turns against a nation in furious rebuke. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 16, '"I will shower you with the deadly arrows of famine to destroy you. The famine will become more and more severe until every crumb of food is gone.', 'NLT'),
(30, 5, 17, 'And along with the famine, wild animals will attack you, robbing you of your children. Disease and war will stalk your land, and I will bring the sword of the enemy against you. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 1, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 2, '"Son of man, look over toward the mountains of Israel and prophesy against them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 3, 'Give the mountains of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD. This is what the Sovereign LORD says to the mountains and hills and to the ravines and valleys: I am about to bring war upon you, and I will destroy your pagan shrines.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 4, 'All your altars will be demolished, and your incense altars will be smashed. I will kill your people in front of your idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 5, 'I will lay your corpses in front of your idols and scatter your bones around your altars.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 6, 'Wherever you live there will be desolation. I will destroy your pagan shrines, your altars, your idols, your incense altars, and all the other religious objects you have made.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 7, 'Then when the place is littered with corpses, you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 8, '"But I will let a few of my people escape destruction, and they will be scattered among the nations of the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 9, 'Then when they are exiled among the nations, they will remember me. They will recognize how grieved I am by their unfaithful hearts and lustful eyes that long for other gods. Then at last they will hate themselves for all their wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 10, 'They will know that I alone am the LORD and that I was serious when I predicted that all this would happen to them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 11, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Clap your hands in horror, and stamp your feet. Cry out, `Alas!'' because of all the evil that the people of Israel have done. Now they are going to die from war and famine and disease.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 12, 'Disease will strike down those who are far away in exile. War will destroy those who are nearby. And anyone who survives will be killed by famine. So at last I will spend my fury on them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 13, 'When their dead lie scattered among their idols and altars, on every hill and mountain and under every green tree and great oak where they offered incense to their gods, then they will know that I alone am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 6, 14, 'I will crush them and make their cities desolate from the wilderness in the south to Riblah in the north. Then they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 2, '"Son of man, this is what the Sovereign LORD says to Israel: The end is here! Wherever you look--east, west, north, or south--your land is finished.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 3, 'No hope remains, for I will unleash my anger against you. I will call you to account for all your disgusting behavior.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 4, 'I will turn my eyes away and show no pity, repaying you in full for all your evil. Then you will know that I am the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 5, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: With one blow after another I will bring total disaster!', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 6, 'The end has come! It has finally arrived! Your final doom is waiting!', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 7, 'O people of Israel, the day of your destruction is dawning. The time has come; the day of trouble is near. It will ring with shouts of anguish, not shouts of joy.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 8, 'Soon I will pour out my fury to complete your punishment for all your disgusting behavior.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 9, 'I will neither spare nor pity you. I will repay you for all your detestable practices. Then you will know that it is I, the LORD, who is striking the blow.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 10, '"The day of judgment is here; your destruction awaits! The people''s wickedness and pride have reached a climax.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 11, 'Their violence will fall back on them as punishment for their wickedness. None of these proud and wicked people will survive. All their wealth will be swept away.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 12, 'Yes, the time has come; the day is here! There is no reason for buyers to rejoice over the bargains they find or for sellers to grieve over their losses, for all of them will fall under my terrible anger.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 13, 'And if any merchants should survive, they will never return to their business. For what God has said applies to everyone--it will not be changed! Not one person whose life is twisted by sin will recover.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 14, '"The trumpets call Israel''s army to mobilize, but no one listens, for my fury is against them all.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 15, 'Any who leave the city walls will be killed by enemy swords. Those who stay inside will die of famine and disease.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 16, 'The few who survive and escape to the mountains will moan like doves, weeping for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 17, 'Everyone''s hands will be feeble; their knees will be as weak as water.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 18, 'They will dress themselves in sackcloth; horror and shame will cover them. They will shave their heads in sorrow and remorse.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 19, '"They will throw away their money, tossing it out like worthless trash. It won''t buy their deliverance in that day of the LORD''s anger. It will neither satisfy nor feed them, for their love of money made them stumble into sin.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 20, 'They were proud of their gold jewelry and used it to make vile and detestable idols. That is why I will make all their wealth disgusting to them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 21, 'I will give it as plunder to foreigners from the most wicked of nations, and they will defile it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 22, 'I will hide my eyes as these robbers invade my treasured land and corrupt it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 23, '"Prepare chains for my people, for the land is bloodied by terrible crimes. Jerusalem is filled with violence.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 24, 'I will bring the most ruthless of nations to occupy their homes. I will break down their proud fortresses and defile their sanctuaries.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 25, 'Terror and trembling will overcome my people. They will look for peace but will not find it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 26, 'Calamity will follow calamity; rumor will follow rumor. They will look in vain for a vision from the prophets. They will receive no teaching from the priests and no counsel from the leaders.', 'NLT'),
(30, 7, 27, 'The king and the prince will stand helpless, weeping in despair, and the people''s hands will tremble with fear. I will bring against them the evil they have done to others, and they will receive the punishment they so richly deserve. Then they will know that I am the LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 1, 'Then on September 17, during the sixth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, while the leaders of Judah were in my home, the Sovereign LORD took hold of me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 2, 'I saw a figure that appeared to be a man. From the waist down he looked like a burning flame. From the waist up he looked like gleaming amber.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 3, 'He put out what seemed to be a hand and took me by the hair. Then the Spirit lifted me up into the sky and transported me in a vision of God to Jerusalem. I was taken to the north gate of the inner courtyard of the Temple, where there is a large idol that has made the LORD very angry.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 4, 'Suddenly, the glory of the God of Israel was there, just as I had seen it before in the valley.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 5, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Son of man, look toward the north." So I looked, and there to the north, beside the entrance to the gate of the altar, stood the idol that had made the LORD so angry.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 6, '"Son of man," he said, "do you see what they are doing? Do you see the great sins the people of Israel are doing to drive me from my Temple? But come, and you will see even greater sins than these!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 7, 'Then he brought me to the door of the Temple courtyard, where I could see an opening in the wall.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 8, 'He said to me, "Now, son of man, dig into the wall." So I dug into the wall and uncovered a door to a hidden room.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 9, '"Go in," he said, "and see the unspeakable wickedness going on in there!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 10, 'So I went in and saw the walls engraved with all kinds of snakes, lizards, and hideous creatures. I also saw the various idols worshiped by the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 11, 'Seventy leaders of Israel were standing there with Jaazaniah son of Shaphan in the middle. Each of them held an incense burner, so there was a thick cloud of incense above their heads.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 12, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Son of man, have you seen what the leaders of Israel are doing with their idols in dark rooms? They are saying, `The LORD doesn''t see us; he has deserted our land!''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 13, 'Then he added, "Come, and I will show you greater sins than these!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 14, 'He brought me to the north gate of the LORD''s Temple, and some women were sitting there, weeping for the god Tammuz.', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 15, '"Have you seen this?" he asked. "But I will show you even greater sins than these!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 16, 'Then he brought me into the inner courtyard of the LORD''s Temple. At the entrance, between the foyer and the bronze altar, about twenty-five men were standing with their backs to the LORD''s Temple. They were facing eastward, worshiping the sun!', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 17, '"Have you seen this, son of man?" he asked. "Is it nothing to the people of Judah that they commit these terrible sins, leading the whole nation into violence, thumbing their noses at me, and rousing my fury against them?', 'NLT'),
(30, 8, 18, 'Therefore, I will deal with them in fury. I will neither pity nor spare them. And though they scream for mercy, I will not listen."', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 1, 'Then the LORD thundered, "Bring on the men appointed to punish the city! Tell them to bring their weapons with them!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 2, 'Six men soon appeared from the upper gate that faces north, each carrying a battle club in his hand. One of them was dressed in linen and carried a writer''s case strapped to his side. They all went into the Temple courtyard and stood beside the bronze altar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 3, 'Then the glory of the God of Israel rose up from between the cherubim, where it had rested, and moved to the entrance of the Temple. And the LORD called to the man dressed in linen who was carrying the writer''s case.', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 4, 'He said to him, "Walk through the streets of Jerusalem and put a mark on the foreheads of all those who weep and sigh because of the sins they see around them."', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 5, 'Then I heard the LORD say to the other men, "Follow him through the city and kill everyone whose forehead is not marked. Show no mercy; have no pity!', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 6, 'Kill them all--old and young, girls and women and little children. But do not touch anyone with the mark. Begin your task right here at the Temple." So they began by killing the seventy leaders.', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 7, '"Defile the Temple!" the LORD commanded. "Fill its courtyards with the bodies of those you kill! Go!" So they went throughout the city and did as they were told.', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 8, 'While they were carrying out their orders, I was all alone. I fell face down in the dust and cried out, "O Sovereign LORD! Will your fury against Jerusalem wipe out everyone left in Israel?"', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 9, 'Then he said to me, "The sins of the people of Israel and Judah are very great. The entire land is full of murder; the city is filled with injustice. They are saying, `The LORD doesn''t see it! The LORD has forsaken the land!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 10, 'So I will not spare them or have any pity on them. I will fully repay them for all they have done."', 'NLT'),
(30, 9, 11, 'Then the man in linen clothing, who carried the writer''s case, reported back and said, "I have finished the work you gave me to do."', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 1, 'As I looked, I saw what appeared to be a throne of blue sapphire above the crystal surface over the heads of the cherubim.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 2, 'Then the LORD spoke to the man in linen clothing and said, "Go in between the whirling wheels beneath the cherubim, and take a handful of glowing coals and scatter them over the city." He did this as I watched.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 3, 'The cherubim were standing at the south end of the Temple when the man went in, and the cloud of glory filled the inner courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 4, 'Then the glory of the LORD rose up from above the cherubim and went over to the door of the Temple. The Temple was filled with this cloud of glory, and the Temple courtyard glowed brightly with the glory of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 5, 'The moving wings of the cherubim sounded like the voice of God Almighty and could be heard clearly in the outer courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 6, 'The LORD said to the man in linen clothing, "Go between the cherubim and take some burning coals from between the wheels." So the man went in and stood beside one of the wheels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 7, 'Then one of the cherubim reached out his hand and took some live coals from the fire burning among them. He put the coals into the hands of the man in linen clothing, and the man took them and went out.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 8, '(All the cherubim had what looked like human hands hidden beneath their wings.)', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 9, 'Each of the four cherubim had a wheel beside him, and the wheels sparkled like chrysolite.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 10, 'All four wheels looked the same; each wheel had a second wheel turning crosswise within it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 11, 'The cherubim could move forward in any of the four directions they faced, without turning as they moved. They went straight in the direction in which their heads were turned, never turning aside.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 12, 'Both the cherubim and the wheels were covered with eyes. The cherubim had eyes all over their bodies, including their hands, their backs, and their wings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 13, 'I heard someone refer to the wheels as "the whirling wheels."', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 14, 'Each of the four cherubim had four faces--the first was the face of an ox, the second was a human face, the third was the face of a lion, and the fourth was the face of an eagle.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 15, 'Then the cherubim rose upward. These were the same living beings I had seen beside the Kebar River.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 16, 'When the cherubim moved, the wheels moved with them. When they rose into the air, the wheels stayed beside them, going with them as they flew.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 17, 'When the cherubim stood still, the wheels also stopped, for the spirit of the living beings was in the wheels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 18, 'Then the glory of the LORD moved from the door of the Temple and hovered above the cherubim.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 19, 'And as I watched, the cherubim flew with their wheels to the east gate of the LORD''s Temple. And the glory of the God of Israel hovered above them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 20, 'These were the same living beings I had seen beneath the God of Israel when I was by the Kebar River. I knew they were cherubim,', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 21, 'for each had four faces and four wings and what looked like human hands under their wings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 10, 22, 'Their faces, too, were just like the faces of the beings I had seen at the Kebar, and they traveled straight ahead, just as the others had.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 1, 'Then the Spirit lifted me and brought me over to the east gateway of the LORD''s Temple, where I saw twenty-five prominent men of the city. Among them were Jaazaniah son of Azzur and Pelatiah son of Benaiah, who were leaders among the people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 2, 'Then the Spirit said to me, "Son of man, these are the men who are responsible for the wicked counsel being given in this city.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 3, 'They say to the people, `Is it not a good time to build houses? Our city is like an iron pot. Inside it we will be like meat--safe from all harm. ''', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 4, 'Therefore, son of man, prophesy against them loudly and clearly."', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 5, 'Then the Spirit of the LORD came upon me, and he told me to say, "This is what the LORD says to the people of Israel: Is that what you are saying? Yes, I know it is, for I know every thought that comes into your minds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 6, 'You have murdered endlessly and filled your streets with the dead.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 7, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: This city is an iron pot, but the victims of your injustice are the pieces of meat. And you are not safe, for I will soon drag you from the city.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 8, 'I will expose you to the war you so greatly fear, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 9, 'I will drive you out of Jerusalem and hand you over to foreigners who will carry out my judgments against you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 10, 'You will be slaughtered all the way to the borders of Israel, and then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 11, 'No, this city will not be an iron pot for you, and you will not be the meat, safe inside. I will judge you even to the borders of Israel,', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 12, 'and you will know that I am the LORD. For you have refused to obey me; instead, you have copied the sins of the nations around you."', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 13, 'While I was still speaking, Pelatiah son of Benaiah suddenly died. Then I fell face down in the dust and cried out, "O Sovereign LORD, are you going to kill everyone in Israel?"', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 14, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 15, '"Son of man, the people still left in Jerusalem are talking about their relatives in exile, saying, `They are far away from the LORD, so now he has given their land to us!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 16, 'Therefore, give the exiles this message from the Sovereign LORD: Although I have scattered you in the countries of the world, I will be a sanctuary to you during your time in exile.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 17, 'I, the Sovereign LORD, will gather you back from the nations where you are scattered, and I will give you the land of Israel once again.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 18, '"When the people return to their homeland, they will remove every trace of their detestable idol worship.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 19, 'And I will give them singleness of heart and put a new spirit within them. I will take away their hearts of stone and give them tender hearts instead,', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 20, 'so they will obey my laws and regulations. Then they will truly be my people, and I will be their God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 21, 'But as for those who long for idols, I will repay them fully for their sins, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 22, 'Then the cherubim lifted their wings and rose into the air with their wheels beside them, and the glory of the God of Israel hovered above them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 23, 'Then the glory of the LORD went up from the city and stopped above the mountain to the east.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 24, 'Afterward the Spirit of God carried me back again to Babylonia, to the Judeans in exile there. And so ended the vision of my visit to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 11, 25, 'And I told the exiles everything the LORD had shown me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 1, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 2, '"Son of man, you live among rebels who could see the truth if they wanted to, but they don''t want to. They could hear me if they would listen, but they won''t listen because they are rebellious.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 3, 'So now put on a demonstration to show them what it will be like to go off into exile. Pack whatever you can carry on your back and leave your home to go on a journey. Make your preparations in broad daylight so the people can see you, for perhaps they will even yet consider what this means, even though they are such rebels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 4, 'Bring your baggage outside during the day so they can watch you. Then as they are watching, leave your house in the evening, just as captives do when they begin a long march to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 5, 'Dig a hole through the wall while they are watching and carry your possessions out through it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 6, 'As they watch, lift your pack to your shoulders and walk away into the night. Cover your face and don''t look around. All of these actions will be a sign for the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 7, 'So I did as I was told. In broad daylight I brought my pack outside, filled with the things I might carry into exile. Then in the evening while the people looked on, I dug through the wall with my hands and went out into the darkness with my pack on my shoulder.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 8, 'The next morning this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 9, '"Son of man, these rebels, the people of Israel, have asked you what all this means.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 10, 'Say to them, `This is what the Sovereign LORD says: These actions contain a message for Zedekiah in Jerusalem and for all the people of Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 11, 'Then explain that your actions are a demonstration of what will soon happen to them, for they will be driven from their homes and sent away into exile.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 12, '"Even Zedekiah will leave Jerusalem at night through a hole in the wall, taking only what he can carry with him. He will cover his face, and his eyes will never see his homeland again.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 13, 'Then I will spread out my net and capture him in my snare. I will bring him to Babylon, the land of the Babylonians, though he will never see it, and he will die there.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 14, 'I will scatter his servants and guards to the four winds and send the sword after them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 15, 'And when I scatter them among the nations, they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 16, 'But I will spare a few of them from death by war, famine, or disease, so they can confess to their captors about how wicked they have been. Then they will know that I am the LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 17, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 18, '"Son of man, tremble as you eat your food. Drink your water with fear, as if it were your last.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 19, 'Give the people this message from the Sovereign LORD concerning those living in Israel and Jerusalem: They will eat their food with trembling and sip their tiny portions of water in utter despair, because their land will be stripped bare on account of their violence.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 20, 'The cities will be destroyed and the farmland deserted. Then you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 21, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 22, '"Son of man, what is that proverb they quote in Israel: `Time passes, making a liar of every prophet''?', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 23, 'Give the people this message from the Sovereign LORD: I will put an end to this proverb, and you will soon stop quoting it. Now give them this new proverb to replace the old one: `The time has come for every prophecy to be fulfilled!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 24, '"Then you will see what becomes of all the false visions and misleading predictions about peace in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 25, 'For I am the LORD! What I threaten always happens. There will be no more delays, you rebels of Israel! I will fulfill my threat of destruction in your own lifetime, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 26, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 27, '"Son of man, the people of Israel are saying, `His visions won''t come true for a long, long time.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 12, 28, 'Therefore, give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: No more delay! I will now do everything I have threatened! I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 2, '"Son of man, speak against the false prophets of Israel who are inventing their own prophecies. Tell them to listen to the word of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 3, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Destruction is certain for the false prophets who are following their own imaginations and have seen nothing at all!', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 4, '"O people of Israel, these prophets of yours are like jackals digging around in the ruins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 5, 'They have done nothing to strengthen the breaks in the walls around the nation. They have not helped it to stand firm in battle on the day of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 6, 'Instead, they have lied and said, `My message is from the LORD,'' even though the LORD never sent them. And yet they expect him to fulfill their prophecies!', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 7, 'Can your visions be anything but false if you claim, `This message is from the LORD,'' when I have not even spoken to you?', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 8, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Because what you say is false and your visions are a lie, I will stand against you, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 9, 'I will raise my fist against all the lying prophets, and they will be banished from the community of Israel. I will blot their names from Israel''s record books, and they will never again see their own land. Then you will know that I am the Sovereign LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 10, '"These evil prophets deceive my people by saying, `All is peaceful!'' when there is no peace at all! It''s as if the people have built a flimsy wall, and these prophets are trying to hold it together by covering it with whitewash!', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 11, 'Tell these whitewashers that their wall will soon fall down. A heavy rainstorm will undermine it; great hailstones and mighty winds will knock it down.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 12, 'And when the wall falls, the people will cry out, `Where is the whitewash you applied?''', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 13, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will sweep away your whitewashed wall with a storm of indignation, with a great flood of anger, and with hailstones of fury.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 14, 'I will break down your wall right to the foundation, and when it falls, it will crush you. Then you will know that I am the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 15, 'At last my anger against the wall and those who covered it with whitewash will be satisfied. Then I will say to you: `The wall and those who whitewashed it are both gone.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 16, 'They were lying prophets who claimed peace would come to Jerusalem when there was no peace. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 17, '"Now, son of man, also speak out against the women who prophesy from their own imaginations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 18, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Destruction is certain for you women who are ensnaring the souls of my people, both young and old alike. You tie magic charms on their wrists and furnish them with magic veils. Do you think you can trap others without bringing destruction on yourselves?', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 19, 'You turn my people away from me for a few handfuls of barley or a piece of bread. By lying to my people who love to listen to lies, you kill those who should not die, and you promise life to those who should not live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 20, '"And so the Sovereign LORD says: I am against all your magic charms, which you use to ensnare my people like birds. I will tear them from your arms, setting my people free like birds set free from a cage.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 21, 'I will tear off the magic veils and save my people from your grasp. They will no longer be your victims. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 22, 'You have discouraged the righteous with your lies, when I didn''t want them to suffer grief. And you have encouraged the wicked by promising them life, even though they continue in their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 13, 23, 'But you will no longer talk of seeing visions that you never saw, nor will you practice your magic. For I will rescue my people from your grasp. Then you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 1, 'Then some of the leaders of Israel visited me, and while they were there,', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 2, 'this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 3, '"Son of man, these leaders have set up idols in their hearts. They have embraced things that lead them into sin. Why should I let them ask me anything?', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 4, 'Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: I, the LORD, will punish the people of Israel who set up idols in their hearts so they fall into sin and then come to a prophet asking for help.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 5, 'I will do this to capture the minds and hearts of all my people who have turned from me to worship their detestable idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 6, '"Therefore, give the people of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: Repent and turn away from your idols, and stop all your loathsome practices.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 7, 'I, the LORD, will punish all those, both Israelites and foreigners, who reject me and set up idols in their hearts so they fall into sin, and who then come to a prophet asking for my advice.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 8, 'I will turn against such people and make a terrible example of them, destroying them. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 9, 'And if a prophet is deceived and gives a message anyway, it is because I, the LORD, have deceived that prophet. I will stand against such prophets and cut them off from the community of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 10, 'False prophets and hypocrites--evil people who claim to want my advice--will all be punished for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 11, 'In this way, the people of Israel will learn not to stray from me, polluting themselves with sin. They will be my people, and I will be their God, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 12, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 13, '"Son of man, suppose the people of a country were to sin against me, and I lifted my fist to crush them, cutting off their food supply and sending a famine to destroy both people and animals alike.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 14, 'Even if Noah, Daniel, and Job were there, their righteousness would save no one but themselves, declares the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 15, '"Or suppose I were to send an invasion of dangerous wild animals to devastate the land and kill the people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 16, 'Even if these three men were there, the Sovereign LORD swears that it would do no good--it wouldn''t save the people from destruction. Those three alone would be saved, but the land would be devastated.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 17, '"Or suppose I were to bring war against the land, and I told enemy armies to come and destroy everything.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 18, 'Even if these three men were in the land, the Sovereign LORD swears that they could not save the people. They alone would be saved.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 19, '"Or suppose I were to pour out my fury by sending an epidemic of disease into the land, and the plague killed people and animals alike.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 20, 'Even if Noah, Daniel, and Job were living there, the Sovereign LORD swears that they could not save the people. They alone would be saved by their righteousness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 21, '"Now this is what the Sovereign LORD says: How terrible it will be when all four of these fearsome punishments fall upon Jerusalem--war, famine, beasts, and plague--destroying all her people and animals.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 22, 'Yet there will be survivors, and they will come here to join you as exiles in Babylon. You will see with your own eyes how wicked they are, and then you will feel better about what I have done to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 14, 23, 'When you meet them and see their behavior, you will agree that these things are not being done to Israel without cause, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 2, '"Son of man, how does a grapevine compare to a tree? Is a vine''s wood as useful as the wood of a tree?', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 3, 'Can its wood be used for making things, like pegs to hang up pots and pans?', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 4, 'No, it can only be used for fuel, and even as fuel, it burns too quickly.', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 5, 'Vine branches are useless both before and after being put into the fire!', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 6, '"And this is what the Sovereign LORD says: The people of Jerusalem are like grapevines growing among the trees of the forest. Since they are useless, I have set them aside to be burned!', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 7, 'And I will see to it that if they escape from one fire, they will fall into another. When this happens, you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 15, 8, 'And I will make the land desolate because my people have been unfaithful to me, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 1, 'Then another message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 2, '"Son of man, confront Jerusalem with her loathsome sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 3, 'Give her this message from the Sovereign LORD: You are nothing but a Canaanite! Your father was an Amorite and your mother a Hittite!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 4, 'When you were born, no one cared about you. Your umbilical cord was left uncut, and you were never washed, rubbed with salt, and dressed in warm clothing.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 5, 'No one had the slightest interest in you; no one pitied you or cared for you. On the day you were born, you were dumped in a field and left to die, unwanted.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 6, '"But I came by and saw you there, helplessly kicking about in your own blood. As you lay there, I said, `Live!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 7, 'And I helped you to thrive like a plant in the field. You grew up and became a beautiful jewel. Your breasts became full, and your hair grew, though you were still naked.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 8, 'And when I passed by and saw you again, you were old enough to be married. So I wrapped my cloak around you to cover your nakedness and declared my marriage vows. I made a covenant with you, says the Sovereign LORD, and you became mine.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 9, '"Then I bathed you and washed off your blood, and I rubbed fragrant oils into your skin.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 10, 'I gave you expensive clothing of linen and silk, beautifully embroidered, and sandals made of fine leather.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 11, 'I gave you lovely jewelry, bracelets, and beautiful necklaces,', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 12, 'a ring for your nose and earrings for your ears, and a lovely crown for your head.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 13, 'And so you were made beautiful with gold and silver. Your clothes were made of fine linen and were beautifully embroidered. You ate the finest foods--fine flour, honey, and olive oil--and became more beautiful than ever. You looked like a queen, and so you were!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 14, 'Your fame soon spread throughout the world on account of your beauty, because the splendor I bestowed on you perfected your beauty, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 15, '"But you thought you could get along without me, so you trusted instead in your fame and beauty. You gave yourself as a prostitute to every man who came along. Your beauty was theirs for the asking!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 16, 'You used the lovely things I gave you to make shrines for idols, where you carried out your acts of prostitution. Unbelievable! How could such a thing ever happen?', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 17, 'You took the very jewels and gold and silver ornaments I had given you and made statues of men and worshiped them, which is adultery against me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 18, 'You used the beautifully embroidered clothes I gave you to cover your idols. Then you used my oil and incense to worship them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 19, 'Imagine it! You set before them as a lovely sacrifice the fine flour and oil and honey I had given you, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 20, '"Then you took your sons and daughters--the children you had borne to me--and sacrificed them to your gods. Was it not enough that you should be a prostitute?', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 21, 'Must you also slaughter my children by sacrificing them to idols?', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 22, 'In all your years of adultery and loathsome sin, you have not once thought of the days long ago when you lay naked in a field, kicking about in your own blood.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 23, '"Your destruction is certain, says the Sovereign LORD. In addition to all your other wickedness,', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 24, 'you built a pagan shrine and put altars to idols in every town square.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 25, 'On every street corner you defiled your beauty, offering your body to every passerby in an endless stream of prostitution.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 26, 'Then you added lustful Egypt to your lovers, fanning the flames of my anger with your increasing promiscuity.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 27, 'That is why I struck you with my fist and reduced your boundaries. I handed you over to your enemies, the Philistines, and even they were shocked by your lewd conduct!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 28, 'You have prostituted yourselves with the Assyrians, too. It seems you can never find enough new lovers! And after your prostitution there, you still were not satisfied.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 29, 'You added to your lovers by embracing that great merchant land of Babylonia--but you still weren''t satisfied!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 30, '"What a sick heart you have, says the Sovereign LORD, to do such things as these, acting like a shameless prostitute.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 31, 'You build your pagan shrines on every street corner and your altars to idols in every square. You have been worse than a prostitute, so eager for sin that you have not even demanded payment for your love!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 32, 'Yes, you are an adulterous wife who takes in strangers instead of her own husband.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 33, 'Prostitutes charge for their services--but not you! You give gifts to your lovers, bribing them to come to you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 34, 'So you are the opposite of other prostitutes. No one pays you; instead, you pay them!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 35, '"Therefore, you prostitute, listen to this message from the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 36, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Because you have exposed yourself in prostitution to all your lovers, and because you have worshiped detestable idols, and because you have slaughtered your children as sacrifices to your gods,', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 37, 'this is what I am going to do. I will gather together all your allies--these lovers of yours with whom you have sinned, both those you loved and those you hated--and I will strip you naked in front of them so they can stare at you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 38, 'I will punish you for your murder and adultery. I will cover you with blood in my jealous fury.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 39, 'Then I will give you to your lovers--these many nations--and they will destroy you. They will knock down your pagan shrines and the altars to your idols. They will strip you and take your beautiful jewels, leaving you completely naked and ashamed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 40, 'They will band together in a mob to stone you and run you through with swords.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 41, 'They will burn your homes and punish you in front of many women. I will see to it that you stop your prostitution and end your payments to your many lovers.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 42, '"Then at last my fury against you will be spent, and my jealous anger will subside. I will be calm and will not be angry with you anymore.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 43, 'But first, because you have not remembered your youth but have angered me by doing all these evil things, I will fully repay you for all of your sins, says the Sovereign LORD. For to all your disgusting sins, you have added these lewd acts.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 44, 'Everyone who makes up proverbs will say of you, `Like mother, like daughter.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 45, 'For your mother loathed her husband and her children, and so do you. And you are exactly like your sisters, for they despised their husbands and their children. Truly your mother must have been a Hittite and your father an Amorite.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 46, '"Your older sister was Samaria, who lived with her daughters in the north. Your younger sister was Sodom, who lived with her daughters in the south.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 47, 'But you have not merely sinned as they did--no, that was nothing to you. In a very short time you far surpassed them!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 48, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, Sodom and her daughters were never as wicked as you and your daughters.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 49, 'Sodom''s sins were pride, laziness, and gluttony, while the poor and needy suffered outside her door.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 50, 'She was proud and did loathsome things, so I wiped her out, as you have seen.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 51, '"Even Samaria did not commit half your sins. You have done far more loathsome things than your sisters ever did. They seem righteous compared to you!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 52, 'You should be deeply ashamed because your sins are so terrible. In comparison, you make your sisters seem innocent!', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 53, '"But someday I will restore the fortunes of Sodom and Samaria, and I will restore you, too.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 54, 'Then you will be truly ashamed of everything you have done, for your sins make them feel good in comparison.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 55, 'Yes, your sisters, Sodom and Samaria, and all their people will be restored, and at that time you also will be restored.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 56, 'In your proud days you held Sodom in contempt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 57, 'But now your greater wickedness has been exposed to all the world, and you are the one who is scorned--by Edom and all her neighbors and by Philistia.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 58, 'This is your punishment for all your disgusting sins, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 59, '"Now this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will give you what you deserve, for you have taken your solemn vows lightly by breaking your covenant.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 60, 'Yet I will keep the covenant I made with you when you were young, and I will establish an everlasting covenant with you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 61, 'Then you will remember with shame all the evil you have done. I will make your sisters, Samaria and Sodom, to be your daughters, even though they are not part of our covenant.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 62, 'And I will reaffirm my covenant with you, and you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 16, 63, 'You will remember your sins and cover your mouth in silence and shame when I forgive you of all that you have done, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 2, '"Son of man, tell this story to the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 3, 'Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: A great eagle with broad wings full of many-colored feathers came to Lebanon. He took hold of the highest branch of a cedar tree', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 4, 'and plucked off its topmost shoot. Then he carried it away to a city filled with merchants, where he planted it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 5, '"Then he planted one of its seedlings in fertile ground beside a broad river, where it would grow as quickly as a willow tree.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 6, 'It took root there and grew into a low, spreading vine. Its branches turned up toward the eagle, and its roots grew down beneath it. It soon produced strong branches and luxuriant leaves.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 7, 'But then another great eagle with broad wings and full plumage came along. So the vine sent its roots and branches out toward him for water.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 8, 'The vine did this even though it was already planted in good soil and had plenty of water so it could grow into a splendid vine and produce rich leaves and luscious fruit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 9, '"So now the Sovereign LORD asks: Should I let this vine grow and prosper? No! I will pull it out, roots and all! I will cut off its fruit and let its leaves wither and die. I will pull it out easily enough--it won''t take a strong arm or a large army to do it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 10, 'Then when the vine is transplanted, will it thrive? No, it will wither away completely when the east wind blows against it. It will die in the same good soil where it had grown so well."', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 11, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 12, '"Say to these rebels of Israel: Don''t you understand the meaning of this riddle of the eagles? I will tell you, says the Sovereign LORD. The king of Babylon came to Jerusalem, took away her king and princes, and brought them to Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 13, 'He made a treaty with a member of the royal family and made him take an oath of loyalty. He also exiled Israel''s most influential leaders,', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 14, 'so Israel would not become strong again and revolt. Only by keeping her treaty with Babylon could Israel maintain her national identity.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 15, '"Nevertheless, this man of Israel''s royal family rebelled against Babylon, sending ambassadors to Egypt to request a great army and many horses. Can Israel break her sworn treaties like that and get away with it?', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 16, 'No! For as surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, the king of Israel will die in Babylon, the land of the king who put him in power and whose treaty he despised and broke.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 17, 'Pharaoh and all his mighty army will fail to help Israel when the king of Babylon lays siege to Jerusalem again and destroys the lives of many.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 18, 'For the king of Israel broke his treaty after swearing to obey; therefore, he will not escape.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 19, '"So this is what the Sovereign LORD says: As surely as I live, I will punish him for breaking my covenant and despising the solemn oath he made in my name.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 20, 'I will throw my net over him and capture him in my snare. I will bring him to Babylon and deal with him there for this treason against me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 21, 'And all the best warriors of Israel will be killed in battle, and those remaining in the city will be scattered to the four winds. Then you will know that I, the LORD, have spoken these words.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 22, '"And the Sovereign LORD says: I will take a tender shoot from the top of a tall cedar, and I will plant it on the top of Israel''s highest mountain.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 23, 'It will become a noble cedar, sending forth its branches and producing seed. Birds of every sort will nest in it, finding shelter beneath its branches.', 'NLT'),
(30, 17, 24, 'And all the trees will know that it is I, the LORD, who cuts down the tall tree and helps the short tree to grow tall. It is I who makes the green tree wither and gives new life to the dead tree. I, the LORD, have spoken! I will do what I have said."', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 1, 'Then another message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 2, '"Why do you quote this proverb in the land of Israel: `The parents have eaten sour grapes, but their children''s mouths pucker at the taste''?', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 3, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, you will not say this proverb anymore in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 4, 'For all people are mine to judge--both parents and children alike. And this is my rule: The person who sins will be the one who dies.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 5, '"Suppose a certain man is just and does what is lawful and right,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 6, 'and he has not feasted in the mountains before Israel''s idols or worshiped them. And suppose he does not commit adultery or have intercourse with a woman during her menstrual period.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 7, 'Suppose he is a merciful creditor, not keeping the items given in pledge by poor debtors, and does not rob the poor but instead gives food to the hungry and provides clothes for people in need.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 8, 'And suppose he grants loans without interest, stays away from injustice, is honest and fair when judging others,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 9, 'and faithfully obeys my laws and regulations. Anyone who does these things is just and will surely live, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 10, '"But suppose that man has a son who grows up to be a robber or murderer and refuses to do what is right.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 11, 'And suppose that son does all the evil things his father would never do--worships idols on the mountains, commits adultery,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 12, 'oppresses the poor and helpless, steals from debtors by refusing to let them redeem what they have given in pledge, worships idols and takes part in loathsome practices,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 13, 'and lends money at interest. Should such a sinful person live? No! He must die and must take full blame.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 14, '"But suppose that sinful son, in turn, has a son who sees his father''s wickedness but decides against that kind of life.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 15, 'Suppose this son refuses to worship idols on the mountains, does not commit adultery,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 16, 'and does not exploit the poor, but instead is fair to debtors and does not rob them. And suppose this son feeds the hungry, provides clothes for the needy,', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 17, 'helps the poor, does not lend money at interest, and obeys all my regulations and laws. Such a person will not die because of his father''s sins; he will surely live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 18, 'But the father will die for the many sins he committed--for being cruel and robbing close relatives, doing what was clearly wrong among his people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 19, '" `What?'' you ask. `Doesn''t the child pay for the parent''s sins?'' No! For if the child does what is right and keeps my laws, that child will surely live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 20, 'The one who sins is the one who dies. The child will not be punished for the parent''s sins, and the parent will not be punished for the child''s sins. Righteous people will be rewarded for their own goodness, and wicked people will be punished for their own wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 21, 'But if wicked people turn away from all their sins and begin to obey my laws and do what is just and right, they will surely live and not die.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 22, 'All their past sins will be forgotten, and they will live because of the righteous things they have done.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 23, '"Do you think, asks the Sovereign LORD, that I like to see wicked people die? Of course not! I only want them to turn from their wicked ways and live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 24, 'However, if righteous people turn to sinful ways and start acting like other sinners, should they be allowed to live? No, of course not! All their previous goodness will be forgotten, and they will die for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 25, '"Yet you say, `The Lord isn''t being just!'' Listen to me, O people of Israel. Am I the one who is unjust, or is it you?', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 26, 'When righteous people turn from being good and start doing sinful things, they will die for it. Yes, they will die because of their sinful deeds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 27, 'And if wicked people turn away from their wickedness, obey the law, and do what is just and right, they will save their lives.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 28, 'They will live, because after thinking it over, they decided to turn from their sins. Such people will not die.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 29, 'And yet the people of Israel keep saying, `The Lord is unjust!'' O people of Israel, it is you who are unjust, not I.', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 30, '"Therefore, I will judge each of you, O people of Israel, according to your actions, says the Sovereign LORD. Turn from your sins! Don''t let them destroy you!', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 31, 'Put all your rebellion behind you, and get for yourselves a new heart and a new spirit. For why should you die, O people of Israel?', 'NLT'),
(30, 18, 32, 'I don''t want you to die, says the Sovereign LORD. Turn back and live!', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 1, '"Sing this funeral song for the princes of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 2, '`What is your mother? A lioness among lions! She lay down among the young lions and reared her cubs.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 3, 'She raised one of her cubs to become a strong young lion. He learned to catch and devour prey, and he became a man-eater.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 4, 'Then the nations heard about him, and he was trapped in their pit. They led him away in chains to the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 5, '`When the mother lion saw that all her hopes for him were gone, she took another of her cubs and taught him to be a strong lion.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 6, 'He prowled among the other lions and became a leader among them. He learned to catch and devour prey, and he, too, became a man-eater.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 7, 'He demolished fortresses in nearby nations and destroyed their towns and cities. Their farms were desolated, and their crops were destroyed. Everyone in the land trembled in fear when they heard him roar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 8, 'Then the armies of the nations attacked him, surrounding him from every direction. They spread out their nets for him and captured him in their pit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 9, 'With hooks, they dragged him into a cage and brought him before the king of Babylon. They held him in captivity, so his voice could never again be heard on the mountains of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 10, '`Your mother was like a vine planted by the water''s edge. It had lush, green foliage because of the abundant water.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 11, 'Its branches became very strong, strong enough to be a ruler''s scepter. It soon became very tall, towering above all the others. It stood out because of its height and because of its many lush branches.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 12, 'But the vine was uprooted in fury and thrown down to the ground. The desert wind dried up its fruit and tore off its branches. Its stem was destroyed by fire.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 13, 'Now the vine is growing in the wilderness, where the ground is hard and dry.', 'NLT'),
(30, 19, 14, 'A fire has come from its branches and devoured its fruit. None of the remaining limbs is strong enough to be a ruler''s scepter.'' This is a funeral song, and it is now time for the funeral."', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 1, 'On August 14, during the seventh year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, some of the leaders of Israel came to request a message from the LORD. They sat down in front of me to wait for his reply.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 2, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 3, '"Son of man, give the leaders of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: How dare you come to ask for my help? As surely as I live, I will tell you nothing. This is the word of the Sovereign LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 4, '"Son of man, bring judgment against them and condemn them. Make them realize how loathsome the actions of their ancestors really were.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 5, 'Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: When I chose Israel and revealed myself to her in Egypt, I swore that I, the LORD, would be her God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 6, 'I promised that I would bring her and her descendants out of Egypt to a land I had discovered and explored for them--a good land, a land flowing with milk and honey, the best of all lands anywhere.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 7, 'Then I said to them, `Each of you, get rid of your idols. Do not defile yourselves with the Egyptian gods, for I am the LORD your God.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 8, '"But they rebelled against me and would not listen. They did not get rid of their idols or forsake the gods of Egypt. Then I threatened to pour out my fury on them to satisfy my anger while they were still in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 9, 'But I didn''t do it, for I acted to protect the honor of my name. That way the surrounding nations wouldn''t be able to laugh at Israel''s God, who had promised to deliver his people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 10, 'So I brought my people out of Egypt and led them into the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 11, 'There I gave them my laws so they could live by keeping them. Yes, all those who keep them will live!', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 12, 'And I gave them my Sabbath days of rest as a sign between them and me. It was to remind them that I, the LORD, had set them apart to be holy, making them my special people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 13, '"But the people of Israel rebelled against me, and they refused to obey my laws there in the wilderness. They wouldn''t obey my instructions even though obedience would have given them life. And they also violated my Sabbath days. So I threatened to pour out my fury on them, and I made plans to utterly consume them in the desert.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 14, 'But again I held back in order to protect the honor of my name. That way the nations who saw me lead my people out of Egypt wouldn''t be able to claim I destroyed them because I couldn''t take care of them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 15, 'But I swore to them in the wilderness that I would not bring them into the land I had given them, a land flowing with milk and honey, the most beautiful place on earth.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 16, 'I told them this because they had rejected my laws, ignored my will for them, and violated my Sabbath days. Their hearts were given to their idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 17, 'Nevertheless, I pitied them and held back from destroying them in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 18, '"Then I warned their children and told them not to follow in their parents'' footsteps, defiling themselves with their idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 19, '`I am the LORD your God,'' I told them. `Follow my laws, pay attention to my instructions,', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 20, 'and keep my Sabbath days holy, for they are a sign to remind you that I am the LORD your God.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 21, '"But their children, too, rebelled against me. They refused to keep my laws and follow my instructions, even though obeying them would have given them life. And they also violated my Sabbath days. So again I threatened to pour out my fury on them in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 22, 'Nevertheless, I withdrew my judgment against them to protect the honor of my name among the nations who had seen my power in bringing them out of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 23, 'But I took a solemn oath against them while they were in the wilderness. I vowed I would scatter them among all the nations', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 24, 'because they did not obey my laws. They scorned my instructions by violating my Sabbath days and longing for the idols of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 25, 'I gave them over to worthless customs and laws that would not lead to life.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 26, 'I let them pollute themselves with the very gifts I had given them, and I allowed them to give their firstborn children as offerings to their gods--so I might devastate them and show them that I alone am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 27, '"Therefore, son of man, give the people of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: Your ancestors continued to blaspheme and betray me,', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 28, 'for when I brought them into the land I had promised them, they offered sacrifices and incense on every high hill and under every green tree they saw! They roused my fury as they offered up sacrifices to their gods. They brought their perfumes and incense and poured out their drink offerings to them!', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 29, 'I said to them, `What is this high place where you are going?'' (This idol shrine has been called Bamah--`high place''--ever since.)', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 30, '"Therefore, give the people of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: Do you plan to pollute yourselves just as your ancestors did? Do you intend to keep prostituting yourselves by worshiping detestable idols?', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 31, 'For when you offer gifts to them and give your little children to be burned as sacrifices, you continue to pollute yourselves to this day. Should I listen to you or help you, O people of Israel? As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, I will not give you a message even though you have come to me requesting one.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 32, '"You say, `We want to be like the nations all around us, who serve idols of wood and stone.'' But what you have in mind will never happen.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 33, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, I will rule you with an iron fist in great anger and with awesome power.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 34, 'With might and fury I will bring you out from the lands where you are scattered.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 35, 'I will bring you into the wilderness of the nations, and there I will judge you face to face.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 36, 'I will judge you there just as I did your ancestors in the wilderness after bringing them out of Egypt, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 37, 'I will count you carefully and hold you to the terms of the covenant.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 38, 'I will purge you of all those who rebel and sin against me. I will bring them out of the countries where they are in exile, but they will never enter the land of Israel. And when that happens, you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 39, '"As for you, O people of Israel, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: If you insist, go right ahead and worship your idols, but then don''t turn around and bring gifts to me. Such desecration of my holy name must stop!', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 40, 'For on my holy mountain, says the Sovereign LORD, the people of Israel will someday worship me, and I will accept them. There I will require that you bring me all your offerings and choice gifts and sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 41, 'When I bring you home from exile, you will be as pleasing to me as an offering of perfumed incense. And I will display my holiness in you as all the nations watch.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 42, 'Then when I have brought you home to the land I promised your ancestors, you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 43, 'You will look back at all your sins and hate yourselves because of the evil you have done.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 44, 'You will know that I am the LORD, O people of Israel, when I have honored my name by treating you mercifully in spite of your wickedness, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 45, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 46, '"Son of man, look toward the south and speak out against it; prophesy against the fields of the Negev.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 47, 'Give the southern wilderness this message from the Sovereign LORD: Hear the word of the LORD! I will set you on fire, O forest, and every tree will be burned--green and dry trees alike. The terrible flames will not be quenched; they will scorch everything from south to north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 48, 'And all the world will see that I, the LORD, have set this fire. It will not be put out."', 'NLT'),
(30, 20, 49, 'Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, they are saying of me, `He only talks in riddles!''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 2, '"Son of man, look toward Jerusalem and prophesy against Israel and her sanctuaries.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 3, 'Give her this message from the LORD: I am your enemy, O Israel, and I am about to unsheath my sword to destroy your people--the righteous and the wicked alike.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 4, 'Yes, I will not spare even the righteous! I will make a clean sweep throughout the land from south to north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 5, 'All the world will know that I am the LORD. My sword is in my hand, and it will not return to its sheath until its work is finished.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 6, '"Son of man, groan before the people! Groan before them with bitter anguish and a broken heart.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 7, 'When they ask you why, tell them, `I groan because of the terrifying news I have heard. When it comes true, the boldest heart will melt with fear; all strength will disappear. Every spirit will faint; strong knees will tremble and become as weak as water. And the Sovereign LORD says: It is coming! It''s on its way!''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 8, 'Then the LORD said to me,', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 9, '"Son of man, give the people this message from the LORD: A sword is being sharpened and polished.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 10, 'It is being prepared for terrible slaughter; it will flash like lightning! Now will you laugh? Those far stronger than you have fallen beneath its power!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 11, 'Yes, the sword is now being sharpened and polished; it is being prepared for the executioner!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 12, '"Son of man, cry out and wail; pound your thighs in anguish, for that sword will slaughter my people and their leaders--everyone will die!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 13, 'It will put them all to the test! So now the Sovereign LORD asks: What chance do they have?', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 14, '"Son of man, prophesy to them and clap your hands vigorously. Then take the sword and brandish it twice, even three times, to symbolize the great massacre they will face!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 15, 'Let their hearts melt with terror, for the sword glitters at every gate. It flashes like lightning; it is polished for slaughter!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 16, 'O sword, slash to the right, and slash to the left, wherever you will, wherever you want.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 17, 'I, too, will clap my hands, and I will satisfy my fury. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 18, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 19, '"Son of man, make a map and trace two routes on it for the sword of Babylon''s king to follow. Put a signpost on the road that comes out of Babylon where the road forks into two--', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 20, 'one road going to Ammon and its capital, Rabbah, and the other to Judah and fortified Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 21, 'The king of Babylon now stands at the fork, uncertain whether to attack Jerusalem or Rabbah. He will call his magicians to use divination. They will cast lots by shaking arrows from the quiver. They will inspect the livers of their animal sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 22, 'Then they will decide to turn toward Jerusalem! With battering rams they will go against the gates, shouting for the kill. They will put up siege towers and build ramps against the walls to reach the top.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 23, 'The people of Jerusalem will think it is a mistake, because of their treaty with the Babylonians. But the king of Babylon will remind the people of their rebellion. Then he will attack and capture them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 24, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Again and again your guilt cries out against you, for you are not ashamed of your sin. You don''t even try to hide it! Wherever you go, whatever you do, all your actions are filled with sin. So now the time of your punishment has come!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 25, '"O you corrupt and wicked prince of Israel, your final day of reckoning is here!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 26, 'Take off your jeweled crown, says the Sovereign LORD. The old order changes--now the lowly are exalted, and the mighty are brought low.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 27, 'Destruction! Destruction! I will surely destroy the kingdom. And it will not be restored until the one appears who has the right to judge it. Then I will hand it over to him.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 28, '"And now, son of man, prophesy concerning the Ammonites and their mockery. Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: My sword is drawn for your slaughter; it is sharpened to destroy, flashing like lightning!', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 29, 'Your magicians and false prophets have given false visions and told lies about the sword. And now it will fall with even greater force on the wicked for whom the day of final reckoning has come.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 30, 'Should I return my sword to its sheath before I deal with you? No, I will destroy you in your own country, the land of your birth.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 31, 'I will pour out my fury on you and blow on you with the fire of my anger. I will hand you over to cruel men who are skilled in destruction.', 'NLT'),
(30, 21, 32, 'You are fuel for the fire, and your blood will be spilled in your own land. You will be utterly wiped out, your memory lost to history. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 1, 'Now this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 2, '"Son of man, are you ready to judge Jerusalem? Are you ready to judge this city of murderers? Denounce her terrible deeds in public,', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 3, 'and give her this message from the Sovereign LORD: O city of murderers, doomed and damned--city of idols, filthy and foul--', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 4, 'you are guilty of both murder and idolatry. Your day of destruction has come! You have reached the end of your years. I will make you an object of mockery throughout the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 5, 'O infamous city, filled with confusion, you will be mocked by people both far and near.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 6, '"Every leader in Israel who lives within your walls is bent on murder.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 7, 'Fathers and mothers are contemptuously ignored. Resident foreigners are forced to pay for protection. Orphans and widows are wronged and oppressed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 8, 'Inside your walls you despise my holy things and violate my Sabbath days of rest.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 9, 'People accuse others falsely and send them to their death. You are filled with idol worshipers and people who take part in lewd activities.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 10, 'Men sleep with their fathers'' wives and have intercourse with women who are menstruating.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 11, 'Within your walls live men who commit adultery with their neighbors'' wives, who defile their daughters-in-law or who rape their own sisters.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 12, 'There are hired murderers, loan racketeers, and extortioners everywhere! They never even think of me and my commands, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 13, '"But now I clap my hands in indignation over your dishonest gain and bloodshed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 14, 'How strong and courageous will you be in my day of reckoning? I, the LORD, have spoken! I will do what I have said.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 15, 'I will scatter you among the nations and purge you of your wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 16, 'And when you have been dishonored among the nations, you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 17, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 18, '"Son of man, the people of Israel are the worthless slag that remains after silver is smelted. They are the dross that is left over--a useless mixture of copper, tin, iron, and lead.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 19, 'So give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: Because you are all worthless slag, I will bring you to my crucible in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 20, 'I will melt you down in the heat of my fury, just as copper, tin, iron, and lead are melted down in a furnace.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 21, 'I will gather you together and blow the fire of my anger upon you,', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 22, 'and you will melt like silver in fierce heat. Then you will know that I, the LORD, have poured out my fury on you."', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 23, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT');
